<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Backs Smart Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG declared Monday  
that production of the mini Smart car would continue, dismissing as 
``speculation'' a weekly newsmagazine report that the model could 
be cancelled unless sales improved. 
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel in its Monday edition said that DaimlerChrysler  
co-chairman and co-CEO Juergen Schrempp had given the Smart unit 
``six months at the most'' to improve sales or he would cut off 
investment in the project. 
</P>
<P>
	A DaimlerChrysler spokesman on Monday said the company had no  
plans to stop production, noting that orders had been rising. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the magazine, Schrempp told managers he would  
``turn off the money tap'' on the cartoonish, two-seater car if 
sales did not increase substantially this year. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler has invested $1.1 billion in developing the  
Smart model, which is built in Hambach, France. 
</P>
<P>
	The company already has changed management of the Smart unit,  
lowered prices and launched a sweeping ad campaign to improve 
sales, the magazine said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
