<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Arafat to Israelis: 'Elect Peace' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had a simple  
message today for Israelis heading to the polls: ``Elect peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Short in words, the message was long in meaning: a carefully  
couched appeal to vote for Labor's moderate candidate, Ehud Barak. 
</P>
<P>
	In public statements, Palestinian leaders have tried to remain  
neutral in Israel's race for the premiership. But behind the 
scenes, most hoped the tenure of Prime Minister Benjamin 
Netanyahu's hard-line government was coming to an end. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Arafat was being updated throughout the day on the  
voting and expected that he would watch the televised results 
tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by reporters as he entered his seaside Gaza office today  
what message he had for the Israelis on their big day, Arafat said 
simply, ``To elect peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Israelis stood in long lines at polling stations across the  
country, Palestinians went about their daily lives but were barred 
from entering Israel until midnight, after the voting was over. 
</P>
<P>
	In the divided West Bank town of Hebron, restaurant owner Khalil  
Natshe said he would turn on his TV to watch exit polls later 
tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	An editorial in the daily Al Quds newspaper said today's  
elections test Israel's desire to achieve reconciliation with the 
Palestinians and Arab world at large. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today poses a true opportunity for the Israelis to prove to  
what degree they ... want a better future for the next 
generation,'' the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Israelis should know now, more than at any time before, the  
connection between progress in the peace process and internal 
Israeli issues such as economics and security,'' Al Quds wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Al Ayyam newspaper, editor-in-chief and Arafat adviser  
Akram Hanyieh wrote that Israelis will be faced with a choice 
between a return to confrontations espoused by Netanyahu or for a 
path which dares to raise the slogan ``money for education not for 
settlements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Netanyahu government's expansion of Jewish settlements as  
the election neared has angered Palestinians. The latest example 
came on the eve of the voting when work resumed at the 
controversial Har Homa housing project in east Jerusalem, where 
Palestinians wish to establish the capital of an independent state. 
</P>
<P>
	Salah Tamari, a Palestinian legislator, said the decision to  
build at the site known in Arabic as Jabal Abu Ghaneim was ``a 
desperate attempt by Netanyahu to get some last minute votes from 
extremists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ground-breaking at Har Homa in March 1997 touched off riots and  
froze peace negotiations. Building of housing itself only began 
Sunday with the work halted again today by the national election 
holiday. Tamari said he was not hopeful that even a new Barak-led 
government could stop it now. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians want Israel's next prime minister to bring about  
the swift resumption of the peace process, which would lead to 
further Israeli withdrawals from the West Bank and negotiations on 
a final peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of the Barak promises to revitalize the peace process,  
Hanyieh cautioned Arab and world leaders to wait and see what Barak 
does. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next prime minister has a hard test ahead of him -- to  
prove his ability in peace making, and no one can in full 
confidence bet on his success in that test,'' Hanyieh wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
