<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tomko Shines in Reds' Rotation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Brett Tomko and manager Jack McKeon see  
eye-to-eye on one thing: The Cincinnati Reds need their most 
promising young pitcher in the rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, there's little they agree on.  
</P>
<P>
	Tomko made a triumphant return from the minor leagues on Sunday,  
allowing only four hits in 8 2-3 innings of a 3-0 victory over the 
San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	That was one of the most encouraging developments of a two-week  
homestand for the Reds, who aren't going to get out of their 
season-long rut until they get some consistency out of their 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	With Denny Neagle still slow to come around from a weak  
shoulder, Steve Avery sidelined by a blister and Jason Bere 
struggling, the Reds have to have Tomko at his best. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need him,'' McKeon said, summing it up in three words.  
</P>
<P>
	Informed of McKeon's comment, Tomko smiled.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's nice to know,'' he said. ``When you get sent down,  
there's a lot of thoughts that go through your mind. You find out 
who's really behind you and who's not. A lot of things happen. A 
lot of people said things that didn't sit too well with me. So 
that's nice to hear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The relationship between manager and pitcher was strained in  
spring training last year, when Tomko missed a start because of a 
tender shoulder. McKeon thought his young pitcher was being too 
soft. 
</P>
<P>
	They had another go-round this season after Tomko went 0-1 with  
a 7.76 ERA in five starts. McKeon and pitching coach Don Gullett 
urged Tomko to pitch inside more and felt that he resisted. 
</P>
<P>
	When Tomko was sent to Triple-A on April 29, the Reds  
characterized it as a wake-up call. Tomko was brought back when 
Avery came down with a blister and he responded with the best start 
of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, it was clear that the 26-year-old pitcher and the  
68-year-old manager are still on different wavelengths. McKeon said 
Tomko had done so well because he followed advice and changed how 
he pitched; Tomko insisted he'd done no such thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was doing the things he did last year,'' McKeon said. ``He  
was pitching inside. That's all (Gullett) talked about all year, 
using the inside half of the plate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko's take on it?  
</P>
<P>
	``Honestly, I didn't try to pitch any different than when I was  
up here before,'' Tomko said. ``It's just that I had command of my 
fastball and could move the ball around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was never not trying to throw inside. I think that was a  
good blame, a point to say, 'He's not doing this.' And that was not 
the point at all. The fact that I had trouble throwing the 
fastball, period, was the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The question now is whether the sometimes strained relationship  
between manager and pitcher will turn into a problem. The Reds 
can't afford to have Tomko drift off again. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko developed into the Reds' most promising young pitcher in  
1997, when he went 11-7 with a 3.43 ERA in 22 games as a rookie. He 
followed with a 13-12 record and 4.44 ERA in 34 starts last season, 
his fourth in pro ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The demotion in April and the Reds' explanation for it shocked  
Tomko, who had started the season opener because of injuries to 
Denny Neagle and Pete Harnisch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first night was pretty rough,'' Tomko said. ``I had a  
whole gamut of emotions going, thoughts like, 'Am I not good 
enough? What are they thinking?''' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, it appears the demotion had the intended effect. Asked  
if Tomko needed it in order to get turned around, McKeon said, ``I 
don't know. He'd probably say no. But he hadn't pitched like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only start where he pitched like the Tomko we know.  
He's very fortunate that Avery came up with that blister.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko will agree with McKeon on one other thing: The trip to the  
minors made an impact on him. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn to appreciate what you have up here,'' he said.  
``It's a jungle down there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
