<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Hopes for WTO, but Has Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's foreign trade minister said Monday that  
China hopes to join the World Trade Organization by year's end but 
that there are limits to the concessions it can offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The minister, Shi Guangsheng, told visiting Australian Deputy  
Prime Minister Tim Fischer that Beijing remained committed to 
getting into the WTO, the official Xinhua News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Shi acknowledged the commitment made by trade ministers from the  
United States, Japan, Canada and the European Union last week to 
see China in the Geneva-based WTO this year, but suggested that 
concessions from Beijing are limited. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to tell them that there is an ultimate limitation  
on what China can offer,'' Xinhua quoted Shi as saying. ``We will 
never go beyond that limitation in making our commitment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shi was the highest ranking Chinese official to speak on the  
subject since NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia 
on May 7. The bombing, which the alliance said was an accident, 
probably strengthened the hand of anti-Western hard-liners in the 
leadership and came at a critical time in China's 13-year effort to 
join world trade's leading rule-making body. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the bombing, senior officials had criticized the  
broad market-opening offer Premier Zhu Rongji made in Washington 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``China will never sacrifice its own fundamental interests to  
join the WTO,'' Shi was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
