<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 14:51:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Telecom Deal Draws Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- France Telecom is seeking several billion dollars  
in damages from Deutsche Telekom, saying the German company's 
planned merger with Telecom Italia violates previous pacts between 
the French and German telecoms operators. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal action announced Monday marks a deepening of the split  
between the German and French companies, which are linked by 
several joint ventures and cooperative agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	France Telecom chairman Michel Bon has warned since Deutsche  
Telekom and Telecom Italia announced plans to merge that such a 
deal could damage the Deutsche Telekom-France Telecom partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	``The merger plan between Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia,  
without the slightest discussion with France Telecom, seriously 
damages the trust between the (French and German) partners,'' 
France Telecom said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The exact amount of the damages sought will be specified during  
the course of the court proceedings, the French company said. 
</P>
<P>
	France Telecom said it had filed its complaint against Deutsche  
Telekom in the International Court of Arbitration of the 
International Chamber of Commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom have reciprocal two percent  
shareholdings, and together with Sprint Corp. of the United States, 
they own the Global One joint venture. They also hold minority 
stakes in the Italian telephone company Wind. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Deutsche Telekom, who declined to be named, said  
the merger wasn't designed to work against the company's partners. 
``We just hope to see the problem resolved in a more sensible and 
professional manner,'' the spokesman said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
