<HEADLINE> Maryland Wins Lacrosse Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Jen Adams had four goals and one assist to lead  
the top-seeded Maryland Terrapins to a 16-6 win over the Virginia 
Cavaliers Sunday in the NCAA women's lacrosse championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight different Terps (21-0) scored. Kristin Sommar added three  
goals and three assists while Quinn Carney scored two goals and 
five assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Alex Kahoe made 18 saves.  
</P>
<P>
	The win was Maryland's fifth straight title and third straight  
undefeated season. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland set several NCAA championship records in the game: 11  
goals in a half, 16 total goals and largest margin of victory at 
10. 
</P>
<P>
	``This win was all about Maryland's conviction and belief that  
this could happen,'' said coach Cindy Timchall. ``We just want to 
relish this victory today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Virginia (15-6), Samm Taylor scored three goals and Liz  
McCarthy made nine save in 40 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are definitely disappointed with our overall performance,''  
said coach Julie Myers. ``They are always at their best in the 
finals. They don't miss a beat.'' 
</P>
