<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Disapproval of Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans lag well behind Democrats on top  
priority issues such as Social Security and education, and swing 
voters disapprove of the Congress by double-digit margins, 
according to a recent GOP survey. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the survey taken for the Republican National  
Committee reported strong public support for a GOP proposal for a 
``lockbox'' to safeguard surplus funds in the Social Security 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	A Republican call to allow workers to invest a portion of their  
payroll taxes individually also has strong backing -- so much so 
that pollster Fred Steeper suggested it might be one way to 
``counter the popularity of increasing the minimum wage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was conducted April 23-25 by Market Strategies, Inc.  
The results were distributed to party leaders and lawmakers in both 
the House and Senate. A total of 800 registered voters was polled, 
with a margin of error of 3.5 percent. A copy was obtained by The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was taken at a pivotal time for GOP leaders, with  
Republicans in both houses of Congress struggling to implement an 
agenda and fend off politically popular Democratic initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	One finding struck GOP leaders in particular: a majority of  
those polled said the nation had gotten off on the wrong track. The 
finding came in the wake of the continuing air strikes over Kosovo 
and a few days after the deadly high school shootings in Littleton, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, 55 percent of those polled disapproved of the way the  
Republican Congress is handling its job. Thirty-eight percent 
approved. The breakdown among so-called swing voters was nearly 
identical -- 38 per cent in favor and 53 percent opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked which party's candidate they would vote for, 43 percent of  
those polled said the Democrat, and 39 percent responded the 
Republican. That is half the deficit found in two separate polls 
conducted during last winter's impeachment trial of President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	On the issues that voters said they care most about, Social  
Security and education, the poll found a decided Democratic 
advantage, as has been the case in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The voters' current issue agenda favors the Democrats,''  
Steeper wrote in a summary of his findings that some Republicans 
received. Republicans hold the advantage on tax simplification and 
tax cuts, but they ``rank well behind education and Social 
Security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were encouraged to confront both issues directly.  
</P>
<P>
	``Making social security and education offensive issues, rather  
than relegating them to defensive issues, may be what the 
Republican Party must ultimately do in order to build on its gains 
achieved in 1994,'' Steeper wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey showed voters prefer Democrats, 49-28, on Social  
Security, and 48-33 on education. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP enjoyed advantages among voters for upholding  
traditional moral values; controlling government spending and 
holding down taxes, but these counted for less than Social Security 
and education. 
</P>
<P>
	Steeper also warned Republicans that opposition to a plan for  
prescription drug coverage for Medicare ``could be a political 
disaster. ... Even 42 percent of the Conservative Republican Base 
favors the Democratic position,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what step would do the most good in the wake of killings  
at the Columbine High School in Colorado, 58 percent said they 
preferred mandatory jail time for those who commit a crime with a 
gun. Thirty-three percent chose ``greater restrictions on the sale 
of guns.'' The Senate has been battling over gun control in recent 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	On minimum wage, the poll found that given a choice, 60 percent  
of those surveyed favored individual retirement accounts to help 
working people, and 38 percent favored an increase in the minimum 
wage. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans have signaled a willingness to bring a minimum  
wage bill to the floor this year, although they are consulting with 
business interests to see what provisions they would like included. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, however, a more conventional struggle is possible  
with opponents trying to derail the increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
