<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 59.85 to 10,853.47 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices closed mixed on Wall Street today as  
traders cautiously placed some last-minute bets before Tuesday's 
meeting of the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	At 4 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 59.85 at 10,853.47. The index had fallen as much as 167 points 
earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, which were lower for most of the day,  
closed mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index and the Nasdaq 
composite index were higher, but declining issues outdistanced 
advancers on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of the day, traders extended Friday's broad selloff, in  
which the Dow fell 193.87 to 10,913.32, responding to a 
steeper-than-expected increase in the consumer price index that fed 
worries about rising inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The report prompted speculation that the Fed will at least  
consider an interest rate hike when its Open Market Committee meets 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Many cautious traders appeared willing to wait on the sidelines  
today, as volume was well behind Friday's pace. But others were 
willing to take a chance on some stocks as the market fell and 
prices were more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a strange day and a half in the market,''  
said Charles White, portfolio manager at Avatar Associates. ``It's 
hard to convince people to put money to work in front of word from 
the Fed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts attributed today's rebound to growing sentiment  
that the Fed will leave rates untouched, instead announcing a 
``tightening bias,'' which would indicate that the group may raise 
rates at a future meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed tightens rates when central bankers believe the economy  
is growing too fast. Higher interest rates raise corporate 
borrowing rates, which can often hurt profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The lingering concern over interest rates hammered banking and  
financial stocks for a second straight session. Rising rates are a 
particular threat to banks as companies become more reluctant to 
take out loans. Citigroup, a component of the Dow, fell today. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of inflation has rattled the bond market in recent  
sessions, pushing yields to their highest levels in nearly a year. 
Today, prices bounced back slightly, lowering the yield of the 
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond to 5.90 percent from 5.92 percent 
last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the buying came from traders looking ahead to the next  
batch of corporate earnings reports. Dell Computer, which typically 
sets the standard for computer makers, rose in advance of its 
earnings announcement, scheduled for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Big mergers influenced trading in individual stocks today. After  
former Baby Bell U S West and telecommunications company Global 
Crossing announced they would merge, the stocks of both companies 
fell as investors appeared uncertain of the benefits to be gained. 
</P>
<P>
	Wyman Gordon was the biggest percentage gainer on the Big Board  
after Precision Castparts Corp. agreed to acquire it for about $721 
million. And Gulfstream Aerospace got a big boost from its intended 
merger with defense giant General Dynamics. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
