<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Goalie Meeting Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- They are two of hockey's best goalies, The  
Dominator and Dafoe. One has been at the top for a while. The other 
is headed there. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's Byron Dafoe has been outstanding in the Bruins' playoff  
series with Buffalo in which Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek is the 
marquee netminder. 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe's strong play helped Boston win Game 5 on Sunday, 5-3, and  
forced a Game 6 in Buffalo on Tuesday night. Hasek, the NHL's 
two-time defending MVP, allowed four goals on 26 shots before being 
benched after two periods. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely think Byron has outplayed him this series,'' said  
Rob Tallas, who played just 17 regular-season games and none in the 
playoffs as Dafoe's backup. ``Whatever might happen in this series 
happens, but Byron walks away with his head high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe got a well-deserved day off Monday while his teammates  
practiced. One day earlier, he made one of his most important saves 
of the season with Boston leading 4-3 in Game 5. With 1:46 left, he 
stopped Geoff Sanderson's slap shot that would have tied the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's made unbelievable saves all series,'' Bruins defenseman  
Hal Gill said Monday. ``You don't want to rely on him too much, but 
he's been there every time we needed him. It's real comforting to 
have him back there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe, 28, is in his fourth full NHL season and second with the  
Bruins. He led the league with 10 regular-season shutouts, was 
second in save percentage and third with a 1.99 goals against 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, 34, was first in save percentage and second with nine  
shutouts and a 1.87 goals against average. He also is one of three 
MVP candidates and, with Dafoe and Toronto's Curtis Joseph, one of 
three candidates for the Vezina Trophy that goes to the NHL's best 
goalie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hasek will be there for now and maybe next year,'' Bruins  
coach Pat Burns said, ``but, Byron, give him some time. He's 
proving it day to day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hasek, seven, eight years ago, couldn't be the backup in  
Chicago, so you have to give a guy some time, and I think Byron is 
biding his time and playing well and getting people noticing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek played a total of 25 games for Chicago in 1990-91 and  
1991-92 before moving to Buffalo where he became the No. 1 goalie 
in 1993-94. 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe played a total of 10 games with Washington over three  
seasons, then was traded to Los Angeles where he played in 47 games 
in 1995-96. Last season, he had a 2.24 goals against average and 
six shutouts with Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	After five games of the best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal,  
Buffalo has a 14-12 advantage in goals and leads 3-2 in games. 
</P>
<P>
	In the playoffs, Hasek has allowed 16 goals in nine games, while  
Dafoe has permitted 23 goals in 11 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``His personal goal is probably to compete with Hasek,'' Bruins  
defenseman Kyle McLaren said, ``and Hasek's been one of the top 
goalies in the league for a couple of years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any goalie in the league wants to compare themselves to the  
best and Byron's done that. I think he's excelled at that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players on both sides insist that one player doesn't win a game  
-- even if that player is one of the league's top goalies. 
</P>
<P>
	But both goalies can have a major impact on the outcome.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's so prepared every night. He's so consistent,'' Tallas  
said of Dafoe. ``I think he's outplayed Hasek every game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
