<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Barak Wins Israeli Election  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Ehud Barak, a former general who promised to  
resume Mideast peace talks, today unseated Benjamin Netanyahu, the 
tough-talking prime minister who slowed the negotiations and froze 
Israel's budding ties with the Arab world. A tearful Netanyahu 
conceded defeat just half an hour after exit polls projected Barak 
winning by a wide margin, and said he also would step down as 
leader of the Likud Party. With 6.46 percent of the vote counted, 
Barak led by 60.1 percent to 39.7 percent for Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton Calls To Congratulate Barak  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton pledged his support today to  
Ehud Barak, Israel's new prime minister-elect. The administration 
also renewed its call for an Israeli pullback on the West Bank and 
rapid talks with the Palestinians on Jerusalem and statehood. 
Clinton spoke by telephone with both Barak and the current prime 
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu. The administration had maintained an 
outwardly neutral stance during the Israeli campaign. But it is 
likely to find the incoming prime minister more amenable to the 
U.S. land-for-peace formula for the peace process. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Support Slipping for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' support for the air war over  
Kosovo, still backed by a majority, is slipping, and more than half 
favor negotiations to settle the conflict, reveals a poll released 
today. A majority, 59 percent, support the air war, and just over 
half, 52 percent, would support ground troops as a way to end the 
conflict, according to an ABC-Washington Post poll. But support for 
the air war has slipped 9 percentage points since early April and 
support for ground troops to end the conflict dropped 5 percentage 
points in that time. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Ground Invasion Unlikely  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO has all but abandoned the idea of  
mounting a ground invasion to expel Serb troops from Kosovo, 
convinced that air power alone can succeed. The allies still are 
discussing the role of ground troops in Kosovo but only as 
peacekeepers, officials said today. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said 
a ``total and irreversible'' Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo 
would have to be under way before an international security force 
with NATO at its core would be sent in. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Issues Major Welfare Decision  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today banned states from  
paying lower benefits to newcomers than to longtime residents. In 
other decisions today, the court ruled that police do not need a 
warrant to seize someone's car from a public place under laws 
requiring forfeiture of property linked to crime. The court also 
made it harder for federal judges to invalidate election districts 
drawn by state legislatures just because they suspect race was the 
major factor. 

</P>
<P>
	Teamsters OK Car Haulers Strike  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Teamsters union truck drivers voted  
overwhelmingly today to authorize a strike against any or all of 17 
trucking companies that haul new cars and trucks to dealers 
nationwide. Automakers were already preparing for the threat of a 
Teamsters strike once the truckers' contract expires May 31. A 
walkout could dash hopes for what's shaping up to be a record year 
for U.S. sales of cars and light trucks. 

</P>
<P>
	CVS Buys Online Pharmacy Soma.com  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Combining a virtual drug store with its  
real-world counterpart, pharmacy chain CVS Corp. announced today it 
is buying online drug retailer Soma.com for $30 million. The move 
accelerates CVS' fledgling effort to sell drugs over the Internet, 
a concept that experts predict could take off the way Amazon.com 
has transformed the book selling business. CVS has 4,122 stores, 
more than any other pharmacy chain. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 59.85  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed today. The Dow Jones  
industrial average fell 59.85 to close at 10,853.47. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 1,999-1,046. The Nasdaq composite index rose 
33.98 to 2,561.84. 

</P>
<P>
	Olympic Whistle-Blower Reemerges  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The man who blew the whistle on Olympic  
bribery is back at the scene of the scandal. Marc Hodler, the 
senior member of the International Olympic Committee, returned to 
Salt Lake City for meetings of the coordination commission he heads 
for the 2002 Winter Games, an event the Swiss lawyer helped forever 
link with corruption. Last December, Hodler was the first Olympic 
official to say the million-dollar program of scholarships, travel, 
medical care and cash run by Salt Lake bidders was purely and 
simply a scheme to buy IOC members' votes. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
