<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 05:57:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest White House Tree Enters Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Evergreen and graceful, the tree has survived  
the branch-whipping blast of countless helicopters, stubborn 
starlings, a suicide airplane and 17 decades of presidential 
history. Andrew Jackson would be proud. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a stately Southern tree, a Magnolia grandiflora with  
glossy dark-green leaves, supported in its old age by a web of 
steel wires and a 30-foot-tall, telescopic iron pole sunk seven 
feet into the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the oldest tree on the White House grounds, so rooted in  
the history of the place that it appears on the back of older $20 
bills, rising to the roofline just about where Jackson and his 
gardeners planted it to the left of the long-columned South Portico 
facing the Potomac. 
</P>
<P>
	When the magnolia blooms in late June or early July it produces  
creamy and fragrant white blossoms, eight to nine inches across. 
</P>
<P>
	White House lore, passed on through a long line of presidential  
gardeners, cherishes the Jackson magnolia as the rough-hewn, 
battle-winning, whip-tongued president's tribute to his gardening 
wife, Rachel Donelson Jackson, who died before he reached 
Washington in 1829. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a touch of irony in that. After a campaign in which she  
and her husband had been accused of adultery, bigamy and other 
offenses, Rachel Jackson was not looking forward to moving to the 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would rather be a doorkeeper in the house of God than live  
in that palace in Washington,'' she had cried. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin Williams, who began working at the White House a  
half-century ago and is now chief gardener, says the Jackson 
magnolia ``creates an atmosphere, a structure of something living'' 
as it reaches up to screen the private family quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	There's a reasonable chance the venerable magnolia will live  
well into the next century, even with a hollow center and evident 
signs of decay on its lower limbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping for another 50 years myself,'' Williams said.  
``These old trees, they look bad on the surface, but on the inside 
they're determined to keep going. Like anything old, it wants to 
stay alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing everything we can to keep it as healthy as  
possible,'' Williams said. ``It's declined some. But not a whole 
lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a way that's a bit surprising. The Jackson magnolia is north  
of its usual range. Harsh winters are a worry. But the White House 
wall at the tree's back shelters it from the worst winter storms, a 
factor Williams said was critical when it was newly planted. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four presidents have lived at the White House since  
Jackson and his magnolia has been there with all of them. Reporters 
turn their backs against the prop blast when the presidential 
helicopter takes off and lands, and they watch the magnolia shake 
and shiver. 
</P>
<P>
	When the White House interior was rebuilt in the 1950s,  
Jackson's tree was moved carefully to safety, then returned. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 12, 1995, a pilot, apparently bent on suicide, aimed a  
stolen Cessna 150 at the White House. Falling just short, the plane 
cut a groove in the South Lawn and barked against the magnolia's 
trunk. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still a scar on the tree,'' Williams said.  
</P>
<P>
	Persistent birds are a more common problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``The tree is a haven in winter for the starlings; flocks of  
hundreds and hundreds of them,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	The starlings are noisy, and not very considerate. ``They  
plaster the patio with droppings,'' the gardener said. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams placed a rubber owl and rubber snakes in the magnolia's  
high branches to scare them off. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crows took to sitting on top of the rubber owl and it  
didn't bother the starlings either,'' he said. ``They were not 
scared. They still come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trees and the White House have always been linked. ``Trees  
should be planted at once so as to make it an agreeable place to 
walk in,'' a government official said in 1800. 
</P>
<P>
	An American elm, believed to have been planted in John Adams'  
time, hung on until 1991. First lady Barbara Bush replaced it with 
a young tree propagated from the old one. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 500-plus trees on the 18-acre White House grounds, more  
than 40 are commemoratives, including a scarlet oak planted by 
Benjamin Harrison in 1889 and a Japanese Threadleaf maple planted 
by first lady Frances Folsom Cleveland in 1893. Bill and Hillary 
Clinton have planted eight, including white dogwoods and a 
littleleaf linden. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``The White House Garden,'' published in 1996 by the White  
House Historical Association, William Seale calls the presidents' 
trees ``an unsung glory'' that help express ``the continuity of 
this place through time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Generations of trees have been planted, grown and died,''  
Seale writes. ``New generations always replace them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the Jackson magnolia is the exception.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
