<HEADLINE> European Farm Firm Buys US Farm Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RACINE, Wis. (AP) -- European farm equipment maker New Holland  
N.V. will acquire Case Corp. for about $4.3 billion, creating a 
powerful rival to Deere &AMP; Co. in the slumping big-ticket farm 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Case shareholders will receive $55 per  
share in cash from New Holland, a Dutch company with operations in 
England and Italy, the companies said today. 
</P>
<P>
	New Holland's Italian parent company, Fiat, would retain a 71  
percent controlling interest in the new venture. Fiat now owns 69 
percent of New Holland. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company's chairman and chief executive officer will  
be Jean-Pierre Rosso, chairman and CEO of Case. Umberto Quadrino, 
New Holland's CEO, would serve as the board's co-chairman during a 
transition period, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger must be approved by Case shareholders and by U.S. and  
European regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are creating a new company with an extraordinary range of  
products and services that will meet the needs of more customers 
around the world than any other equipment company,'' Rosso said. 
</P>
<P>
	New Holland has a strong foothold in Europe, while Case, based  
in Racine, Wis., is more established in the United States, Latin 
America, Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. Also, Case 
focuses on larger-horsepower tractors and combines for big farms, 
while New Holland is stronger in light equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Case's stock price began rising last week as takeover  
speculation hit the market. Case posted a $48 million loss in its 
first quarter, and is carrying out plans to idle 3,400 workers by 
the end of this year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
