<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TRW To Sell 4 Automotive Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Inc., fresh from its acquisition of  
LucasVarity PLC, plans to sell four automotive businesses to reduce 
its debt from the deal -- a move that could affect 21,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Debt reduction is an immediate priority for TRW,'' chairman  
and CEO Joseph Gorman said in a statement. ``Exiting these 
businesses will contribute significantly to the timely achievement 
of that goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TRW, which makes products for the automobile, aerospace and  
information technology industries, wants to sell TRW Engine 
Components, Lucas Diesel Systems operations, TRW Nelson Stud 
Welding and the LucasVarity Wiring companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman said TRW will now concentrate its automotive business on  
steering, suspension and antilock brake systems, along with safety 
restraints such as seat belts, steering wheels and air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that he's had unsolicited inquiries about the companies  
and is optimistic they can be sold by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Michael Schmall said he wasn't surprised by the move.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little cleaning of the house,'' said Schmall, managing  
partner of The Planning Edge, a Troy, Mich., automotive industry 
analysis and consulting firm, 
</P>
<P>
	``TRW's making sure they're focused on what they want to do long  
term and obviously it's nice to get a little cash after spending 
that much money'' on LucasVarity, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW's $7 billion acquisition of LucasVarity, the British auto  
parts maker, closed May 10. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, TRW took an $85.3 million charge for buying  
LucasVarity, reducing its first-quarter earnings to a net loss of 
$28.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman said the sale of the companies should raise $1.2 billion  
to $1.5 billion. TRW wants to reduce its debt by approximately $2.5 
billion in the next year and a half, including profits from the 
sale. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW stock closed down 68 3/4 cents, at $46.43 3/4, on the New York  
Stock Exchange Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW Engine Components produces more than 300 million engine  
valves annually. It has about 6,000 employees and operates in 12 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas Diesel Systems, employing 9,200 people, is one of the  
world's largest manufacturers of diesel fuel injection systems, 
serving the car, van, truck, bus, agricultural, industrial and 
marine industries. It supplies fuel injection systems to more than 
one-third of Europe's diesel car and van market. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW Nelson Stud Welding, which makes stud welding fasteners and  
equipment, employs about 400 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lucas Wiring businesses are the leading supplier of  
electrical wiring systems in the United Kingdom. The businesses 
employ 5,500 people and have operations in the United Kingdom, 
Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Egypt and Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	Including the businesses that TRW is selling, the company has  
about 130,000 employees worldwide. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
