<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Group Won't Censor Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Canada's national broadcast regulator said Monday  
it won't try to regulate new media services on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after almost a year of hearings by the  
Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our message is clear: The CRTC will not regulate the Internet,  
nothing on the Internet,'' said commission chairwoman Francoise 
Bertrand. ``The Canadian new media industry is vibrant, highly 
competitive and successful without regulation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the hearings, the commission heard from an array of  
broadcasters and telecommunications companies, free-speech 
advocates and Internet service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of interveners told the commission it should  
avoid regulating the relatively new Internet industry, fearing the 
commission might cramp its growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
