<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Wants To End Racial Profiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich brought his campaign for  
the Republican presidential nomination home today, telling a civil 
rights group that police should never detain people simply because 
of their race. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, said the  
practice known as ``racial profiling'' should stop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is an insidious action that has gone on in too many  
parts of America,'' Kasich said at a news conference before 
delivering a speech at the Columbus Urban League's annual awards 
luncheon. ``Those kinds of actions that divide this country have to 
be ended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department has been investigating complaints by  
blacks and Hispanics that they are more likely to be targeted by 
police and customs inspectors for traffic stops and searches. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, also a Republican,  
recently acknowledged that state troopers treated blacks and 
Hispanics more aggressively than whites during traffic stops on the 
New Jersey Turnpike. Similar accusations have been made in Florida, 
Maryland, Connecticut and elsewhere along the Interstate 95 
corridor. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton called for an end to the practice during a  
radio speech in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``It almost gets to be a matter of guilty until proven innocent  
and that's just not the way America should be,'' Kasich said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ohio congressman said he is against racial quotas being  
forced on employers, but supports aggressive recruiting of people 
of all backgrounds by the business world. 
</P>
<P>
	``Affirmative action should not be an effort to treat us like so  
many beans and should be an effort to unify this country,'' he 
said. ``I don't think people in America see the value in quotas 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich has formed an exploratory committee looking into a run  
for the Republican presidential nomination and has been campaigning 
in New Hampshire, Iowa and California. He drew 1 percent support 
among Republicans in a national CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll released 
early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
