<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Country Living Guide for City Folks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- City folk who move to the country for  
fresh air and peace and quiet are getting a pamphlet to enlighten 
them on the way things really are in rural Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The pamphlet, called the ``Code of the West,'' was published in  
response to complaints received by the Spokane County Commission 
about the less than attractive aspects of the countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you choose to live among the farms and ranches of our rural  
countryside, do not expect county government to intervene in the 
day-to-day operations of your agribusiness neighbors,'' the 
pamphlet counsels. 
</P>
<P>
	The pamphlet cautions that:  
</P>
<P>
	--Farmers often work around the clock during harvest, meaning  
extra noise and dust. 
</P>
<P>
	--Animals can be dangerous, and they sometimes smell.  
</P>
<P>
	--Hunting is allowed in most rural areas.  
</P>
<P>
	--Fences may not always be an accurate indication of a property  
line. 
</P>
<P>
	--Response times by emergency crews can be extremely slow.  
</P>
<P>
	Janet Thorson, president of the Green Bluff Growers Association  
north of Spokane, said many of her neighbors do not farm, so there 
is potential for conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to know they're not moving into a totally pristine  
area where nothing commercial happens,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
