<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Tries To Get Past Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- They used to be the very, very VIPs in  
these parts, wined and dined, taken to ski condos and courtside 
seats at NBA games. 
</P>
<P>
	Those days are long gone for International Olympic Committee  
members visiting Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	When the oversight task force for the 2002 Winter Games opens  
four days of meetings today, it will be the first time a large 
group of IOC leaders has come to the Utah capital since the Olympic 
bribery scandal broke last November. 
</P>
<P>
	And this time, instead of lavish hospitality, the members will  
be greeted by a packed agenda of important meetings and a single 
night on the town -- a dinner at the home of Mitt Romney, the 
venture capitalist brought in three months ago to run Salt Lake's 
sullied Olympic organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah Jazz might have played host to the Sacramento Kings on  
Sunday in a do-or-die playoff game, but if the IOC wanted tickets 
it had to deal with scalpers. 
</P>
<P>
	This fourth meeting of the IOC's coordination commission long  
has been on the books, but its timing could not have been better 
for Salt Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	When they sit down with Romney and his lieutenants, the task  
force members, led by corruption-case whistleblower Marc Hodler of 
Switzerland, will face some dark and dismal facts -- but also be 
shown some definite rays of light breaking through the clouds of 
the six-month-old scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Romney announced three sponsorship and supplier  
contracts with Utah companies worth some $25 million-$30 million, 
the first big deals signed since well before the bribery case 
broke. 
</P>
<P>
	And on Saturday night, Salt Lake turned out for its first  
Olympic celebration in a long time -- the unveiling of a snowshoe 
rabbit, a coyote and a black bear as the game's mascots and 
merchandising keys. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 15,000 people jammed an amphitheater for the ceremony,  
billed as ``Putting a new face on the Games,'' and scooped up 
hundreds of mascot T-shirts and pins, on sale for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd also watched a clock in the shape of an Indian  
arrowhead start to count down the 1,000 days remaining until the 
opening ceremony on Feb. 8, 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not looking back,'' Romney said. ``It sort of starts  
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all the news is good.  
</P>
<P>
	Romney still needs $300 million to fill his sponsorship revenue  
and has $84 million in budget cuts on the table that could affect 
athletes, spectators and volunteers -- even the IOC itself. 
</P>
<P>
	But after months of doom and gloom, the SLOC staff seems upbeat.  
The mood was casual and fun-loving at Saturday night's festivities, 
with Romney casually strolling the grounds in chinos and a winter 
vest, produced by one of the new sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The mascots were chosen because of their historic links to the  
original settlers of the Wasatch range. The story goes that each 
played a part in making this region of snowy mountains and salty 
lakes a good place to live. 
</P>
<P>
	They also were picked because of their appeal to modern  
consumers. Focus groups told SLOC that these three critters would 
sell. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're buying things, that helps, too,'' Romney told the  
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC estimates the mascots will account for the core of $40  
million-$50 million in merchandise sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal, the worst in Olympic history, has resulted in a  
purge of 10 IOC members, the creation of panels that could 
drastically redo the committee and at least six investigations, 
including ones by the Justice Department and the Utah attorney 
general's office that won't report their findings for weeks or 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The coordination commission will discuss finances,  
transportation, ticket sales, media operations and dozens of other 
areas involved in staging a modern Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	It will visit sports venues, most of which are ready for use,  
and get a feel of how Salt Lake has emerged from the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The experience was a bruising one for all of us,'' Utah Gov.  
Mike Leavitt said. ``But we're healing and have come to understand 
that, as uncomfortable as it was, we're still intact physically and 
we will rise to the occasion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our redemption lies in a successful games.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
