<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugees Said Blocked  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Diplomatic efforts to resolve the  
nearly 2-month-old conflict moved into higher gear today, and NATO 
accused Serb authorities anew of using ethnic Albanians as human 
shields. In what U.N. officials and NATO said was a worrying 
development, Serb forces today barred hundreds of ethnic Albanians 
who arrived at the Macedonian border in a packed train from leaving 
the province. The development came as a U.N. delegation was in 
Belgrade, preparing to make the first trip to Kosovo by 
international authorities since some 790,000 ethnic Albanians were 
driven out of the southern Serb province beginning March 24, when 
NATO launched airstrikes against Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	New Jordanian King Visits U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- King Abdullah of Jordan began a week of talks  
here by pledging to ``stand side by side'' with peace-minded 
Israelis and Palestinians. ``The core issue is the 
Palestinian-Israeli peace process,'' Abdullah said, reviving the 
traditional Arab slogan that if the conflict with the Jewish state 
were resolved other problems in the region would be more easily 
addressed. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who met with the 
king, openly encouraged Abdullah to seek additional American 
economic assistance. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Expected To Win in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Labor Party candidate Ehud Barak, a peace  
process moderate, is heavily favored today to unseat Prime Minister 
Benjamin Netanyahu in general elections. Last-minute polls showed 
Barak widening his lead over the Likud Party's Netanyahu. ``I feel 
that the Israeli people want to see a new way of governing,'' Barak 
said today while greeting supporters. ``The people want to see 
change, unity and hope.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Aussie Charged in Attempted Spying  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former Australian government intelligence  
official was charged today with attempted espionage for selling 
U.S. defense secrets to an undercover FBI agent posing as a foreign 
spy, law enforcement officials said. The officials said the 
Australian, Jean-Philippe Wispelaere, 28, obtained $120,000 from 
undercover FBI agents in exchange for more than 713 classified U.S. 
documents. He worked for the Australian Defence Intelligence 
Organization from July 1998 to January 1999. 

</P>
<P>
	Makah Indians Harpoon Gray Whale  
</P>
<P>
	NEAH BAY, Wash. (AP) -- For the first time in more than 70 years,  
Makah Indians seeking to re-establish their whale-hunting tradition 
harpooned and apparently killed a gray whale this morning off 
Washington's Olympic Peninsula. The whaling crew in a traditional, 
hand-carved cedar canoe struck the whale and motorized support 
boats moved in with guns and fired at least two shots to try to 
kill it. Gray whales were removed from the endangered species list 
in 1994, and the tribe moved to renew hunts guaranteed under an 
1855 treaty despite protests in anti-whaling circles. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Discounting Bestsellers  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Online retailer Amazon.com sees a demand for  
best-selling books in cyber circles and is offering 50 percent 
discounts on them. The lists of those books available based on the 
New York Times bestseller list and covering both hardcover and 
paperback titles, will be updated weekly, the company says. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientists Speed Up 'Evolution'  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- In a revolution in evolution that Charles Darwin  
never dreamed of, biotechnology companies are conducting high-speed 
evolution in test tubes to create everything from super laundry 
detergents to novel drugs. Called directed evolution, the process 
could prove one of the most important steps in biotechnology since 
genetic engineering. The idea is to discover in nature substances 
that perform in a certain way but have drawbacks -- like a 
cancer-fighting protein that can only be used in small doses 
because of side effects -- and force them to rapidly evolve to be 
better. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 132  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 132.87 at 10,780.45. NYSE decliners outnumbered 
advancers 2,096-822. The Nasdaq was down 14.35 at 2,513.51. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Charged With Assault on Jockey  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The man who stood on the track as horses raced  
past him on the day of the Preakness Stakes was charged today with 
assaulting a jockey. Lee Ferrell also was charged with trespassing, 
reckless endangerment, disorderly conduct, resisting arrest and 
alcohol-related offenses. The 22-year-old man punched jockey Jorge 
Chavez at Pimlico Race Course on Saturday, an assault that has been 
shown repeatedly on television. He was released from detention 
yesterday after posting bond. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  

</P>
</TEXT>
