<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Vs. Western Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against major Western currencies  
today as U.S. stocks and bonds fell on fears of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the Japanese yen, however, as investors  
expected wider interest rate gaps between U.S. and Japanese bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0665 in late trading in New York, up  
from $1.0654 late Friday. The dollar was quoted at 1.5030 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.5059, and 1.4593 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.4640. The British pound was unchanged at $1.6184. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose, meanwhile, to 123.49 Japanese yen from 122.73  
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were worried that the Federal Reserve's Open Markets  
Committee was considering raising interest rates following a report 
Friday that showed consumer prices jumping in April by the largest 
amount in nearly nine years. Higher rates would make borrowing 
harder and could cause corporate profits to slump. 
</P>
<P>
	The FOMC meets for two days starting Tuesday. While analysts  
didn't expect a change during this meeting, investors suspected the 
Fed would move toward raising rates in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign exchange investors took their cues from stocks and  
bonds, selling off U.S. Treasurys with maturities of 10 years or 
less and plunging the Dow Jones industrial average as low as 167 
points before it recovered to close at 10,853.47, down 59.85. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, we're mirroring the stock market,'' said John  
McCarthy, a senior vice president for foreign exchange at ING 
Barings Capital Markets. ``That's helping the euro (and other 
currencies) rise against the dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Asian trading, investors ran up the dollar to a two-month  
high against the yen on expectations of widening gaps between U.S. 
and Japanese bond yields following Friday's price report. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on a benchmark Japanese 10-year government bond was  
1.230 Monday, while the yield on the U.S. Treasury 10-year bond was 
hovering at 5.640 percent, underpinning the dollar's vigor against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Treasury Secretary-designate Lawrence Summers added to the  
dollar's strength by reiterating the position of outgoing Treasury 
Secretary Robert Rubin at a world trade conference Sunday, that a 
strong dollar is in the best interests of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the euro countries are no longer traded separately  
and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8339 German marks, down from 1.8359; 6.1501 French francs, down 
from 6.1576; and 1,814.88 Italian lire, down from 1,818.18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
