<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foxes Killed To Protect Rare Bird </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Endangered foxes are being killed on San  
Clemente Island because they prey on an even rarer species of bird. 
</P>
<P>
	The federally protected San Clemente Island loggerhead shrike is  
one of the rarest birds in North America, with only 13 of these 
birds known to exist in the wild. 
</P>
<P>
	But the small bird with a long tail and white belly is also food  
for a small island fox protected under the California Endangered 
Species Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Navy, which owns San Clemente Island and uses it for  
weapons research and as a communications center for ships and 
aircraft, is spending $2.3 million this year trying to save the 
shrike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy has long controlled the rats, cats and birds that also  
feed on the shrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, experts had experimented with special collars that  
shocked the foxes when they approached trees where shrikes live. 
But that experiment was unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, for the first time, scientists killed 15 out of the  
650 to 700 foxes on the island and shipped eight others to zoos. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy decided to kill up to 50 foxes a year using a ``two  
strikes'' rule. Foxes that cross the shock collar's electrical 
barrier more than once are to be killed. For now, the program is on 
hold while scientists decide whether more foxes need to be 
eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are we going to have to keep making choices?'' asked David  
Garcelon, a wildlife biologist working with the Navy to protect the 
shrike. ``Do we like the ones that are furry? The ones with the 
pretty feathers?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though federal and state officials say they are torn over the  
decision, ``it's the lesser of two evils,'' said Susan Cochrane, 
chief of habitat conservation planning for the state Department of 
Fish and Game. 
</P>
<P>
	More foxes may be killed later this spring when shrike  
fledglings emerge from their nests and are most vulnerable. Or, 
scientists may trap foxes found within the shrikes' nesting area 
and release them after the young birds mature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
