<DOCNO> APW19990517.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 07:41:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Jordanian King Visits U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Israel voted, choosing what kind of leader  
and approach to take in Mideast negotiations, King Abdullah of 
Jordan began a week of talks here by pledging to ``stand side by 
side'' with peace-minded Israelis and Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	``The core issue is the Palestinian-Israeli peace process,''  
Abdullah said, reviving the traditional Arab slogan that if the 
conflict with the Jewish state were resolved other problems in the 
region would be more easily addressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who met with the king  
over breakfast at the State Department, openly encouraged Abdullah 
to seek additional American economic assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the Clinton administration was encouraging trade and  
investment in the Arab kingdom and was providing wheat to help 
overcome a drought. Albright also said friendship with the monarchy 
was being affirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	What Albright would not talk about was the Israeli election, in  
which Ehud Barak, the candidate of the Labor party and its allies, 
is poised to unseat Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who is far 
more skeptical about relinquishing territory to the Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Albright said ``we continue to be dedicated to the Wye  
process,'' referring to the land-for-security agreement reached 
last October by Israel and the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	In the U.S.-mediated accords, Netanyahu agreed to give up  
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in exchange for promises by 
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to root out terrorism in areas 
already under his control. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu halted the pullback after yielding 2 percent, saying  
Arafat had not done enough to assure Israel's security. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan has been at peace with Israel for five years, and for  
many more years unofficially before the late King Hussein came to 
terms. Abdullah is eager to see the Jewish state make 
accommodations to the Palestinians and Syria, both of which have 
made territorial claims on Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan's economic condition was at least as much a topic on the  
king's visit as the Arab-Israeli dispute. Peace with Israel has not 
produced the economic miracle to pull the Arab kingdom out of the 
doldrums, and the Clinton administration has its checkbook ready. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton is urging Japan, Germany, France and other  
creditor nations to cancel or postpone payment of Jordan's debts to 
help the new king cope with the faltering economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah arrived at the State Department with a screeching  
police motorcycle escort and will be treated with special deference 
by the administration, partly in tribute to his father, partly to 
promote Arab friendship. 
</P>
<P>
	The king is due also to meet with Clinton at the White House  
Tuesday and hold talks with Cabinet officers and members of 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The king is staying at Blair House, the presidential guest house  
across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House, as well as at a 
Georgetown hotel. Ceremony and lavish dinners are being arranged 
for his first visit as king. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Abdullah succeeded to the Jordanian throne after Hussein's  
death three months ago, he has shown coolness toward Netanyahu and 
reached out to Syria for better relations. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old king told reporters two weeks ago in Amman that  
Israel's leaders could have peace with the Arabs in one month if 
they wanted it. ``The ball is in Israel's court,'' Abdullah said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton already has forgiven Jordan's $700 million debt to the  
United States and is providing $200 million in yearly assistance. 
On top of that, he has asked Congress for an additional $100 
million this year with $200 million to follow over the next two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Indyk, the assistant secretary of state for the Near  
East, told reporters before Abdullah's arrival Friday from Canada 
that Clinton was asking other nations to forgive or defer Jordan's 
debts, as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jordan is a critical ally in the region and a key part of the  
peace process,'' Indyk said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
