<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Clarify Speedy Trial Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court agreed Monday to clarify the  
speedy-trial rights of people who are charged with a crime in one 
state while serving prison time in another state. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will consider New York prosecutors' bid to  
reinstate a man's convictions of second-degree murder and robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's highest court had voided Michael Hill's convictions  
and ordered the charges against him dismissed, saying prosecutors 
failed to bring him to trial within 180 days as required by the 
Interstate Agreement on Detainers. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, adopted in 1957, gives defendants a right to a  
speedy trial even if they are imprisoned in another state. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill was being held at the Lorain Correctional Institution in  
Grafton, Ohio, in 1993 when New York authorities filed notice that 
he was wanted for murder and robbery in the shooting death of 
Michael Weeks in the Rochester suburb of Gates on New Year's Eve 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill invoked the speedy-trial provisions of the interstate  
agreement. Later, pretrial maneuvering by Hill's lawyers put the 
deadline on hold for about seven months. 
</P>
<P>
	But the clock was running in January 1995 when prosecution and  
defense lawyers met to set a trial date. The prosecutor noted a May 
1 trial date had been discussed, and when asked by the judge, 
Hill's lawyer said, ``That will be fine, your honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The following April, Hill's lawyers sought dismissal of the  
charges on grounds that prosecutors had failed to bring him to 
trial within 180 days. A judge refused, and Hill was convicted and 
sentenced to 25 years to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	An appeals court upheld the conviction, but the New York Court  
of Appeals ordered the charges dismissed. His lawyer's agreement to 
the trial date did not waive Hill's speedy-trial protection because 
he did not make an ``affirmative request'' for a trial date beyond 
the 180-day deadline, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Monroe County prosecutors said the  
deadline should not turn on ``hypertechnical semantics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is New York vs. Hill, 98-1299.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
