<DOCNO> APW19990517.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:39:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Death Penalty Biased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The system for administering the death penalty  
in the United States is fraught with racial prejudice that leads a 
disproportionate number of minorities to face capital punishment, 
Amnesty International USA said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Amnesty used the findings of a study of capital punishment in  
America to urge abolition of the death penalty because it said 
discrimination pervades the system at every level. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the report, 81 percent of the 500 prisoners  
executed between 1977 and 1998 were convicted of murdering a white 
person, although blacks and whites are victims of homicide in 
almost equal numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 133 federal death penalty prosecutions authorized by the  
attorney general since 1988, 101 of the defendants have been 
members of minority groups. 
</P>
<P>
	A black person killing a white person also is 11 times more  
likely to face a death sentence than the killer in the opposite 
scenario, Amnesty reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, whether those charged with crimes in the U.S. live or  
die appears to be largely determined by the color of their skin and 
the race of their victim,'' said William Schulz, Amnesty USA's 
executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has leveled similar charges in the past, faulting the  
nation's law enforcement authorities for ignoring the situation. In 
a letter to Amnesty, the office of Attorney General Janet Reno said 
it supports the death penalty in appropriate cases but added: ``We 
are unalterably opposed to its application in an unfair manner, 
particularly if that unfairness is grounded in racial or other 
discrimination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report chronicled the levels at which racial bias can  
infiltrate the system, from the local district attorneys who decide 
whether to seek the death penalty to the jurors who hear the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The group cited a 1998 study by the Death Penalty Information  
Center that found blacks in Philadelphia are almost four times as 
likely to be sentenced to death as others convicted of similar 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	In other situations, prosecutors have sought to keep blacks out  
of the jury box, according to Amnesty. The report cites the case of 
Albert Jefferson, a black man convicted of murdering a white in 
Alabama. The prosecutor in the case removed 26 potential black 
jurors in order to obtain an all-white jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Supreme Court has ruled that removal of potential  
jurors on the basis of race was unconstitutional, Amnesty said the 
problem persists because proving ``purposeful discrimination'' is 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	Discrimination can even come from court-appointed lawyers who  
represent clients too poor to afford counsel. A California man, 
Melvin Wade, was called racial slurs by his own lawyer. He was 
sentenced to death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
