<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shooter's Parents Say Son Seemed OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PADUCAH, Ky. (AP) -- Michael Carneal's parents say they saw no  
signs that he was suffering from mental illness before he opened 
fire on a student prayer group, killing three students. 
</P>
<P>
	They said their only explanation for their son's action was that  
he suffered from a mental illness hidden until the rampage, The 
Paducah Sun reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments came in a deposition taken this month in a civil  
suit brought by parents of the three girls slain in the December 
1997 shooting at Heath High School. Five other students were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	John and Ann Carneal are among 10 defendants still a part of the  
suit. Judge Will Shadoan has dismissed numerous others as 
defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deposition, John Carneal said he has read more than 100  
books on mental illness since the shooting, and believes his son 
suffers from a form of schizophrenia. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the diagnosis first made by a psychiatrist who was  
hired as part of the criminal case against Michael. He pleaded 
guilty but mentally ill to murder and was sentenced to life in 
prison with no chance of parole for 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the shooting, Carneal said, he viewed his 15-year-old  
son as a passive, happy person who was not aggressive and not a 
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a person who enjoyed people but was an observer of life  
rather than a participant,'' Carneal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Carneals said they never had any concern that their son had  
potential for violence because he avoided confrontations and was 
compassionate. He even dropped out of karate lessons after he 
accidentally hit a friend too hard and knocked his breath out. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never went back because he hurt his friend,'' Carneal said.  
``That is the Michael Carneal that I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The boy that I see now is not in any way, shape, form or  
fashion the boy who lived in my house,'' Carneal said. ``They are 
entirely different people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Carneal said she was shocked at some of the items found in  
her son's room after the shooting. They included copies of 
pornographic material downloaded from the Internet, documents from 
the Internet that gave instructions for violence, and violent 
stories that Michael had written. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she occasionally ``snooped'' in her son's room but had  
not seen those items. She couldn't speculate on how she would have 
reacted if she had seen them before the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Looking at one piece of work might lead to one response ...  
but putting them all together, there is quite a different picture 
emerging,'' she testified. ``It shows someone who is very hurt.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
