<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Urges Stable Sino-US Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Steady U.S.-China ties are crucial to global  
stability, and the United States should be sensitive to Chinese 
history and culture to maintain the relationship, Hong Kong Chief 
Executive Tung Chee-hwa said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a keynote address to an international business conference,  
Tung said, ``Stable and constructive Sino-U.S. relations are 
crucial, not only to China and the United States, not only to the 
Asia-Pacific region, but to the world as a whole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two countries have held talks on China's entry into the  
World Trade Organization, the global trade liberalization watchdog, 
but their relationship was strained after NATO bombed the Chinese 
embassy in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, Chinese State Councilor Wu Yi, chief negotiator in  
the WTO talks, said the bombing was a ``serious incident,'' but 
didn't comment on whether it could derail WTO talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing, which NATO said was an accident, killed three  
journalists, set off waves of anti-U.S. protests in China, and 
prompted Beijing to cut discussions on military relations and other 
issues with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Wu said she hopes the international investment community isn't  
expecting too much from China in terms of economic liberalization 
and reform as it negotiates to join the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	She said China is committed to market-opening measures, but they  
will have to be conducted in a stable and steady manner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. has to recognize that different countries, with  
different history, culture and most likely in different stages of 
socioeconomic development have different needs,'' Tung said. ``Each 
nation has to find its own way forward as she develops.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
