<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search Renewed for Missing Couple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Donna Morrow disappeared a week before  
Christmas 1991, leaving behind four young children and their 
unwrapped gifts still hidden in the closet. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband, Joe, was accused of her murder. First he attempted  
suicide. Then, when his wife's family sued him, Joe Morrow 
disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	That was six years ago.  
</P>
<P>
	Now Menlo Park police investigators are renewing their search  
for the Morrows -- Donna, who is believed buried somewhere around 
the Silicon Valley, and Joe, who police think is hiding in 
California, Colorado or somewhere in between. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week investigators unsealed a $10 million warrant for Joe  
Morrow, 45 when he disappeared, admitting that their long-term, 
low-profile manhunt had failed. 
</P>
<P>
	``For years we thought we could catch him more easily if he  
didn't know we were looking for him, but that didn't really work 
out,'' said Menlo Park police commander Dominick Peloso. ``Now 
we're enlisting the public's help. If anyone sees Joe Morrow, they 
should call 911.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donna's mother, Shirley Rubio, said she's glad the search is  
picking up again. ``I don't live with rage,'' she said. ``I'm just 
very unhappy, wondering every day if I will have closure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Rubio, who lives in West Plains, Mo., last spoke with her  
daughter Dec. 12, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``Donna called on my birthday and she was crying, saying she  
wanted to leave Joe. She said she wanted to send me something, but 
I told her to save her money so she could support the kids,'' Mrs. 
Rubio said. ``I know she's dead, because if she was alive, she 
would have called me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Morrow was last seen alive Dec. 19 by a neighborhood  
friend. Joe Morrow, a successful businessman, reported her missing 
four days later. He told police they had argued and that Donna had 
walked out late one night with her purse and keys. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and family said Donna Morrow, 37 when she disappeared,  
was a devoted mother whose marriage was falling apart. They said 
she talked about Joe's temper, their fights and how he didn't want 
her to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Police suspected her husband, but failed to gather enough  
evidence to charge him until after he disappeared. ``It's 
frustrating. We had him, but we didn't nail him,'' Peloso said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 13, 1992, investigators interviewed Morrow. The next  
day, his mother reported him missing. He was found in a motel room, 
suffering from what appeared to be an attempted overdose of 
Halcion, a sleeping pill. He left 24 suicide notes, none of which 
was written to his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Court reports show that a blood stain found in the Morrow house  
doesn't match the DNA of Joe or the couple's children. Donna Morrow 
could not be excluded as a possible source, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	After her daughter disappeared, Mrs. Rubio sued Joe Morrow on  
behalf of the four children -- Joseph Jr., Elizabeth, Carrie and 
Alma -- who were ages 12 to 5 when they last saw their mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through the case Joe Morrow vanished. His attorney said  
he stopped calling and failed to make a court appearance on an 
unrelated grand theft charge in San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say the disappearance caught them off guard.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were trying to keep in regular contact with him,'' Peloso  
said. ``All of a sudden he wasn't available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, with Joe Morrow missing, his attorneys settled the  
wrongful death case, agreeing to set up a conservatorship that 
would solely benefit the Morrow children. They will receive their 
portion of the estate, worth about $2 million, when each turns 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The children have been raised by Joe Morrow's brother and  
sister-in-law, David and Ruth Morrow of Roseville, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the children, nor their uncle and aunt, have spoken at  
length with reporters. Police said that the Morrow family has 
refused to help with their investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	According to court records, Ruth Morrow told lawyers during a  
deposition that the children were haunted by the loss of their 
mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so hard for us because we want to give them answers and  
we just can't,'' she said in a deposition in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Menlo Park, an affluent Silicon Valley community with wide  
streets, thick oaks and lawns that spill across neighborhood yards, 
has four police detectives. One of them is always assigned to the 
Morrow case. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the years of frustration, Peloso won't give up.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I'm sure she's dead. Yes, I'm sure Joe did it,'' he said.  
He tapped a photo of Donna Morrow, smiling up from his desk. 
</P>
<P>
	``And yes,'' he said, ``I'm sure we're going to catch him.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
