<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Limits Redistricting Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court made it harder today for  
federal judges to invalidate election districts drawn by state 
legislatures on grounds that race was the major factor in setting 
the boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's unanimous ruling in a North Carolina case could have  
great influence on redistricting disputes nationwide after the 2000 
census -- causing judges to be more certain of the role race played 
before deciding to strike down any reapportionment plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's ruling did not, however, indicate a major change in the  
Supreme Court's hostility to making race the prime factor in 
drawing election district boundaries. The court has been intent 
since 1993 on minimizing the use of race. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of decisions, the court has said that drawing  
districts primarily to maintain or enhance minority voting power 
unlawfully discriminates against white voters. 
</P>
<P>
	But the justices did vote to overturn a three-judge federal  
court's conclusion that North Carolina's 12th Congressional 
District was unlawfully drawn in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The district is represented by Democrat Mel Watt, one of two  
blacks elected to Congress in 1992 from a state that had not sent a 
black to Washington since 1901. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Clarence Thomas, writing for the court, said a  
three-judge federal court wrongly chose not to conduct a full trial 
before ruling last year that the 1997 election map devised by the 
North Carolina Legislature was too race-conscious. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge court made that ruling in what lawyers call a  
``summary judgment,'' after considering the 12th District's shape 
and its racial makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Evidence tends to support an inference that the state drew its  
district lines to support an impermissible racial motive -- even 
though ... (challengers) presented no direct evidence of intent,'' 
Thomas said. ``Summary judgment, however, is appropriate only where 
there is no genuine issue of material fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of decisions since 1993, the Supreme Court has  
scuttled attempts by state and local lawmakers to draw districts to 
preserve or enhance minority candidates' chances to win if race was 
a ``predominant factor.'' Most of those rulings were reached by 5-4 
votes that traced the court's ideological divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra  
Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy united in those 
cases to control the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissenting in those previous cases were Justices John Paul  
Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. 
Breyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, those four justices joined in the final result but not in  
Thomas' opinion. Stevens wrote separately for the four. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record supports the conclusion that most loyal Democrats  
living near the borders of District 12 happen to be black 
Democrats, and I have no doubt that the Legislature was conscious 
of that fact when it enacted the apportionment plan,'' Stevens 
said. ``But everyone agrees that that fact is not sufficient to 
invalidate the district.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The North Carolina dispute now will return to the three-judge  
federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Redrawing 12 congressional districts after the 1990 census,  
North Carolina lawmakers created two majority-black districts in 
1992 -- the 1st and 12th. That 1992 redistricting sparked two 
Supreme Court decisions, one in 1996 that struck down the 12th 
District as unlawfully drawn. As drawn in 1992, the district had a 
57 percent majority of blacks among registered voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The district, which connected several concentrated areas of  
black voters, was 160 miles long and sometimes was no wider than 
Interstate 85. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature redrew the district in 1997, creating one 71  
miles long in which blacks comprised 47 percent of registered 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices' previous redistricting rulings have offered  
precious little guidance for lower courts on just how much evidence 
is needed to conclude that race played too large a role in the 
drawing of an election district. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that Watt's district has been before the justices three  
times in six years, New York lawyer Richard Buery Jr. wrote 
recently, ``This lack of doctrinal guidance has left states subject 
to the inconsistent whims of district judges, forcing the Supreme 
Court into micromanagement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today's decision put district courts on notice that more than  
circumstantial evidence that race was the primary consideration is 
required before the Legislature's redistricting work can be 
invalidated. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Hunt vs. Cromartie, 98-85.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 14:22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Tries for Education Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Parents who send children to private schools  
or who teach at home would get new education tax breaks under 
Republican legislation unveiled Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, similar to a bill vetoed last year by President  
Clinton, is strongly opposed by Democratic-aligned teacher unions 
even though the GOP added sweeteners this time such as tax 
incentives to help finance school construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance  
Committee, called the bill ``a first but important step'' in making 
education more affordable for all students and parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``This proposal is a down payment on education assistance for  
our nation's students and their families,'' Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Committee is scheduled to vote on the bill  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would cost $7.6 billion over 10 years, according to  
a preliminary congressional analysis. It would be paid for by $7.9 
billion in revenue offsets that chiefly affect business. 
</P>
<P>
	The centerpiece of the measure would raise the annual  
contribution limit on education IRAs, now used only for higher 
education, from $500 to $2,000. For the first time, the money could 
be withdrawn tax-free to pay expenses for kindergarten through 12th 
grade students attending public, private or parochial school or who 
are taught at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualified expenses would include tuition, fees, books, supplies,  
computer software and required uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Like current law, the contribution limit would be phased out for  
individuals earning more than $95,000 in adjusted gross income and 
$150,000 for joint income tax filers. 
</P>
<P>
	When he vetoed a similar measure last year, Clinton said the  
money could be better used for public school construction and 
contended the GOP bill would primarily benefit the wealthy. The 
National Education Association, which led last year's opposition, 
said little has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's bad tax policy and it's bad education policy,'' said Mary  
Elizabeth Teasley, NEA legislative affairs director. ``It's a 
disguise for a private school voucher for the wealthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House did not immediately comment on the bill.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are optimistic, however, that they can gain  
significant Democratic support for the measure. Sen. Robert 
Torricelli, D-N.J., is the main co-sponsor of the education IRA 
bill and several other items supported by Democrats were included. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them are the public school construction components  
introduced by Democratic Sen. Bob Graham of Florida. The components 
would relax certain revenue bond rules and add schools to the list 
of projects that can be paid for with tax-exempt private activity 
bonds, which have an annual limit of $10 per resident or at least 
$5 million per state. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would allow tax-free distributions from state-sponsored  
and private prepaid college tuition plans, costing $925 million 
over 10 years. It would also extend the tax-free treatment of 
college-level educational assistance provided by an employer, a 
break now scheduled to expire in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
