<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Barak Elected Israeli Premier  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Ehud Barak, a former general who promised to  
resume Mideast peace talks, today unseated Israeli Prime Minister 
Benjamin Netanyahu. A tearful Netanyahu later said he also would 
step down as leader of the Likud Party. President Clinton called 
Barak to congratulate him, and the two pledged to restore 
U.S.-Israeli ties that had suffered under Netanyahu, said a Barak 
aide. Barak, unlike Netanyahu, has not ruled out the creation of an 
independent Palestinian state and he was expected to quickly carry 
out the West Bank troop withdrawals Netanyahu held up. Barak has 
also pledged to pull Israeli troops out of Lebanon within a year. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat Congratulates Barak  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat  
offered congratulations to Ehud Barak, Israel's newly elected prime 
minister. The Palestinian leader was careful throughout the race to 
describe the outcome as a strictly Israeli affair. Asked if he 
thought the left-leaning Barak would move the peace process 
forward, he answered: ``We hope so.'' Other Palestinian officials, 
however, wasted no time in calling on Barak to get negotiations 
back on track. ``The message the Israeli people sent out ... was 
that they want to make peace with the Palestinians and that they 
want change,'' chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Jets Strike Again  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets struck an industrial zone,  
a key Yugoslav highway and Kosovo targets today. A U.N. delegation 
was in Belgrade preparing for the first trip to Kosovo by 
international authorities since March 24, when NATO launched 
airstrikes against Yugoslavia. Hours after nightfall, NATO attacks 
resumed, with three powerful blasts heard in Nis, the private news 
agency Beta said. Bridges and overpasses on main Belgrade-Nis 
highway were also struck. In Kosovo, attacks targeted the former 
command center of rebels at Likovac, which was overrun by Serb 
forces earlier this year, Yugoslav media said. 

</P>
<P>
	Sonia Gandhi Quits Party Position  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sonia Gandhi, a main contender to be  
India's prime minister, stepped down as president of the Congress 
party today after several party leaders complained her Italian 
birth was a political liability. But her resignation was 
immediately rejected by the party's highest decision-making body, 
the Congress Working Committee, and party leaders went to Mrs. 
Gandhi's house to beg her to reconsider. Mrs. Gandhi was born in 
Italy, but became a citizen after she married into India's foremost 
political dynasty. 

</P>
<P>
	House GOP Maps Cuts in Bills  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bills covering education, environment and  
other traditional Democratic priorities face billions of dollars in 
cuts next year under emerging Republican plans. The House 
Appropriations Committee plans to decide this week how it would 
divide $538 billion among 13 bills covering all government 
agencies. The committee's blueprint, obtained by The Associated 
Press, shows that the appropriations committee plans $78.1 billion 
for the Labor, Education and Health and Human Services departments 
-- $10.7 billion less than this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Denny's To Revamp Restaurants  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The Denny's restaurant chain announced  
plans today to revamp its Grand Slam breakfast image into juke box 
rockin' 1950s-style diners. Advantica Restaurant Group Inc., 
Denny's parent company, plans to spend more than $30 million this 
year to remodel 150 restaurants with stainless steel exteriors, 
neon lights, rotating pie cases and juke boxes. The company 
eventually wants to convert all 1,700 Denny's restaurants across 
the country. The menu and prices will largely be the same. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks edged higher Tuesday. The benchmark  
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 12.75 points to 16,433.77 in 
early trading. In New York Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
fell 59.85 to close at 10,853.47. 

</P>
<P>
	Pacers Edge 76ers 94-90  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana made five free throws over the final  
23 seconds tonight in a 94-90 victory over Philadelphia in the 
opening game of the best-of-7 NBA Eastern Conference semifinal. 
Jalen Rose came off the bench to score a career playoff-high 27 
points. The Pacers used balanced scoring to overcome the 35 points 
of league scoring champion Allen Iverson. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa Homers Twice As Cubs Win  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Sammy Sosa homered twice for the first time this  
season as the Chicago Cubs beat the Florida Marlins 8-1. It marked 
Sosa's 34th multihomer game and first since Sept. 23 at Milwaukee. 
He has 11 homers this season and seven in his past 12 games. Kevin 
Tapani (3-1) pitched a four-hitter and lowered his ERA to 1.77. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
