<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Collectors Snap Up Olympic Pins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The new Olympic mascots already are  
winners at the cash register. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee raked in nearly $75,000 from  
the sales of merchandise during Saturday night's mascot launch and 
celebration marking 1,000 days to the 2002 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the revenue came from sales of collector pins,  
snapped up by devotees of Olympic pins and the money to be made 
trading them. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC sold out of its allotment of 200 limited edition jumbo  
pins, one reading ``We're Here'' and showing the three new mascots 
-- a snowshoe hare, coyote and black bear -- and another showing the 
mascots along with the words ``1,000 Days Until the Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't have anywhere near enough of those,'' said Ray  
Carter, retail operation coordinator for the SLOC, which is 
organizing the Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 2,002 of those pins were produced for sale in stores that  
carry Olympic merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	Other pins also sold well, including mascot and 1,000-day pins  
in five color combinations, on sale only at the festivities in 
downtown Salt Lake Saturday night. Besides introducing the mascots 
-- to be named in a national contest this summer -- the SLOC unveiled 
an arrowhead-shaped bronze sculpture bearing the countdown clock 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC estimated sales were between $50,000 and $75,000,  
including totals for T-shirts, caps and other merchandise carrying 
the Salt Lake Games' logo. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pins were clearly the hit, partly because there was a  
pin-collector convention here over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC limited each customer to two pins of each kind, in part  
to discourage collectors from stripping the shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the collectors were peeved and made a scene when they  
were not allowed to buy mascot and countdown merchandise before the 
mascots and clock were unveiled. ``They just wanted to know why 
they weren't told ahead of time. We had some signage that didn't 
come through,'' Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the booth doors opened, there were more than 300  
customers in line. 
</P>
<P>
	The green Jell-O Olympic pin that poked fun at Utah's reputation  
for high consumption of Jell-O, sold for $7 when it was introduced 
last year. The Jell-O pins now command $40 to $50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
