<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Address Gun Control Rift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gun control is not the only factor to be  
considered in protecting the nation's youth from violence, but 
everybody with a gun should be capable of using it properly and 
willing to use it lawfully, Attorney General Janet Reno says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to focus on prevention, on intervention programs, on  
enforcement programs that go far beyond the gun issue,'' Reno said 
Sunday on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she ``couldn't agree more'' with Sen. Orrin Hatch,  
R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, that gun 
control is not the only answer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch's compromise gun legislation in a bill on juvenile crime  
raised a furor in the Senate last week as normally pro-gun control 
Democrats angrily declared it politicized the question. Hatch and 
other Republicans alleged the Democrats were doing the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch and Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., worked over the weekend to  
try to reach a new compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said Hatch's measure ``still permits the sale of (some)  
guns at gun shows without a background check. It leaves open a big 
category of flea markets, where a large number of guns can be sold 
without the background check. 
</P>
<P>
	``And it reduces the time for doing the check from three days --  
three working days -- to 24 hours, where most gun shows are held on 
weekends. You're not going to have the chance to check it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, the sale could go through unless a negative  
background report comes back on the purchaser within 24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether politics can be removed from so sensitive an  
issue, the attorney general said: ``Just say no one should possess 
a weapon unless they have demonstrated that they know how to safely 
and lawfully use it and are capable of safely and lawfully using 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In appearances on ``Fox News Sunday'' and ABC's ``This Week,''  
Hatch conceded his bill is imperfect, but he said the Republicans 
remain open to more compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats made a particular issue over a provision that would  
remove the requirement for pawn shops to check the backgrounds of 
people reclaiming pawned weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch accused the Democrats, particularly New York Sen. Charles  
Schumer, of playing politics. As evidence, he produced a 1994 
letter in which then-Rep. Schumer, during House debate on a major 
crime bill that session, said he could accept a pawn shop waiver. 
</P>
<P>
	On CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' Schumer said the 1994 measure was  
the Omnibus Crime Bill. He said he actually opposed the pawn shop 
amendment, which was proposed by former Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, 
a member of the National Rifle Association board. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Hatch and Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., showed for TV cameras  
copies of Schumer's letter on the pawn shop issue to then-Treasury 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen. They also displayed charts showing numbers 
of federal prosecutions under existing gun laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Allard, appearing with Schumer on CBS, said federal prosecution  
of crimes committed with a firearm had dropped 40 percent during 
the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``We simply need to step up enforcement,'' Allard said. ``How  
can you justify passing more laws and particularly with using 
political arguments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said the figures are misleading because state and local  
prosecutions have increased. ``These cases involve juvenile justice 
cases, better handled at the local level,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
