<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns, Steelers Do Lunch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Doug Dieken remembers breaking from the Browns'  
huddle, lining up at offensive tackle against Pittsburgh's ``Steel 
Curtain'' defense and being awed by the names on the other side. 
</P>
<P>
	L.C. Greenwood. ``Mean'' Joe Greene. Ernie Holmes. Dwight White.  
And a certain linebacker, who played like a monster and looked like 
one, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'd see Jack Lambert smiling and you'd realize, they've got  
some darn good football players,'' Dieken said. ``But we've got a 
better dental plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dieken's shot at Lambert was one of many taken Monday as former  
members of the Browns and Steelers joined current players from the 
teams for the second ``Grudge Luncheon,'' a charity event designed 
to rekindle one of the NFL's fiercest rivalries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns are returning to the league in 1999 following a  
three-year hiatus. Fittingly, they'll open the season and a new 
stadium against the Steelers on Sept. 12 in a nationally televised 
night game. 
</P>
<P>
	At lunch on Monday, stories of old Browns-Steelers games were  
told and an NFL films video titled ``The Rivalry Returns'' was 
shown. The film drew cheers from Browns fans when Bernie Kosar 
threw a TD pass, and prompting a sizable contingent of Steelers 
fans to wave their Terrible Towels when Lambert planted a Browns 
running back into the turf. 
</P>
<P>
	If any player in the Browns-Steelers games had reasons to hold a  
grudge, Dieken said he had at least 14. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played in Pittsburgh 14 times,'' he said. ``I lost 14  
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dieken's turn at the microphone came after long-time Steelers  
radio analyst Myron Cope finished insulting Browns coach Chris 
Palmer, owner Al Lerner and telling off-color stories about 
covering games in the old Cleveland Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here I am in Cleveland again after an enjoyable absence of  
three years,'' Cope said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns moved to Baltimore after the 1995 season and return  
as an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	Dieken's first target was Steelers coach Bill Cowher, a backup  
linebacker with the Browns who made a brief cameo in the video. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was nice of NFL films to show Bill Cowher's tackle,''  
Dieken said. ``Actually, he had two others. One was a guy going out 
of bounds and the other was a goalpost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dieken also compared the differences in Cleveland and  
Pittsburgh, cities just 90 miles apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Cleveland, Lerner is the name of the man who owns our  
franchise,'' he said. ``In Pittsburgh, Lerner is the answer you get 
when you ask the people there why they send their daughters to 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Cleveland, football is a passion. Football is a religion.  
In Pittsburgh, football is the word that knocked Bill Cowher out of 
his high school spelling bee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The luncheons were the idea of Browns president Carmen Policy,  
who along with Lerner and Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney, were in New 
York for the funeral of Jets owner Leon Hess and missed last week's 
luncheon in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	But all three quickly warmed to the occasion, taking turns at  
telling stories and delivering cheap shots. 
</P>
<P>
	When Pittsburgh used to visit the old Cleveland Stadium, with  
its tiny, outdated locker rooms, many Steelers would bring nails 
they could pound into the walls to hang their clothes. Palmer 
presented Cowher with a symbolic nail as a gift. 
</P>
</TEXT>
