<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones, Reuters Combine Archives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones and Reuters announced a deal Monday to  
combine their business news archives into a company that will 
provide financial information to paid subscribers over the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies plan to introduce the new product, to be called  
Dow Jones Reuters Business Interactive, in about a year. Before 
that time, the two companies will share archived news for their 
database services. 
</P>
<P>
	The new venture will combine the resources of Dow Jones  
Interactive, which was formerly known as Dow Jones News/Retrieval, 
with a similar offering from the London-based financial news 
publisher called Reuters Business Briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined service will be aimed mainly at business users,  
offering archived stories from thousands of news sources, including 
newspapers, magazines and wire services. The service will be 
offered in 11 different languages. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal does not include the consumer Internet services of  
either company, such as the successful online version of Dow Jones' 
flagship newspaper, Wall Street Journal Interactive. Also excluded 
are the competing real-time financial news wires run by the two 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones and Reuters will have equal ownership stakes in the  
new company, and management will also be shared. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the current boom among investors for Internet-related  
companies, officials said there were no plans to float shares in 
the joint venture, which would have had 1998 revenues of $225 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones Interactive is currently available to more than  
650,000 users, and its largest market is in North America. The 
Reuters Business Briefing is sold to more than 6,000 companies and 
financial institutions, and most of its business comes from Europe 
and Asia. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
