<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Keeps Marathon Oil Suit Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today kept alive, but  
perhaps just barely, a Texas lawsuit in which Marathon Oil Co. 
accused a German company, Ruhrgas A.G., of illegally trying to 
monopolize the market on natural gas from the Norwegian North Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ruled unanimously that a federal trial judge may  
have acted within his authority when he threw out the 1995 lawsuit 
in a way that barred it from being taken up by any Texas state 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court had overturned the judge's action.  
</P>
<P>
	Today's ruling had nothing to do with Marathon's allegations  
against Ruhrgas, but focused instead on the judicial equivalent of 
an age-old question: What came first, the chicken or the egg? 
</P>
<P>
	In deciding whether a lawsuit originally filed in a state court  
properly can be transferred to a federal court in the same state, 
federal trial judges must make two determinations about their 
authority, or what the courts call jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge in such a case must decide whether he or she has  
jurisdiction over the lawsuit's subject matter. If federal 
``subject-matter jurisdiction'' does not exist, the case must be 
returned to the state court where it can run its course. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal judge also must decide whether he or she has  
``personal jurisdiction'' -- authority over all parties involved in 
the case. For a judge to have such authority, all the parties must 
have some minimal connection to the state. 
</P>
<P>
	If no federal court personal jurisdiction is found, there can be  
no personal jurisdiction in a state court within that same state. 
That means a federal judge's dismissal, for lack of personal 
jurisdiction, of a lawsuit transferred from a state court 
effectively kills the lawsuit. It cannot be heard in the state 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal courts have not agreed which type of jurisdiction should  
be determined first. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the court today, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said  
there is no hard and fast rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``In most instances, subject-matter jurisdiction will involve no  
arduous inquiry ... In such cases, both expedition and sensitivity 
to state courts' coequal stature should impel the federal courts to 
dispose of that issue first,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometimes the personal-jurisdiction issue can be the first  
resolved, she added. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where, as here, ... a district court has before it a  
straightforward personal jurisdiction issue presenting no complex 
question of state law, and the alleged defect in subject-matter 
jurisdiction raises a difficult and novel question, the court does 
not abuse its discretion by turning directly to personal 
jurisdiction,'' Ginsburg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas case now heads back to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals for more study. 
</P>
<P>
	Marathon's lawsuit against Ruhrgas originally was filed in a  
state court in Houston, but Ruhrgas sought to transfer the case to 
a federal court in that city. The federal trial judge dismissed the 
case after citing a lack of personal jurisdiction. Subject-matter 
jurisdiction was never considered. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5th Circuit court ruled by a 9-7 vote last year that the  
trial judge made a mistake. In cases seeking transfer from state 
courts, the appeals court ruled, federal trial judges first must 
consider whether they have subject-matter jurisdiction. Only when 
they find such authority exists can they move on to determining 
whether their court has personal jurisdiction as well. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling reinstated Marathon's lawsuit and sent it back to  
the federal trial judge. Marathon's lawyers had reason to hope the 
judge would find he lacked subject-matter jurisdiction so the case 
could return to the Texas state court where the lawsuit began. 
</P>
<P>
	That outcome could change after the 5th Circuit court takes a  
new look at the case, in light of today's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Ruhrgas A.G. vs. Marathon Oil Co., 98-470.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 07:01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Program Helps With Downloads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Not all, or even very many, of the truly nifty bits of software  
come from the giant companies that drive herds of programmers 
through their cubicled stockyards daily. Often, it's a small 
company that identifies an opportunity and provides a neat, 
cost-effective solution. 
</P>
<P>
	A good example is Forty Software of Great Neck, N.Y., and their  
$29.77 product called Download Wonder 1.5. Download Wonder 
recognizes that just about everyone who surfs the Internet 
downloads stuff -- often lots of it. Internet browsers can handle 
the downloading part, but they just dump it into the folder you 
used last time, leaving any organization up to you. For most of us, 
that's like leaving henhouse security to the foxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides which, when you're downloading one file, you can't  
continue browsing for others until the transfer is complete. That's 
a real pain if you're downloading a multimegabyte Windows update. 
</P>
<P>
	Download Wonder intercepts the files before your browser gets  
its teeth in them and lets you do several very convenient things. 
Among them: 
</P>
<P>
	--You can continue browsing while downloading and have multiple  
downloads going at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	--You can complete downloading files even after the browser has  
been closed. 
</P>
<P>
	--A ``keep-alive'' feature prevents your service provider from  
knocking you offline, a problem often cited by AOL users. 
</P>
<P>
	--You can resume interrupted download at the point of  
interruption (at least if the sending server supports that 
function). 
</P>
<P>
	Once downloaded, you can select a folder for the file and  
classify it by the original Web site, the download URL, category, 
description, notes, up to three keywords, download date, time and 
size, and file modification date. 
</P>
<P>
	If that sounds like overkill, suppose you hunt foodtv.com or  
other Web cooking sites for recipes. Wouldn't it be nice to have an 
easy way to categorize those recipes by hors d'oeuvre or main 
course and so on, cross-referenced by kind of meat? The software 
will do it. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also come in very handy for any sort of extensive  
online research. 
</P>
<P>
	Download Wonder 1.5 installs easily and has good online help. It  
includes an uninstall program, a sign that the authors are 
responsible people. 
</P>
<P>
	System requirements are modest: eight megabytes of RAM and  
Windows 95, 98 or NT 4.0 and above. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the registered version for $29.77, you can  
download an advertiser-sponsored freeware version at www.forty.com. 
A human being will accept an order Monday to Friday, 9:30 a.m. to 
6:30 p.m., at (877) 386-8833, and you can also order the registered 
version online. 
</P>
<P>
	Since most software pricing ends in ``95,'' and this one ends in  
``77,'' Forty Software chief operating officer Michael S. Klein was 
asked why the oddball price. He explained that research showed 
folks were more likely to buy a product with a price ending in a 
seven. 
</P>
<P>
	Now why didn't Microsoft think of that?  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
