<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Mummy' Hangs On to Top Spot / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A string of low-budget, independent films  
peppered the box office this weekend yet ``The Mummy'' continued to 
grasp the No. 1 spot with $25.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Moviegoers endured the final ``Star Wars''-less weekend of the  
year, what some might call the calm before the storm troopers, 
industry estimates showed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Earning a total of $80.8 million in only two weeks of release,  
``The Mummy,'' a swashbuckling story of a group of explorers who 
accidentally resurrect an ancient Egyptian priest, has become the 
season's biggest blockbuster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Mummy'' and two other big-budget spectaculars --  
``Entrapment'' and ``The Matrix'' -- held off a horde of 
bacchanalian fairies in the latest film version of ``William 
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The update of the Bard's lighthearted romp through a mystical  
forest, starring Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer, Stanley Tucci and 
Calista Flockhart, opened this week in fourth place with $4.4 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-stakes caper ``Entrapment'' starring Sean Connery was  
No. 2 with $8.7 million, while ``The Matrix'' featuring Keanu 
Reeves was third with $4.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening in fifth place was the Hong Kong martial arts thriller  
``Black Mask,'' starring Jet Li as a mild-mannered librarian who 
becomes a masked crimefighter. The film earned $4.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The urban comedy ``Trippin','' about a rambunctious teen-aged  
daydreamer, debuted in seventh place with $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In limited release, ``Tea With Mussolini,'' the story of a boy  
raised by eccentric Englishwomen in World War II Italy, landed in 
10th place in only 270 theaters, earning a per-screen average of 
$6,296. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend was considered a virtual wasteland by most studios  
who feared a black hole-effect from the impending opening of ``Star 
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' The hyper-publicized sci-fi 
prequel opens Wednesday and is expected to draw audiences away from 
most other movies. 
</P>
<P>
	That may account for the unusually high number of smaller films  
in the top 10 this weekend, according to Robert Bucksbaum, a Reel 
Source Inc. movie analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't usually want to open a film five days before the  
most anticipated film of the decade, and perhaps of all time,'' he 
said. ``When you do, you're either hoping to get spillover audience 
from the sold-out 'Star Wars' shows, or you're trying to appeal to 
a totally different audience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Films such as ``Tea with Mussolini'' and ``A Midsummer Night's  
Dream,'' are aimed at older audiences who couldn't care less about 
The Force, while ``Trippin,'' and ``Black Mask'' may draw a younger 
crowd who can't get tickets to the prequel, Bucksbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekend ticket sales were 2.2 percent higher than the same  
weekend last year, when ``Deep Impact'' was No. 1 followed by ``The 
Horse Whisperer'' and ``The Quest For Camelot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Sunday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Inc., with final figures 
to be released today: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Mummy,'' $25.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Entrapment,'' $8.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Matrix,'' $4.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' $4.4  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Black Mask,'' $4.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Life,'' $2.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Trippin','' $2.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Never Been Kissed,'' $2.45 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Election,'' $2.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Tea With Mussolini,'' $1.7 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
