<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A gang held 50 people hostage in a  
downtown bank, broke into 200 safety deposit boxes and escaped with 
an undetermined amount of cash and jewelry, police and security 
agents said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's security chief, Alexander Campos, said the robbers  
picked him up as he left home Sunday. They ordered him to open the 
bank, and three stayed at his house with his wife and 11-month-old 
son. 
</P>
<P>
	Campos' wife, Delayne, told reporters the robbers prepared the  
infant's formula and changed his diapers while they waited. ``They 
said they wouldn't hurt us, that they just wanted the money,'' she 
said in a televised interview. 
</P>
<P>
	At the bank, the gang locked up 50 security and maintenance  
personnel and went through safety deposit boxes. Police said they 
suspected a former bank employee had taken part. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A bus swerved off a cliff in Peru's northern  
Andes mountains, killing 14 people and injuring 17, authorities 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened late Sunday on a rain-slick highway near  
Otuzco, 305 miles northwest of Lima, said Dr. Gilberto Gutierrez, 
director of Otuzco's hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus swerved off the edge of the 660-foot cliff and split in  
two during the fall, survivors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bus plummeted off the same cliff in March, killing all  
36 occupants. 
</P>
