<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Futures Tumble  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sugar futures tumbled more than 5 percent Monday on the Board of  
Trade of the City of New York amid heavy producer selling of what 
is expected to be a bumper world crop. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grain and soybeans advanced, while pork  
futures fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures sank amid expectations that a recent increase in  
producer selling will continue for months to come, at a time when 
world demand remains weak. Exporters are taking advantage of price 
gains that came as increased buying lifted prices from 14-year lows 
to dump as much of their supplies on the market as they can. 
</P>
<P>
	That comes as most of the world's major producers are combining  
for another year of record production. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent report from the American attache to Brazil predicted  
that the country will complete harvesting of a crop of 19 million 
metric tons, up from last year's record 18.3 metric million tons. 
</P>
<P>
	And Cuban production has reached an unexpectedly large 3.8  
million metric tons, according to local industry sources. 
Thailand's milled production also is coming in more than 18 percent 
higher than last year's weather-reduced output. 
</P>
<P>
	Raw sugar for July delivery fell .27 cent to 4.63 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures moved modestly higher on the Chicago  
Board of Trade as wet weather continued to delay spring plantings. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants said wheat and corn in particular were  
poised to move sharply higher if wet weather persists in Midwest 
growing regions. Farmers typically have a limited window for 
planting those crops, and that June deadline is rapidly 
approaching. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the government in its weekly updates has reported that  
dry periods between recent storms have given farmers ample time to 
continue planting. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 77 percent of corn acreage already has been planted, the  
U.S. Agriculture Department reported after trading had ended, up 1 
percent over last year and 9 percent over the five-year average. 
Wheat and soybean planting also were proceeding normally, the 
agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	After trading had ended, the National Weather Service also  
predicted normal to below-normal precipitation over the next 10 
days in major Midwestern growing areas, which could speed the rest 
of planting. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans moved higher in step with corn, although some market  
participants worried that any planting delays for corn and wheat 
would lead to increased soybean acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.62 3/4 a bushel; July corn rose 2  
cents to $2.23 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 1/2 cents to $4.70 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
amid ideas retailers already have secured ample supplies going into 
the Memorial Day holiday, leaving little room to sell recent 
increased slaughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 1.84 million hogs were slaughtered last week, up 3 percent  
from 1.79 million hogs a week earlier, according to the USDA. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the losses, some analysts predict pork prices will rise  
this summer as a decision early this year by producers to reduce 
herds begins to have an effect. 
</P>
<P>
	June lean hogs fell .90 cent to 57.97 cents a pound; July pork  
bellies fell 1.55 cents to 54.65 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
