<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.N. Mission To Go to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Bad weather forced the cancellation  
of most NATO flights over Kosovo today as diplomatic efforts to 
solve the nearly 2-month-old conflict moved into higher gear. A 
U.N. delegation was in Belgrade, preparing to make the first trip 
to Kosovo by international authorities since some 790,000 ethnic 
Albanians were driven out of the southern Serb province beginning 
March 24, when NATO launched punitive airstrikes against 
Yugoslavia. Meanwhile, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder made an 
unexpected trip to Finland today, increasing speculation that 
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari is preparing to take a central 
role in seeking a solution to the Kosovo crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb POWs May Be Freed Soon  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. military authorities in Germany are  
preparing to release two Serb soldiers held as prisoners of war for 
several weeks, senior Pentagon officials said today. ``They are 
going to be released,'' one official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said yesterday. ``We're just working out the details 
now.'' Another official said the prisoners likely would be released 
to the International Committee of the Red Cross. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Expected To Win in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Ehud Barak, Israel's most decorated soldier and  
a peace process moderate, was heavily favored today to unseat Prime 
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in general elections capping a divisive 
five-month campaign. Last-minute polls showed the Labor candidate 
widening his lead over Likud's Netanyahu. ``I feel that the Israeli 
people want to see a new way of governing,'' Barak said after 
pushing through security to greet supporters. ``The people want to 
see change, unity and hope.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Independent Counsel Change Proposed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An alternative law must be crafted to replace  
the Independent Counsel Act, former Senate majority leaders Bob 
Dole and George Mitchell said in a New York Times opinion piece 
today. The underlying purpose of the law remains a vital one: to 
make sure allegations of criminal wrongdoing by high-ranking 
government officials are thoroughly investigated and prosecuted, 
Dole and Mitchell wrote. ``The key is to find a system that 
accomplishes that aim while retaining both the independence and the 
accountability of investigators,'' they wrote in the article 
published on the Times' op-ed page. 

</P>
<P>
	Sen. Dole May Make Pledge to McCain  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Sen. Bob Dole says he's not sure his wife  
will seek the Republican presidential nomination. He's even 
considering contributing to the campaign of one of her competitors, 
Sen. John McCain. ``McCain's my friend. And he's not raising the 
money that (Texas Gov.) George Bush is. I think we need to keep 
good people in the race,'' Dole said in an interview in today's New 
York Times. But he added that he would probably check with Mrs. 
Dole first. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's PM Choice May Be Approved  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- There are indications that Boris Yeltsin's choice  
for prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, will be approved by the lower 
chamber of the Russian Parliament, the State Duma, in a scheduled 
vote Wednesday. Stepashin held talks today with centrist deputies 
and regional leaders to ask for their support. Gennady Seleznyov, 
the Communist speaker of the Duma, said he thought that Stepashin 
would be approved on the first vote. The parliament failed to 
impeach President Yeltsin yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Infant Gets Cow Neck Valve in Heart  
</P>
<P>
	EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) -- A 13-month-old boy has become the first  
person in the United States to have a bovine neck valve 
transplanted in his heart, officials said. Ryan Dotys has been 
breathing on his own since Thursday night and the prognosis looks 
good, said Dr. Robert Brown, the cardiothorasic surgeon who 
performed the transplant May 4. The procedure, performed at Riley 
Hospital for Children in Indianapolis, has not been approved in the 
United States, but the Food and Drug Administration permitted the 
surgery as a ``compassionate case'' because of Ryan's critical 
condition. Ryan was born with only one heart valve instead of two. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Prices Open Lower  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened lower today. Just  
before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 21 points. Losers 
on the New York Stock Exchange held a 9-5 lead over gainers. The 
Nasdaq was down 11 points. Stocks were sharply lower on Friday, as 
the bond market reacted negatively to the latest inflation news. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche Beat Red Wings 3-0  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Colorado Avalanche are just one victory away  
from the Western Conference finals after beating the Detroit Red 
Wings 3-0 yesterday for a 3-2 lead in the series. Peter Forsberg 
had a goal and an assist, and Patrick Roy recorded his 12th career 
playoff shutout. Game 6 is tomorrow night in Detroit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
</P>
