<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Kids' Livers Go to Adults </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Two-thirds of children's livers donated for  
transplant in the United States went to adults during an eight-year 
span examined by researchers, while about 75 children a year died 
waiting for a new liver. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings by researchers from the University of Pittsburgh  
add to the debate over how to change the nation's organ allocation 
system to make it fairer. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe has virtually eliminated deaths of children waiting for  
livers by giving them priority over adults for pediatric organs, 
said Dr. Jorge Reyes, a co-author of the study and the chief of 
transplantation at Children's Hospital and the Starzl Transplant 
Institute in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we have to do is just change some computer arrangements.  
We just need to want to do that and put politics aside,'' Reyes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were presented Monday in Chicago at the annual  
meeting of the American Society for Transplantation. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current U.S. system, donated organs are first offered  
to potential recipients in the locality where the organs originate, 
even if a patient -- adult or child -- is in greater need elsewhere. 
Only if the organ is not placed locally is it offered regionally 
and then nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Adults on the waiting list far outnumber children, and the  
adults end up receiving most of the organs, unless the livers are 
are too small to work in adults, which is only true of organs from 
very young donors. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors are increasingly using various techniques to ease the  
organ shortage for children, such as transplanting a liver segment 
from a living donor, usually a parent, or splitting a cadaver liver 
to give a child one segment and an adult another. About one-third 
of children who receive transplants undergo such procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	But children's survival is poorer with adult liver segments --  
67.9 percent -- than with children's livers -- 75.7 percent. Adult 
survival is virtually the same whether the donor was a child or an 
adult. 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, Reyes and his colleagues reviewed the United  
Network for Organ Sharing registry of transplants performed from 
1991 through 1998 and found that 4,288 of 6,028 pediatric livers 
were used in adults. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyes wants two things: First, that pediatric livers first be  
offered to children nationally. Second, that livers from 
``blue-ribbon'' adult donors, those in the best condition, be split 
so that both an adult and a child can benefit when no child liver 
is available. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't particularly say that an adult life is less  
valuable,'' Reyes said. ``I just think it makes good sense and good 
judgment and is humane to try to save our children as much as 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Spieldenner, a spokesman for the UNOS, which sets allocation  
policy, said his organization agrees and is working to revise its 
system. It has already done so for heart transplants, for the same 
reason. 
</P>
<P>
	But the agency is taking care not to worsen the plight of  
adults, more than 1,000 of whom die each year waiting for livers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Sue McDiarmid, head of UNOS' pediatric committee, said:  
``The last thing I want to do is to develop any kind of policies 
that would have a significant impact on adult mortality. That 
wouldn't be right. We've got to be very careful in how we think 
about it so that we get the maximum good for the minimum harm.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
