<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Air, Attendants Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines and its flight attendants' union  
have reached a tentative agreement after nearly nine months of 
contract talks. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no public disputes in these negotiations, unlike the  
last round in 1993 when the flight attendants struck the airline 
for five days and virtually shut down American's operations. 
</P>
<P>
	AMR Corp., the airline's parent company, and the Association of  
Professional Flight Attendants, which represents 20,000 members, 
did not disclose details of the plan, reached Sunday and announced 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact does provide pay increases, improvements in retirement  
and increased scheduling flexibility, according to the APFA and 
AMR. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise Hedges, union president, said the contract will lead the  
industry and set a new standard for flight attendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the accords were reached with informal help from the  
National Mediation Board during two weeks of around-the-clock 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Sue Oliver, vice president of employee relations and chief  
negotiator for the company, said the two sides worked together to 
reach agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative agreement now will be subject to the APFA's  
ratification process. First, the union officers will review and 
vote on the pact. If they approve, the agreement will be sent to 
all members by mail. A simple majority of returned ballots is 
necessary for the deal to pass. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second agreement between APFA and AMR this year.  
Last month, the flight attendants union and American reached an 
understanding on how to integrate flight attendants from Reno Air, 
which AMR purchased last December. 
</P>
<P>
	The dealings between the flight attendants and the company this  
year have been in sharp contrast to strained relations between 
American and its pilots' union. 
</P>
<P>
	The Allied Pilots Association and American are still at odds  
over the acquisition of Reno. Their disagreement led to a massive 
sickout in February that caused the cancellation of nearly 6,700 
flights and contempt damages of $45 million to be paid to AMR by 
APA and its two top officers. The airline said the job action has 
cost it $140 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
