<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: President Can Fire Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, ruling in the case of an  
HIV-positive Air Force major imprisoned for having unprotected sex, 
today bolstered the president's power as the nation's military 
commander in chief. 
</P>
<P>
	The court unanimously overturned an order by the military's  
highest court that had barred the president from dropping from the 
armed forces any commissioned officer jailed for more than six 
months under a court-martial conviction that has become final. 
</P>
<P>
	The Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces had ruled that such  
presidential action violates the constitutional protection against 
being punished twice for the same crime, the court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	But today's decision said the military court lacked the  
authority to make that ruling and to block the president's action. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling spares President Clinton and his successors from the  
awkward position of being unable to fire senior military personnel 
for the same offenses that got them court-martialed and convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Maj. James Goldsmith is infected with the virus that causes  
AIDS. After he was diagnosed, Goldsmith was ordered by a superior 
officer to inform his sexual partners of his health status and to 
use methods, including condoms, to prevent their infection. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldsmith was convicted in 1994 of having unprotected sex with  
two women, willfully disobeying the ``safe-sex'' order while 
stationed at Lackland Air Force Base in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentenced to six years in prison, he retained his rank and  
military status even after being imprisoned at Fort Leavenworth, 
Kan. His ensuing appeal was rejected by an Air Force appellate 
court and his conviction became final. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldsmith was notified in late 1996 that the Air Force was  
seeking, under a federal law enacted earlier that year, to have the 
president drop him from its rolls. Such action, among other things, 
would strip him of health-care coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldsmith's shortened prison term expired in 1997, and he  
returned to duty status. He appealed the Air Force's attempt to 
drop him, and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces 
blocked such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	The military court ruled that the contemplated action carried  
``an associated stigma very akin to that involved in punishment,'' 
and therefore should be deemed punitive. Two punishments for the 
same offense violates the Fifth Amendment's protection against 
double jeopardy, the military court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court said the military court was wrong in  
ever ruling in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Executive action to drop ... (Goldsmith) from the rolls falls  
outside the ... (military court's) statutory jurisdiction,'' 
Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Clinton vs. Goldsmith, 98-347.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
