<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart, Mexico Co. Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. has settled with a  
Mexican grocery store chain for an amount less than the $624 
million already awarded by jurors, after losing a lawsuit filed by 
the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors had been scheduled to begin considering punitive damages  
today against Wal-Mart and its McLane Co. Inc. subsidiary. Wal-Mart 
said today the settlement would result in a charge to non-operating 
earnings in its second quarter of about three cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The company did not specify the exact amount of the settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	Valores Corp. of Monterrey, Mexico, had claimed McLane wouldn't  
honor a 25-year partnership agreement because Wal-Mart didn't want 
it to. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury on Friday found that Wal-Mart and McLane acted with  
malice in ignoring the 1991 pact. 
</P>
<P>
	Valores said it and McLane were to be 50-50 partners in a  
grocery distribution setup. 
</P>
<P>
	McLane is the nation's largest grocery distributor to  
convenience stores, with annual sales of $8 billion. Valores is 
Mexico's second-largest wholesale grocery distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	Valores said Wal-Mart ended the deal after hearing from Cifra,  
Mexico's largest retailer, which was planning its own deal with 
Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	After the trial in San Antonio -- McLane is based at Tyler, Texas  
-- the jury said Wal-Mart knowingly participated in McLane's not 
living up to its deal with Valores. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
