<DOCNO> APW19990517.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 11:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Four Reissues'' (Epic-Legacy) -- Stevie Ray Vaughan &AMP; Double  
Trouble 

</P>
<P>
	So you never purchased CDs of the Double Trouble band's four  
studio albums -- ``Texas Flood,'' ``Couldn't Stand the Weather,'' 
``Soul to Soul'' and ``In Step.'' Perhaps you love the old vinyl 
too much or you hoped for cleaner recordings or you have been 
chronically broke. Now your wait must end. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, you could hold out longer until Epic releases the SRV  
boxed set promised this year, but who knows what they are going to 
leave out? It is always better to have the album arrangements the 
performers sequenced for themselves, especially for someone like 
Stevie Ray, who never recorded a lame track. 
</P>
<P>
	To make these CD reissues irresistible, Epic added 14 new  
tracks, half of them live, totaling 77 minutes across the four 
discs. It's like creating a fifth album. 
</P>
<P>
	The added studio tracks were recorded in the same sessions with  
the original albums but never included. As for the bonus tracks 
that were recorded live, similar versions appear on SRV's live 
releases, but these bonus versions are fresh enough to be worth 
having. 
</P>
<P>
	And what bonuses! From the seductive ``Tin Pan Alley'' on the  
``Texas Flood'' reissue to the long-overdue appearance of a Hound 
Dog Taylor cover, ``Give Me Back My Wig,'' on ``Weather,'' they are 
all terrific. 
</P>
<P>
	Each disc contains brief interviews with Stevie that are  
distracting but at least demarcate where the bonus tracks begin. 
</P>
<P>
	No more excuses not to own all four discs because these were,  
and are, the best blues releases of the past two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Ralph Siegel, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the Spell'' (Alligator) -- Dave Hole  

</P>
<P>
	Australian fretmaster Dave Hole has unleashed his fifth and  
perhaps best compact disc for Alligator Records. On ``Under the 
Spell'' Hole tones down the guitar pyrotechnics a tad and unveils 
his most sophisticated songwriting. Don't worry. There's plenty of 
flying fingerwork from the slide man. But he also sings with more 
confidence. Where the hallmark of earlier Hole efforts was 
explosive slide-playing, ``Under the Spell'' combines writing, 
singing and playing into a more balanced package. The result 
actually makes you appreciate his spectacular playing even more. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Across the Winterline'' (Wind River) -- Jack Williams  

</P>
<P>
	Southern troubadour Jack Williams has been making music  
professionally for 40 years, covering a wide waterfront from jazz 
to rock to chamber music to country to completely original, which 
is what you'll find on his release for Wind River records. 
Williams' long career as a side and session guitarist attest to his 
six-string strengths. He also possesses a beautifully smooth voice 
and a pen dipped in the reality of everyday life. ``Moma Lou,'' 
Williams' ode to his mother and her cooking, is so tempting it 
could make a Yankee hungry. His examination of coming to terms with 
yourself, ``The Man in Me,'' is a song of unusually strong 
character. Williams calls it a ``stream of consciousness 
scrapbook.'' It's a true-running stream. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Lowdown and Up'' (Antone's Records) -- Toni Price  

</P>
<P>
	Texan singer Toni Price hasn't made her reputation as a crooner  
but she turns to what she calls ``smooth and silky'' for her fourth 
record for Antone's. ``Foolin' Around'' as done by Price is a great 
shuffle swing number. Her mid-range vocals slide around all the 
corners with nary a bump. Price even takes on ``Comes Love,'' done 
originally by Billie Holiday, and does the original justice with a 
style that again emphasizes swing. The fiddle of Johnny Gimble is 
no small part of that feat. Price fronts some fine playing 
throughout the recording, which holds true to her description. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 22:31:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Denny's To Revamp Restaurants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The Denny's restaurant chain plans to take  
its Grand Slam breakfast back to the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantica Restaurant Group Inc., Denny's parent company, said  
Monday it will spend more than $30 million this year to remodel 150 
restaurants in 50s-style diners with stainless steel exteriors, 
neon lights, rotating pie cases and jukeboxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to stay relevant with today's changing society you  
really do have to refresh your image on some consistent basis or 
you become really irrelevant,'' said John Romandetti, Denny's 
president and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Romandetti said the company eventually wants to convert all  
1,700 Denny's restaurants across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Clad in colorful bowling-style shirts, employees will serve  
similar items on the menu, with a few classic American additions 
such as chili, meatloaf, pot roast and open-face sandwiches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to change the image of a family-style restaurant  
that's open 24 hours a day because that really is our heritage,'' 
Romandetti said. ``Our restaurants right now are really fairly 
sedate and when you put a jukebox in there and you put some very 
bright colors in there you change the energy level of the interior 
very quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first Denny's Diner opened in North Myrtle Beach last  
summer. Other test markets have been in Florida and along the West 
Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Denny's has been repairing its image after several lawsuits  
filed in recent years alleged racial discrimination. In 1994, the 
chain paid $45.7 million to settle a discrimination lawsuit by 
black customers. Other suits are pending. Denny's employees now are 
required to undergo sensitivity training. 
</P>
<P>
	Romandetti said that the remodeling was overdue for many  
restaurants and that the timing has more to do with the company's 
improved financial situation than it's image. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision to remodel, if you will, or re-image the  
restaurant has been made simply because we have many markets where 
we haven't done remodels in 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartanburg-based company, which owns Denny's and other  
restaurant chains, emerged from bankruptcy protection last year 
with better financial structuring and the ability to remodel the 
restaurants, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Denny's probably needed some type of revamping because I don't  
think that it was attaining its potential,'' said Jerry Hirschberg, 
a S&AMP;P Ratings Services analyst. ``If this '50s diner works it will 
be very nice for them. I think the only problem that could surface 
in the future is that this could turn out to be more of a fad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the Denny's restaurants are company-owned. The  
franchise owners will be expected to follow suit with the company's 
changes, Romandetti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantica officials blamed an increase in operating costs at  
Denny's and another chain for a $61.7 million first-quarter loss. 
But analysts said the company has enough money in the bank to 
invest in the restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantica also owns the Carros, Coco's and El Pollo Loco  
restaurant brands, but the Denny's chain accounts for about 70 
percent of the company's consolidated revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantica stock closed up 3 1/8 cents, at $4.56 1/4 on the Nasdaq  
Stock Market Monday. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 07:52:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rhode Island Star Odom May Go Pro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- The University of Rhode Island is not  
counting on having Lamar Odom around next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island spokesman Mike Ballweg said he would ``bet money''  
the 6-foot-10 forward -- a probable lottery pick -- would declare for 
the June 30 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN, citing unidentified sources, reported that Odom will do  
just that. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA on Friday will announce its list of players applying for  
early entry to the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom's aunt told The Providence Journal he would formally  
announce his plans in Rhode Island today. 
</P>
<P>
	Basketball coach Jerry DeGregorio was unable to track down Odom  
last weekend to confirm his decision. The deadline for declaring 
for the draft was midnight Sunday, meaning Odom had to notify the 
NBA by then. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless he hires an agent, Odom can pull out of the draft as late  
as June 23 and return to college ball. Last year, Odom declared for 
the draft, then pulled out June 16 after he was admitted to Rhode 
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballweg said Odom returned home to New York last weekend,  
although a woman answering Odom's home phone said he was in Rhode 
Island. The spring semester ended Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility that Odom might leave Rhode Island has hurt the  
school's ability to recruit. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom led Rhode Island in scoring (17.6) and rebounding (9.4)  
last season. The Rams (20-13) lost to North Carolina-Charlotte in 
the first round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom has played just one season at Rhode Island, and the school  
took the unusual step of giving him a voice in the hiring of its 
coach after Jim Harrick left for Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom entered UNLV in 1997, but he was accused of cheating on a  
college entrance exam. He was upset by the accusations and chose to 
transfer. A UNLV assistant coach insists Odom did not cheat on the 
test. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 11:31:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up; Gold Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices were lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0668, down from $1.0712 Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Friday: 123.12 Japanese  
yen, up from 122.04; 1.5017 Swiss francs, up from 1.4944; and 
1.4609 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4590 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6181, down from $1.6222.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8334 German marks, up from 1.8258; 
6.1488 French francs, up from 6.1236; 2.0657 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0572; 1,815.03 Italian lire, up from 1,807.57 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $275.80 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$275.90 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $275.25, down from Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $0.45 in Hong Kong to close at $276.45.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.39 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.38. 
</P>
</TEXT>
