<DOCNO> APW19990517.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:43:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sonia Gandhi Quits Party Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sonia Gandhi, a main contender to be  
India's prime minister, stepped down as president of the Congress 
party Monday after several party leaders complained her Italian 
birth was a political liability. 
</P>
<P>
	But her resignation was immediately rejected by the party's  
highest decision-making body, the Congress Working Committee, and 
party leaders went to Mrs. Gandhi's house to beg her to reconsider. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of a youth wing of the Congress party began a hunger  
strike outside Mrs. Gandhi's sprawling New Delhi home, demanding 
she withdraw her resignation and that three critics of her 
candidacy be removed from the party. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation came a day after three senior Congress party  
leaders -- Sharad Pawar, Purno Sangma and Tariq Anwar -- said India 
should have a native-born leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi was born in Italy but became a citizen after she  
married into India's foremost political dynasty. She joined active 
politics only last year, seven years after her husband, former 
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, was assassinated during the 1991 
election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``My colleagues expressed views to the effect that my having  
been born elsewhere is a liability to the Congress Party,'' Mrs. 
Gandhi said in her resignation letter. ``I am pained by their lack 
of confidence in my ability to act in the best interests of the 
party and the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, minor scuffles broke out in Bombay between  
factions for and against Mrs. Gandhi. Posters were torn at the 
party's regional office and a sign torn down. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi was expected to be the Congress party candidate in  
elections later this year. She joined active politics last year, 
seven years after her husband, former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, 
was assassinated during the 1991 election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter published Sunday, the three dissenting Congress  
party leaders said a candidate for prime minister should have a 
``track record in public life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not possible that a country of 980 million people, with  
a wealth of education, competence and ability, can have anyone 
other than an Indian, born of Indian soil, to head its 
government,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages and statements of support came in from regional  
leaders. Discussions reportedly were under way about the possible 
expulsion of the three rebels from the party. 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis in the party comes less than a month after Mrs.  
Gandhi failed to win the support of enough lawmakers to put 
together a coalition to succeed Prime Minister Atal Bihari 
Vajpayee's government after it lost a confidence vote in 
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:43:09 </DATE_TIME>
