<DOCNO> APW19990517.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 01:11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One Basket, Handful of 2nd Chances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Almost 18 months after choking his last coach, Latrell Sprewell  
helped resuscitate the career of his latest one. Everybody's life 
should be as full of second chances as Sprewell's and the rest of 
the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Patrick Ewing who did most of the hardest work and Allan  
Houston who made the shot Sunday that lifted the Knicks to a 78-77 
win over Miami in the fifth and final game of their first-round 
playoff series. But it was Sprewell who kept New York from getting 
blown out early by scoring five points in his first seven minutes 
off the bench. And it was Sprewell who kept New York from getting 
run over late, too, by poking the ball loose from the Heat's Tim 
Hardaway with 20 seconds left to set up the last-gasp heroics. 
</P>
<P>
	And, yes, that was Sprewell, too, who was so intent on  
remembering how good it felt to win that he started celebrating too 
soon, forgetting there was 0.8 seconds left to play after Houston's 
14-foot jumper hit iron, then glass and, finally, the bottom of the 
net. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been in a situation like this, so when I saw that  
go in, we were all just running around and jumping and hollering,'' 
Sprewell said. ``I actually thought the game was over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon enough, though, it was. But the question lingers: Who  
redeems the team next? 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jeff Van Gundy has a job for as long as New York's run  
through the postseason extends. But in a nice twist of fate, the 
length of that run may depend on how well the guys foisted on Van 
Gundy by the front office -- Sprewell, Marcus Camby and Kurt Thomas 
-- play for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a lot of people who watched Michael Jordan exit stage left,  
the Knicks figured they were as close to the head of the 
championship line as anybody else. But unlike the Jazz and Indiana 
Pacers, the Knicks were willing to cut up a veteran team, reshuffle 
the deck and play the cards as they fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell figured to be a bad fit, coming to town with a  
reputation for selfishness and off a long suspension following his 
attack on coach P.J. Carlesimo at Golden State. But the deal that 
caused most of the trouble was the one that shipped longtime local 
hero Charles Oakley to Toronto for Camby. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy relied on Oakley and John Starks the same way he  
relied on Ewing since succeeding Miami's Pat Riley as head coach in 
New York. Then Knicks president and general manager Ernie Grunfeld 
stepped in, sent Oakley and Starks packing, and replaced them with 
players Van Gundy hadn't asked for. There were new cliques, but 
familiar arguments about playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	Things came to a head with the season winding down and the  
Raptors in town. With the game on the line, Oakley boxed out Camby 
and grabbed the decisive rebound in a win that pushed New York two 
places out of the eighth and last playoff spot in the Eastern 
Conference. It became such a convenient snapshot of a season that 
was fast slipping away that Dave Checketts, the Madison Square 
Garden president, took Grunfeld to dinner and then told him he was 
no longer running the ballclub. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks went on a late run, grabbed the last playoff spot and  
all the incentive they could have hoped for in Miami as a 
first-round opponent. It was the third season in a row the two were 
paired and it ended for once, without a single brawl. But that's 
not to say emotions didn't run high. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley has been the Garden's favorite villain since his escape  
from New York, but this time the deciding game was less about the 
coaches than the players. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing has looked old most of the season and played ever older  
amid whispers that he spent too much time fronting for the players 
union during the labor dispute. And though he slows down the New 
York attack more than ever, limiting the effectiveness of quick, 
slashing players like Houston, Sprewell and Camby, Van Gundy still 
insists on running the offense through Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	Remarkably, though everyone knew what was coming, it worked one  
more time. Ewing was never better, though battered and bruised time 
and again. He delivered 22 points and 11 rebounds and played the 
big moments as well as he ever had. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more remarkable, Sprewell and Camby finally absorbed the  
lesson Van Gundy had been pushing, crafted their own games to 
complement Ewing's. And then Houston, brought to New York three 
years ago to help ease the burden on Ewing, did just that with his 
runner down the lane. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still don't think about Jeff's job or where we're going to  
be,'' he said. We're thinking about advancing in the next round 
right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
