<HEADLINE> Hernandez Case Goes to Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Arbitrator Richard Bloch heard testimony from  
four witnesses Monday in the grievance case for Xavier Hernandez, 
whose $2.7 million, two-year contract with Baltimore was voided 
this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing, which was brought by the players association, will  
continue with additional testimony Tuesday. After that, the two 
sides will set a date to file briefs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles voided Hernandez's contract after saying the  
33-year-old right-hander flunked a physical. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, 6-6 with one save and a 3.57 ERA last year, is  
seeking $2.45 million, the difference between his deal with the 
Orioles and one he signed later with the Houston Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	Xavier was eventually released by Houston in March and signed a  
minor league contract with the New York Mets last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez agreed to his deal with Baltimore on Dec. 17, getting  
a contract that called for $1.2 million this year and $1.25 million 
in 2000. The Orioles had a $1.5 million option for 2001 with a 
$250,000 buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloch is hearing the case as an interim arbitrator. Players and  
owners are searching for a new arbitrator to replace Cornell 
professor Dana Eischen, who was hired in December 1997 but quit 
after ruling in May against J.D. Drew's grievance seeking free 
agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
