<HEADLINE> Cubs Reveal Beck Has Bone Spur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Chicago Cubs reliever Rod Beck has a bone spur in  
his pitching elbow, but manager Jim Riggleman said Monday it's an 
old injury and he isn't sure whether it's the reason for Beck's 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've known about it from the day we signed him,'' Riggleman  
said on his radio show before the Cubs played the Florida Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	If so, the ailment didn't keep Beck from saving 51 games in 58  
chances last season as the Cubs earned the NL wild-card playoff 
berth. But things have been far different this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Beck (2-4) is tied for fifth in the NL with seven saves,  
he's blown four chances, has a 10.54 ERA and opposing hitters are 
batting .438 against him. That has cost him the closer's job, 
though Riggleman hasn't designated a replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck was booed off the mound in his last outing after retiring  
just one of four Atlanta batters Sunday. He gave up two runs, two 
hits and a walk, turning a 6-5 Cubs deficit into an 8-5 hole. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how to pitch, and there's no pain there,'' Beck said  
after the Cubs beat Florida 8-1. ``There's still no pain. But my 
arm isn't allowing me to do the things I'm capable of doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander also acknowledged the elbow created problems  
against the Braves saying, the spur ``sometimes got in the wrong 
place and locked up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surgery probably is inevitable, but Beck still hopes to postpone  
it until after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I do it now, I might get back around the middle of  
August,'' he said. ``But being as stubborn as I am, I want to 
contribute to this ballclub. Right now I want to explore all the 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the Cubs have no plans to place Beck on the disabled  
list. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll treat it day-to-day and see how it feels,'' general  
manager Ed Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Riggleman said he's stumped about what has caused the  
eight-year veteran to lose his touch. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make sure he's telling us exactly how he feels,''  
Riggleman said. ``His sinker and forkball just aren't working.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
