<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cicadas Return to Four-State Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Few people are salivating to meet the  
periodical cicada like Craig Vance: He plans to fry the 
black-bodied, red-eyed insects and offer them to guests as a dinner 
appetizer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having an exoskeleton, it would be like eating a crab,'' said  
the 49-year-old post office employee from Peninsula, near Akron. 
</P>
<P>
	Before you say no thanks, remember this: the flying insect about  
the size of a thumb appears only once every 17 years. In fact, 
Vance has never eaten one before -- though insect specialist David 
Shetlar has. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are actually sweet. I kind of thought they had a nutty  
flavor,'' said Shetlar, a professor at Ohio State University. 
</P>
<P>
	In the coming weeks, cicadas in eastern Ohio, most of West  
Virginia and parts of Pennsylvania and Virginia will end a long 
routine of chewing sap from underground roots. 
</P>
<P>
	They will emerge from the ground, wriggle out of their shells  
and fly about in noisy swarms. They'll mate, lay eggs in slits they 
cut into twigs and then die, all within a matter of weeks. When the 
young hatch, they fall to the ground and burrow into the soil. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like an eclipse or a Halley's Comet. It's an  
event,'' said Debbie Wadden, 41, a stay-at-home mother who 
volunteers to teach classes about insects. The cicadas will be the 
stars of her presentation. 
</P>
<P>
	Naturalist Mike Greene said some people will be turned off by  
the huge numbers of cicadas and the abandoned shells that litter 
the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	And then there's the noise by males doing their mating routine.  
``It gets quite overwhelming,'' even disrupting some people's 
sleep, said Wendy Weirich, a naturalist with the Cleveland 
Metroparks. 
</P>
<P>
	Females are silent.  
</P>
<P>
	``The females are flying around and the males are making big  
noise looking for a date,'' Weirich said. ``I know it doesn't sound 
comforting, but they are not going to sting you. They are not going 
to bite you. They don't care about you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are five mating sounds, most like ``whirr ... whirr ...  
faroo,'' said John Baniecki, an entomology professor at West 
Virginia University. ``They mean something to the female.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Debra Shankland remembers the huge numbers of cicadas in 1982,  
when she saw the insects on trips home from school. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'd stop at a rest stop and it was so thick with them you  
would be stepping all over them,'' said Shankland, now a Cleveland 
Metroparks naturalist in suburban Garfield Heights. 
</P>
<P>
	Cicadas don't harm people but can damage newly planted trees  
when they lay eggs. Mature trees usually aren't affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Periodical cicadas are divided into about 20 groups known as  
broods and emerge on different 17-year schedules in different 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	A brood is due in 2000 in Georgia, with more broods in 2001 in  
Louisiana, Mississippi and New York, and different Ohio broods in 
2002 and 2004. There are also the less concentrated and less noisy 
non-periodical cicadas seen each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
