<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 59.85 to 10,853.47 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed Monday as investors  
debated whether a new hint of inflation will prompt the nation's 
economic policymakers to raise interest rates when they meet on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 59.85 to close at  
10,853.47. The blue chips had fallen as much as 167 points earlier 
in the session before regaining ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, which were lower for most of the day,  
posted scattered gains. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 1.69 
to close at 1,339.49 and the Nasdaq composite index advanced 33.98 
to 2,561.84, but declining issues outdistanced advancers on the New 
York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of the day, traders extended Friday's broad selloff, in  
which the Dow fell 193.87 points. That decline followed a 
steeper-than-expected increase in the consumer price index that fed 
worries about rising inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The jump in the CPI also raised expectations that the Federal  
Reserve will consider boosting interest rates when its Open Market 
Committee meets Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is paying respects to the FOMC today,'' said Alfred  
E. Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in 
St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Many cautious traders appeared willing to wait on the sidelines  
all day, as volume was well behind Friday's pace. But as the market 
fell and prices looked more attractive, some began looking for 
bargains. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a strange day and a half in the market,''  
said Charles White, portfolio manager at Avatar Associates. ``It's 
hard to convince people to put money to work in front of word from 
the Fed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, White and other analysts said they expect the Fed to  
ultimately leave rates untouched Tuesday, instead announcing a 
``tightening bias,'' which would indicate that the group may raise 
rates at a future meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed tightens rates when central bankers believe the economy  
is growing too fast. Higher interest rates raise corporate 
borrowing rates, which can often hurt profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The lingering concern over interest rates hammered banking and  
financial stocks for a second straight session. Rising rates are a 
particular threat to banks as companies become more reluctant to 
take out loans. Citigroup, a component of the Dow, dropped 1 to 70, 
and J.P. Morgan tumbled 4 to 136 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of inflation has rattled the bond market in recent  
sessions, pushing yields to their highest levels in nearly a year. 
On Monday, prices bounced back slightly, lowering the yield of the 
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond to 5.89 percent from 5.92 percent 
last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	As Fed watchers settled down and bond yields returned to lower  
levels, some traders turned their attention to a new batch of 
corporate earnings reports. Hewlett-Packard rose 4 9/16 to 88 3/4 and 
then rewarded investors with an after-hours earnings report that 
surpassed analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer, which typically sets the standard for computer  
makers, rose 2 1/16 to 43 1/4 in advance of its earnings announcement, 
scheduled for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw some indications that there's no big slowdown in the  
technology companies,'' White said. 
</P>
<P>
	Big mergers influenced trading in individual stocks. After  
former Baby Bell U S West and telecommunications company Global 
Crossing announced they would merge, the stocks of both companies 
fell as investors appeared uncertain of the benefits to be gained. 
U S West fell 4 to 58 1/4 on the NYSE, while Global Crossing slipped 
1 1/8 to close at 60 1/4 on the Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	Wyman Gordon was the biggest percentage gainer on the Big Board  
after Precision Castparts Corp. agreed to acquire it for about $721 
million, gaining 5 11/16 to close at 18 15/16. And Gulfstream 
Aerospace got a big boost from its intended merger with defense 
giant General Dynamics, rising 6 1/16 to 61 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 1.53 to 636.92, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite fell 3.87 to 784.94. The Russell 2000 
index, reflecting the performance of small-company stocks, fell 
1.78 to 441.35. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets were lower Monday, taking cues from Friday's  
losses on Wall Street. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell nearly 2 
percent. Germany's DAX index closed 1.6 percent lower, Britain's 
FT-SE 100 was down 2.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed down 1.7 
percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
