<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kings Now an Entertaining Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- When the Sacramento Kings gathered at  
the end of the NBA lockout, new coach Rick Adelman must have been 
wondering what he had inherited. 
</P>
<P>
	The team had no center, an unhappy power forward and a rookie  
point guard who'd gotten thrown off his college team. On top of 
that, the Kings had endured an NBA-record 15 straight losing 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	But, within hours, everything had changed.  
</P>
<P>
	Vlade Divac was signed as a free agent and took over at center.  
Chris Webber, a day late in reporting, showed up and became the 
team's leading scorer and rebounder. And one glimpse at Jason 
Williams' court wizardry showed the Kings were about to develop a 
new personality. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings coalesced into a winner, and one of the most  
entertaining teams in the NBA. Sacramento led the league in 
scoring, being the only team to average more than 100 points per 
game, and was worst in the league in defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some of the Kings were amazed at their quick turnaround.  
</P>
<P>
	``People are aware that something is happening here,'' guard  
Tariq Abdul-Wahad said late in the season. ``Everybody was looking 
toward next year, but things worked out and the time is now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the season's first five weeks, they seemed like the  
Sacramento Kings of old. 
</P>
<P>
	They became the first team to lose to the hapless Los Angeles  
Clippers this season on March 11, and a loss at home to Minnesota 
the following night -- during which Webber became so furious at the 
team's lackluster play that he loudly berated his teammates on the 
bench during a timeout -- left them at 9-12. 
</P>
<P>
	They responded by beating the streaking Los Angeles Lakers, and  
started showing promise. They were still only 17-22 April 15, 
though, following a last-second overtime loss to the Seattle 
SuperSonics. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when the Kings turned their season around. They won 10 of  
their final 11 games to clinch only their second playoff spot in 13 
seasons, and barely missed ousting Utah in the first round of the 
playoffs -- a five-game series that included two overtime games and 
another contest decided in the final second of regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the playoffs, the Kings played the type of physical, intense  
defense they had ignored throughout the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we put away the title of the Showtime Team,''  
Webber said. ``I hope that we showed substance to this team besides 
just Jason's flash or an occasional growl from me. I just hope 
people see that comes from the hard work that we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings got valuable contributions from reserves Vernon  
Maxwell, Jon Barry and Predrag Stojakovic, all three of whom hit 
key 3-pointers in various games, but the key to Sacramento's 
success was the play of Divac, Williams and Webber. 
</P>
<P>
	Divac, despite getting little sleep the final month of the  
season while worrying about his parents and brother in Yugoslavia, 
became the team's emotional leader and averaged a double-double for 
the season with 14 points and 10 rebounds per game. His previous 
playoff experience also was important on an inexperienced team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We showed the world that a champion is coming,'' he said.  
``This team is young, and it can go far. Before the season, we were 
thinking about making the playoffs, and now we are thinking to go 
farther. In some ways I am disappointed, but it was a hell of a 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was spectacular at times with his no-look passes, Pete  
Maravich-like dribbling tricks and long 3-pointers, but terribly 
inconsistent. He was at his best against top point guards like 
Jason Kidd and John Stockton, but often disappeared against teams 
like Vancouver and the Clippers. 
</P>
<P>
	And Webber, with 20 points and 13 rebounds per game during the  
regular season, became the first non-center with such gaudy 
statistics since Charles Barkley in 1986-87. He also won the NBA's 
rebounding title. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps even more importantly, Webber found some peace in  
Sacramento after five tumultuous years at Golden State and 
Washington. Though he is not yet ready to make a long-term 
commitment to the Kings, he is far from the unhappy player of three 
months ago who considered his trade from Washington to Sacramento 
as a punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy I was here to play with this group of guys,'' he  
said. ``It's been a joy to play with them, from the players to the 
coaches. I don't have any regrets about being here this year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
