<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Oil Spill Damage Minimal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROSARITO, Mexico (AP) -- An oil spill off Mexico killed four sea  
birds but caused no major ecological damage on the United States' 
side of the border, the U.S. Coast Guard said. 
</P>
<P>
	A fuel transfer between a Chevron-owned tanker and an onshore  
facility led to a spill Thursday of an estimated 110,000 gallons of 
oil, fouling the beaches of Mexico's Baja California. 
</P>
<P>
	A slick had been moving south Saturday, but the Coast Guard  
didn't see any traces of oil along the shoreline or in the water on 
Sunday. Two assessment teams surveyed the shoreline and reported no 
major environmental impact, Coast Guard Lt. Jean Donaldson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tar balls washed ashore in San Diego County, Calif., and two  
oil-soaked birds were discovered Saturday on a beach on Coronado 
Island, Calif. SeaWorld in San Diego took in the birds, along with 
two others found elsewhere, but was unable to save them, Donaldson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The extent of the damage south of the U.S.-Mexico border was not  
immediately determined. 
</P>
<P>
	A joint team of experts was continuing to monitor California  
shoreline in the San Diego area. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
