<DOCNO> APW19990517.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 05:41:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises, Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Investors snapped up dollars today on expectations  
of a widening gap between U.S. and Japanese bond yields, pushing 
the greenback to a two-month high against the yen. Tokyo stocks 
fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 123.14 yen in late trading, up 0.96 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
122.73 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 389.37 points,  
or 2.32 percent, to close the day's trading at 16,421.02 points. On 
Friday, the average closed down 40.86 points, or 0.24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar began its rise after Japan's  
Finance Ministry reported that the March current account surplus -- 
Japan's broadest measure of trade -- fell 25.5 percent to $8.76 
billion from the same month last year. 
</P>
<P>
	After the figures were released, the dollar jumped to 123.36  
yen, its highest level since March 5, when it touched a high of 
123.58 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	But market players said the news had little direct impact on  
currency markets. Instead, they attributed the dollar's rise to a 
slew of factors that pointed to further gains ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of the list are expectations that interest rate  
differentials between the U.S. and Japan are set to widen further, 
in light of stronger-than-expected U.S. inflation data Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback's strength also followed remarks by U.S. Treasury  
Secretary-designate Lawrence Summers, who reiterated on Sunday that 
a strong dollar is in his country's national interest, augmenting 
lower inflation and trade income. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged from 122.82 to 123.40 yen in today's trading.  
The euro was traded at 131.27 yen, up from 130.33 yen late Friday 
in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices fell sharply after fears of  
higher U.S. interest rates led to a big drop Friday on Wall Street, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow fell 193.87 points to 10,913.32, erasing a  
106.82-point gain Thursday, after data showing a 0.7 percent 
increase in consumer prices caused bond yields to rise and sparked 
fears that the U.S. Federal Reserve might change its monetary 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo shares prices were lower across the board, with major  
exporters also racking up losses despite the sharp gains of the 
dollar against the yen, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong U.S. dollar usually pushes shares in exporters higher  
on hopes that their products will become cheaper overseas and that 
their repatriated earnings will rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market seems to be saying it wants additional measures to  
stimulate the economy,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of 
the stock division at Tokyo Securities, referring to recent 
speculation that the Japanese government may up spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo today, an estimated 578.06 million shares changed hands  
on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 728.03 
million shares Friday. Decliners outnumbered advancers 1,064 to 
176, while 72 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 25.02 points, or 1.9 percent, to 1,322.43. 
The TOPIX closed down 4.52 points, or 0.33 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond was unchanged from Friday's close of 1.230 percent, priced at 
102.42 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
