<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Air, Attendants Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines has reached a tentative  
agreement with its flight attendants' union, which is touting the 
deal as a new standard for the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise Hedges, president of the Association of Professional  
Flight Attendants, said the contract provides pay increases, 
improvements in retirement and increased scheduling flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
	AMR Corp., the airline's parent company, and the APFA, which  
represents 20,000 members, did not further disclose details of the 
plan, reached Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	If it does indeed set a new standard, that would be welcome news  
for flight attendants working to amend contracts at Aloha and 
Northwest airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	For American, there were no public disputes during negotiations,  
unlike the last round in 1993 when the flight attendants struck the 
airline for five days and virtually shut down American's 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The contentious strike six years ago was part of the reason why  
negotiations went so well this time around, according to Sue 
Oliver, vice president of employee relations and chief negotiator 
for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both parties recognized this was not what we wanted to see in  
the future,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	This time the company and union asked for informal help from the  
National Mediation Board before tempers flared. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants' contract became amendable last November.  
Now, the six-year tentative agreement will be subject to the APFA's 
ratification process. First, the union officers will review and 
vote on the pact. If they approve, the agreement will be sent to 
all members by mail. A simple majority of returned ballots is 
necessary for the deal to pass. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second agreement between APFA and AMR this year.  
Last month, the flight attendants union and American reached an 
understanding on how to integrate flight attendants from Reno Air, 
which AMR purchased last December. 
</P>
<P>
	The smooth negotiations with flight attendants have been good  
news for AMR, which has been hit this year with a couple of public 
relations disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, a dispute between the Allied Pilots Association and  
American reached a boiling point over the Reno. That disagreement 
led to a massive sickout that caused the cancellation of nearly 
6,700 flights and contempt damages of $45 million to be paid to AMR 
by APA and its two top officers. The airline said the job action 
has cost it $140 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Justice Department sued American for allegedly  
trying to quash competition at its Dallas-Forth Worth hub, the 
first predatory pricing case since the government deregulated the 
industry in 1978. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
