<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford To Meet Calif. Air Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. pickup trucks sold  
throughout the United States and Canada will begin meeting 
California's tougher emission standards in the 2000 model year, the 
No. 2 automaker announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move follows Ford's decision last year to make all its sport  
utility vehicles and Windstar minivans meet the so-called Low 
Emission Vehicle, or LEV, standards starting with the '99 models. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford officials said the move was not in response to the federal  
government's recent decision to require more stringent emission 
levels to be phased in starting in 2004. But Ford said some of its 
2000 trucks will exceed the government's proposed initial 
requirements for 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	President Jac Nasser would not say how much the move would cost,  
but said the technology was affordable and would not result in 
higher sticker prices. 
</P>
<P>
	All F-series pickups will begin meeting the LEV standard with  
2000 models, which go on sale in the fall. The compact Ranger line 
will meet the standards in the 2001 model year. The F-series is the 
best-selling vehicle in the United States, with more than 800,000 
sold annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its trucks that meet the LEV standards will emit from  
15 percent to more than 50 percent fewer smog-forming emissions 
than conventional trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	When the conversion is completed, a maximum of about 2 million  
Ford trucks a year will meet the lower standards. Ford said the 
result would be equivalent to eliminating all smog-producing 
emissions from 350,000 full-size pickups. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has been able to meet the LEV standards cost-effectively  
because its new family of engines permit newer catalytic convertor 
technology to be used, said Kelly Brown, director of vehicle 
engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has been aggressively promoting its environmental  
consciousness since Nasser and new Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. 
took over leadership of the automaker in January. At the same time, 
the company has been criticized by some environmental groups for 
its heavy focus on pickups and SUVs, which generally pollute more 
than cars and use more fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not an action to appease any fringe environmental  
groups,'' Nasser said after Monday's announcement. ``This is an 
action we truly believe has goodness in it in terms of impact on 
clean air. That's what drives us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, none of Ford's cars sold outside California meet the LEV  
standard. Nasser indicated that LEV cars will be added to Ford's 
lineup as model changeovers occur. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda Motor Co. began selling its four-cylinder Accord sedan  
that meets the LEV standard nationwide last year. 
</P>
<P>
	California is in the process of phasing in the tougher  
standards, which differ for cars and trucks and vary based on the 
vehicle's weight. Automakers also are working with the U.S. 
Environmental Protection Agency to meet voluntary national LEV 
standards starting in 2001, but there are no such national 
standards set for pickups. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
