<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Siemens Profits Increase 17 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- German industrial giant Siemens on Monday  
reported a 17 percent increase in both net profits and sales for 
the first half of the fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales grew to 61.2 billion marks ($34 billion) and profits after  
taxes grew to 1.39 billion marks ($772 million), following 
stronger-than-expected first-quarter earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had predicting that growth would ebb toward the end of  
the half of the fiscal year, but Siemens' earnings increased even 
more in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers cautioned that heavy invoicing exaggerated the  
improvements. Siemens said it expects the effects of the billing of 
major contracts in the first half to normalize in the course of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half new orders grew 10 percent to 65.3 billion marks ($36  
billion) 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Heinrich von Pierer said he expects growth to stabilize  
at that level in the course of the year. ``Overall, we're on the 
right track,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
