<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 06:42:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Air Faces New Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- The Philippine government has imposed a Sunday  
deadline for the troubled owner of Philippine Airlines to put up 
$200 million in capital and bring in new management, a senior 
government minister said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	If Lucio Tan, who has a 70 percent stake in the flagship  
carrier, misses the deadline, the government will look at other 
options, including allowing outside investors to set up a new 
airline, said Secretary of Trade and Industry Jose Pardo. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials are talking with three investors interested in taking  
over PAL, Pardo told Dow Jones Newswires on the sidelines of an 
international business conference in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	They include a group from the Middle East, a fund group with a  
regional headquarters in Singapore which already has investments in 
airlines and a group based in Asia, Pardo said. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the new deadline comes as Tan faces pressure to give up  
management control of PAL, Asia's oldest carrier. The airline's 
largest U.S. creditor, the U.S. Export-Import Bank, has lobbied to 
oust Tan from management and is moving to repossess four planes PAL 
uses for long-haul flights. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL has been unable to pay $2.2 billion in debts incurred  
largely in an ambitious but ill-timed fleet modernization program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
