<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Suffers Veto Override </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Jesse Ventura was unable to twist the arm  
of the Legislature on Monday, becoming the first governor in 17 
years to have a veto overridden. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota lawmakers overrode Gov. Ventura's veto Monday when the  
House passed a bill 109-19 that allows accident victims to sue over 
defective seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate overrode Ventura's veto of the bill two weeks ago.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was not allowed to have my day in court. Now I finally  
will,'' said Jodi-Michaelle Carlson, a quadriplegic who had waited 
in her wheelchair outside the House chamber, urging action. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislative overrides of vetoes are rare. Only five have  
occurred since 1939, including Monday's. Ventura's predecessor, 
Gov. Arne Carlson, set a record for vetoes, but none were 
overridden. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, a Reform Party member and former pro wrestler who  
promised during his campaign to muscle opponents into submission, 
said the bill unfairly aided one side. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, he accepted defeat.  
</P>
<P>
	``We respect the right of the Legislature to override,''  
Ventura's spokesman John Wodele said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
