<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 10:23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justices To Rule On Nude Dancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide how  
far governments can go in banning nude dancing in barrooms, a case 
that may clarify the line between protected expression and unlawful 
lewd behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear Erie, Pa., officials' effort to  
reinstate an ordinance that bans appearing in ``a state of nudity'' 
in public places. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials say a Pennsylvania court that invalidated the  
ordinance disregarded a 1991 Supreme Court decision that upheld a 
similar public-decency law in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	In that ruling, the justices allowed states and local  
governments to ban erotic entertainers from appearing totally nude 
in barrooms and other adults-only establishments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Erie ordinance, enacted in 1994, in effect required erotic  
dancers to wear at least pasties and a G-string. It was challenged 
in court by Pap's A.M., owner of a nude dancing establishment 
called Kandyland. 
</P>
<P>
	An Erie County court ruled the measure unconstitutional, but an  
appeals court reversed and reinstated the ordinance. But the 
Pennsylvania Supreme Court again threw out the ordinance last 
October, saying it unconstitutionally burdened free expression. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said the Supreme Court's 1991 decision in the Indiana  
case was a ``hodgepodge of opinions'' and established no clear 
precedent. Therefore, the Pennsylvania made its own analysis based 
largely on the dissent in the 1991 Supreme Court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are several ways to combat these social ills'' such as  
rape and prostitution ``without banning the expressive activity of 
nude dancing,'' the state court said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Erie's lawyers accused the state  
court of ``knowingly disregarding the precedent'' in the Supreme 
Court's 1991 ruling that upheld the Indiana ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyers for Pap's A.M. said the Pennsylvania court did not  
ignore the 1991 ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Erie vs. Pap's A.M., 98-1161.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
