<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Telecom Boss Hopeful on Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom chairman Ron Sommer  
expressed continued optimism Monday that his company's planned $80 
billion merger with Telecom Italia would go through despite the 
Italian government's reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian officials from the prime minister on down have expressed  
hope that Telecom Italia, a former state-owned monopoly, will 
remain in Italian hands, and have pressed the German government to 
cut the 72 percent stake it still holds in Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	Sommer told reporters Monday that he considered those concerns  
to be surmountable, adding he was ``very certain that (the merger) 
would not fail due to politics.'' He said he also did not expect a 
hostile bid by Olivetti SpA for Telecom Italia to succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	He said, however, that several months would be needed to resolve  
many questions before the plan could be presented to shareholders 
of both companies for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $65 billion for Telecom Italia in a tender  
offer that ends Friday. If successful, it would be the largest 
hostile corporate takeover in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the International Herald Tribune reported Monday  
that Olivetti's hostile takeover bid for Telecom Italia is secretly 
supported by some members of the Italian government, quoting 
Olivetti's honorary chairman and former leading shareholder. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlo De Benedetti makes the claim in an autobiographical book,  
excerpts of which were published Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	De Benedetti cited Pierluigi Bersani, Italy's industry minister,  
as one government member backing the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bersani insisted that the Italian government will remain  
neutral in any takeover battle for Telecom Italia and called the 
report ``false and a little ridiculous,'' his press office said 
Monday. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
