<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Dole May Donate to McCain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talk about marital loyalty.  
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Bob Dole says he is considering giving money to Sen.  
John McCain's presidential campaign, never mind that his wife, 
Elizabeth Dole, also is seeking the Republican nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``McCain's my friend. And he's not raising the money that (Texas  
Gov.) George Bush is. I think we need to keep good people in the 
race,'' Dole said in an interview published Monday in The New York 
Times. ``So I've thought about ways to help McCain in particular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But before writing a check, the three-time presidential  
candidate said, ``I think I'd check with Elizabeth first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to Bob Dole for comment was not immediately returned.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole's spokesman, Ari Fleischer, joked, ``We just made our  
first down payment at the lumberyard for the woodshed we are 
building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, a senator from Arizona, is an announced candidate for  
the GOP presidential nomination in 2000. Bush and Mrs. Dole are 
exploring whether to formally enter the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sort of leaning that she'll do it,'' said Dole. ``If  
there's no response out there, or if it looks impossible, this is 
not her whole life. If she can't raise the money, obviously it's 
pretty hard to be a candidate.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
