<DOCNO> APW19990517.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 15:11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms hit from Minnesota to Texas today, while  
the Northeast had partly cloudy skies and Northwest was rainy. 
</P>
<P>
	With low pressure over Wisconsin, rain and thunderstorms were  
seen from southern Minnesota and Iowa east into Wisconsin and 
Illinois. The most intense thunderstorms were pushing through 
northeastern Illinois and southeastern Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms were not severe, but were likely to produce winds up  
to 50 mph and small hail in the Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Other showers and thunderstorms were found along and ahead of  
the cold front in north-central Texas. The strongest storms were 
seen from Missouri south and west through eastern Oklahoma into 
northern Texas, where two counties had quarter-size hail. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure over the mid-Atlantic provided fair, dry and  
tranquil weather to most areas along the East Coast. Sky conditions 
ranged from clear to partly cloudy over the Northeast and 
Appalachians, to partly to mostly cloudy over eastern parts of the 
Carolinas and Florida. Thunderstorms were developing off of the 
Southeast coast. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure over the Rockies brought cooler and drier weather  
to most of the northern and central Plains. Skies were mostly 
cloudy over parts of Nebraska and Kansas, but the sun broke through 
over the Dakotas. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry weather was seen over the Rockies and Southwest.  
Showers fell over the Northwest but most of the showers were 
confined to eastern parts of Washington and Oregon, as well as 
northern and central Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon, temperatures in the continental United States  
ranged from 19 in Yellowston, Wyo., to 89 in Jacksonville, Fla. The 
highest heat index was 96 in Kingsville, Texas, and the lowest wind 
chill was 8 in Cheyenne, Wyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
