<HEADLINE> Microsoft Plays Host to CEO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- More than 100 titans of U.S. industry -- among  
them investment guru Warren Buffet, Disney Chief Executive Officer 
Michael Eisner and homemaking entrepreneur Martha Stewart -- will 
converge on Seattle this week for the Microsoft CEO Summit. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the third year the software giant has hosted the gathering,  
which attendees say provides them with a rare opportunity to talk 
casually and catch up on the rapidly changing world of computers, 
software and the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``They see us as leading or participating in many of the  
technology trends ... sort of a technology `crystal ball,''' said 
Microsoft group vice president Jeff Raikes, who helps organize the 
event and run the company's $14 billion sales operations. ``We are 
a magnet for the business thinkers who want to engage in the 
dialogue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the three-day summit will take place on the Microsoft  
campus, though it kicks off in downtown Seattle Tuesday night with 
a reception at the Four Seasons Olympic Hotel. Wednesday night, 
there's a dinner party at Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates' $60 
million mansion on the shores of Lake Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of gatherings share the prestige of the Microsoft  
summit. 
</P>
<P>
	Every July, someish and talk shop. Their host is New York  
investment banker Herb Allen -- a key power broker in the 
entertainment industry. Gates, Eisner, Buffet and media moguls 
Rupert Murdoch and Barry Diller are regulars there. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the same set jets to Aspen, Colo., every September at  
the invitation of financier Teddy Forstmann. Sun Microsystems CEO 
Scott McNealy and America Online boss Steve Case have been among 
those who have hiked in the Rockies or been treated to a live 
performance from James Taylor there. 
</P>
<P>
	And every February, techno-showman Richard Wurman convenes  
``technology, entertainment and design'' gatherings -- for a fee -- 
in Monterey, Calif., aimed at introducing attendees to new ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	Raikes would not give details of this year's event, which also  
includes Dell Computer founder Michael Dell, Ford Motor CEO Jacques 
Nassau, and Coca Cola Enterprises' boss Henry Schimburg on the 
guest list. Local businessmen invited include Jeff Bezos, chairman 
of Amazon.com, Howard Schultz, the head of Starbucks, and cellular 
phone pioneer Craig McCaw. 

</P>
</TEXT>
