<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to decide, sometime in 2000, whether states can sell  
personal information from driver's license records such as people's 
addresses and Social Security numbers. The Clinton administration 
wants the court to uphold a federal law, the Driver's Privacy 
Protection Act of 1994, that closes such records to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	--Made it harder for federal judges to invalidate election  
districts drawn by state legislatures just because they suspect 
race was the major factor in setting the boundaries. The unanimous 
ruling in a North Carolina case could affect redistricting disputes 
after the 2000 census by leading judges to be more certain of the 
role race played before striking down a reapportionment plan. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled, 7-2, in a Florida case that police do not need a warrant  
to seize someone's car from a public place under laws requiring 
forfeiture of property linked to crime. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to decide in a Pennsylvania case how far state and local  
governments can go in banning nude dancing in bars, a case that may 
clarify the line between protected expression and unlawful lewd 
behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	--Bolstered the president's power as commander in chief by saying  
the military's highest court lacked the power to bar him from 
dropping a court-martialed officer from the armed forces. The 
unanimous ruling came in the case of an HIV-positive Air Force 
major imprisoned for having unprotected sex while stationed in 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	--Left intact a million-dollar libel award against the tabloid  
newspaper Globe for repeating a book's claim that a California man, 
not Sirhan Sirhan, killed Robert F. Kennedy. The justices let stand 
a California Supreme Court ruling that the news media can be liable 
for repeating someone else's libelous statement about a private 
figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
