<HEADLINE> Flynts Gear Up To Sell Hustler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Hustler magazine may soon be readily available  
on Cincinnati newsstands for the first time since Larry Flynt went 
to jail for selling his X-rated publication here in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be actively soliciting retail outlets in Hamilton County  
to let them know that all Larry Flynt Publications magazines will 
be available,'' said Flynt's brother, Jimmy, who manages Hustler 
Books Magazine &AMP; Gifts in downtown Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are probably still going to be apprehensive,'' he said.  
``If I don't pick up a lot of retailers, at least people will know 
that they can buy all our publications here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newsstands around Cincinnati have largely shunned Hustler,  
afraid of a costly legal fight since Larry Flynt was convicted of 
pandering obscenity in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	But 20 years after that conviction was overturned, Flynt  
believes prosecutors will leave the magazine alone now that he has 
agreed to stop selling sexually explicit videos in the county. 
</P>
<P>
	``The county does not want the videos sold; we just used them to  
force the issue of the magazines anyway,'' Jimmy Flynt said. ``If 
they just leave the magazine alone, we'll be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Flynt, 56, and Jimmy, 50, were indicted in April 1998 on  
charges of pandering obscenity, disseminating material harmful to a 
juvenile, conspiracy and engaging in a pattern of corrupt activity. 
</P>
<P>
	A plea bargain announced Wednesday, in the third day of jury  
selection, allowed the Flynts to substitute the store's corporate 
entity, Hustler News &AMP; Gifts Inc., on two of the counts of 
pandering, and the other 13 counts were dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	A guilty plea was entered for the company, which was fined  
$5,000 on each count. The store stayed open, but the videos were 
sent back to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of our magazines are going to be on sale,'' Jimmy Flynt  
said. ``We publish 30 different explicit magazines and they're 
going to be on sale. Our lingerie is going to be on sale, our toys 
and novelties will be on sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``It still will be a warm and inviting atmosphere.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Hustler store, opened two years ago, is one of the only  
places in town to get the explicit magazine. It sells about 1,100 
copies of Hustler a month, compared with 50 to 100 sold at most 
outlets, Jimmy Flynt said. Nationwide, circulation is about 
750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati was the nation's biggest city in which Hustler was  
not readily available, Larry Flynt said. He claimed victory for 
getting what amounted to an admission that selling Hustler magazine 
was not illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton County Prosecutor Mike Allen said although officials  
were most concerned with the X-rated videos, the settlement does 
not promise that Hustler will never be prosecuted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The subject of this indictment was the 16 sexually explicit  
videos; there's nothing anywhere that says we cannot revisit the 
issue with respect to Hustler magazine,'' Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If something is presented to me or my office that we consider  
violative of the law, we can and will present that matter to the 
grand jury,'' Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hustler Books Magazines &AMP; Gifts may have to move later this  
year, but not because of legal problems. A half block of downtown 
Cincinnati is to be razed to make room for construction of the 
Contemporary Arts Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The city has been unsuccessful in its attempts to close Flynt  
with zoning and licensing legislation. It may even have to pay part 
of the store's relocation costs -- up to $20,000 -- when it acquires 
the land for the museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
