<HEADLINE> TRW To Sell 4 Automotive Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Corp. plans to sell four automotive  
operations to help reduce debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which makes automobile airbags and defense and  
aerospace equipment, said today it will sell TRW Engine Components, 
Lucas Diesel Systems operations, TRW Nelson Stud Welding and the 
LucasVarity Wiring companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Debt reduction is an immediate priority for TRW,'' said Joseph  
Gorman, chairman and chief executive officer. ``Exiting these 
businesses will contribute significantly to the timely achievement 
of that goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Net proceeds from the sale, estimated to be $1.2 billion to $1.5  
billion, will be applied to the debt from TRW's purchase of British 
auto parts maker LucasVarity PLC for $7 billion. TRW took a $85.3 
million charge for buying LucasVarity. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW Engine Components produces more than 300 million engine  
valves annually. It has about 6,000 employees and operates in 12 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas Diesel Systems, employing 9,200 people, is one of the  
world's largest manufacturers of diesel fuel injection systems, 
serving the car, van, truck, bus, agricultural, industrial and 
marine industries. It supplies fuel injection systems to more than 
one-third of Europe's diesel car and van market. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW Nelson Stud Welding, which makes stud welding fasteners and  
equipment, employs 250 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lucas Wiring businesses, previously announced for sale March  
29, are the leading supplier of electrical wiring systems in the 
United Kingdom. The businesses employ 5,500 people and have 
operations in the United Kingdom, Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Egypt 
and Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
