<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Partum Depression Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- That period of depression that bothers many  
new mothers could have a long-term effect on the babies, a study 
suggests. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at Emory University found that both depressed  
mothers and their babies have increased amounts of the hormone 
cortisol in their blood -- an indication of stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Cortisol levels in the babies systems remained high months  
later, even after the mothers received treatment and their own 
hormone levels returned to normal, Dr. Yolanda P. Graham reported 
Monday at the annual convention of the American Psychiatric 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said having high cortisol levels can make people  
vulnerable to overreacting to stress later in life. She is 
continuing to follow the infants to see if their hormone levels 
remain high or eventually drop to more normal levels. 
</P>
<P>
	So-called postpartum depression affects 10 percent to 20 percent  
of new mothers. Several studies have shown changes in the behavior 
of children, including infants, as a result of contact with the 
depressed mother, the Emory researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham explained that depressed mothers tend to react in one of  
two ways, either by ignoring their new baby or by overcompensating 
-- smothering it with attention. Either behavior can cause stress 
for the baby, she explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently her study involves 14 mothers who suffered postpartum  
depression. Graham wants to increase that to 20. She is looking at 
a similar number of mothers who did not suffer depression. 
</P>
<P>
	The cortisol levels of the babies were measured before age 7  
months and again two to three months later, with two further 
measurements planned. 
</P>
<P>
	While cortisol levels vary somewhat in infants, they normally  
stabilize by the time of the second visit, she said, and that 
occurred in the children of mothers who were not depressed. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the children of depressed mothers, levels remained above  
normal, even though the mothers hormone levels had been returned to 
normal through treatment. The next two measurements will help 
determine if the effect continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
