<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pollsters Face Threat From Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETE BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Pollsters face a triple challenge to  
their profession now that they've wrapped up one of their most 
influential years. 
</P>
<P>
	The high profile of polls in the last year has led to increased  
scrutiny by critics. The public's response to poll interviewers has 
been declining. And Internet surveys are being offered as a 
tempting -- and cheaper -- alternative to proven scientific methods. 
</P>
<P>
	These were major concerns of pollsters who gathered over the  
weekend for the annual meeting of the American Association for 
Public Opinion Research. 
</P>
<P>
	The role played by public opinion in President Clinton's sex  
scandal and impeachment trial was a frequent theme at the weekend 
sessions. While public support for Clinton did not prevent his 
trial, many analysts believe it contributed to his political 
survival. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last year solidified the importance of public opinion,''  
said New York City pollster Warren Mitofsky. ``The public made it 
abundantly clear over and over again -- they were supporting Bill 
Clinton as president, but condemning his behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the impeachment trial raised the political stakes for  
polling, and the poll results that backed Clinton became part of 
the debate. The polls became ``political footballs to be kicked 
around,'' said Kathleen Frankovic, director of polling for CBS 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	The unwillingness of some people to participate in polls, a  
problem pollsters call ``non-response,'' also was discussed at the 
conference, and participants pledged more research on its effects. 
</P>
<P>
	A study by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press  
showed no difference in the findings of low and high response 
polls, but pollsters say they do not fully understand the effects 
of low response. 
</P>
<P>
	The non-response problem has grown as people have more high-tech  
phone screening devices, less use for inquiries from strangers and 
the perception that they have less time, pollsters said. 
</P>
<P>
	A more controversial issue at this meeting was Internet polls,  
which have sprung up on many Web sites and threaten to drown out 
scientific polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditional pollsters said they are considering a rating system  
to distinguish between scientifically designed polls, which pick a 
random geographic and weighted sample of the entire population, and 
those that do not. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray Edelman, editorial director of Voter News Service and  
incoming vice president of the pollsters association, said Internet 
polling will never supplant the highest quality scientific polls. 
But he acknowledged the Internet efforts are likely to ``reshape 
polling'' at some levels because of their convenience and relative 
low cost. 
</P>
<P>
	The polling firm Harris Black International made a pitch to the  
group that the Internet can be used effectively for election 
polling by drawing a large pool of Web users and then finding a 
representative poll sample from that group. 
</P>
<P>
	But most in the polling field argue the company cannot draw a  
representative sample of the nation's population off the Internet, 
which is used by about 40 percent of Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Voter News Service is a partnership of The Associated Press and  
the ABC, CBS, CNN, NBC and Fox television networks that conducts 
state and national exit polls on Election Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their concerns, pollsters said the last year offered a  
unique environment to practice their craft and reinforce the 
accuracy of polling. 
</P>
<P>
	Association president Michael Traugott said the intense focus of  
pollsters on the Clinton scandal provided quick public judgments 
that proved stable for the duration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure we'll see soon another instance in which there  
was such highly focused polling activity on such a limited set of 
topics,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
