<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged With Assault on Jockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A man who ran in front of horses charging down  
the stretch at Pimlico Race Course told police he was trying to 
commit suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to kill myself,'' Lee Ferrell said, according to  
a report filed by arresting officer Timothy Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrell, of Bel Air, is charged with first-degree assault,  
trespassing, reckless endangerment, disorderly conduct, resisting 
arrest and alcohol-related offenses, for his actions Saturday 
during a race preceding the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Ferrell also stated this isn't the first time he tried to  
commit suicide, and is currently on medication, Paxol and 
Depakote,'' the police report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The drugs are antidepressants.  
</P>
<P>
	Ferrell used a closed fist to strike jockey Jorge Chavez,  
hitting him on his back, according to the police report. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrell was released from Baltimore's central booking facility  
after posting a $2,500 bond. Court officials said Ferrell was not 
released on his own recognizance because he told them he was on 
probation for driving while intoxicated. 
</P>
<P>
	The charge onto the track occurred several hundred yards from  
the finish line during the seventh race Saturday, about 2 1/2 hours 
before Charismatic added a Preakness victory to his win in the 
Kentucky Derby. He goes for the Triple Crown on June 5 in the 
Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferrell made his way to the track from the infield, went over a  
fence separating the fans from the turf course, staggered to the 
inside rail, which he pounded with his fist before ducking under 
it, and walked onto the track. 
</P>
<P>
	As the horses approached, he stood with his fists clenched and  
arms upraised. As the horses charged by on both sides, Ferrell 
could be seen in videotape replays apparently punching at two 
horses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
