<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Makah Tribal Hunters Take Whale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEAH BAY, Wash. (AP) -- As fellow members of the tribe watched on  
live TV, Makah Indians in a hand-carved canoe harpooned a gray 
whale Monday for the first time in 70 years, renewing an ancient 
tradition that defines their culture. 
</P>
<P>
	A larger fishing boat joined the hunters and began slowly towing  
the carcass to Neah Bay, where the 2,000-member tribe declared a 
holiday and planned to cut the whale up and share its meat and oil. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Makah Maiden restaurant in Neah Bay, the breakfast crowd,  
nearly all tribal members, stared transfixed as the hunt was 
broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strike went in and everybody roared in applause, rejoicing  
of their voices all in unity,'' said Joddie Johnson, owner of the 
restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists decried the killing, which was accomplished  
through a combination of the traditional -- the cedar canoe and its 
hand-carved paddles -- and the modern, including .50-caliber rifles 
and motorized boats. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're obviously very upset that the Makah went ahead with  
killing an innocent, sentient creature in such a bloody and 
untraditional way,'' said Jake Conroy of the anti-whaling group Sea 
Defense Alliance. ``We find it very hurtful and despicable that 
they did destroy that whale's life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For centuries, the Makahs hunted the huge gray whales that  
migrate along the Pacific Coast between Alaska and the Gulf of 
Mexico. The tribe stopped hunting in the 1920s, after the grays 
were decimated by commercial whaling. 
</P>
<P>
	Whaling still looms large in Makah culture, with images of the  
animal emblazoned on the high school and the backdrop used for 
traditional dances. 
</P>
<P>
	So after gray whales were taken off the Endangered Species List  
in 1994, the tribe sought to resume whale hunts to preserve their 
culture on their remote reservation. They won international 
permission to kill 20 whales through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Up until last fall, however, no living Makahs had ever even been  
on a whale hunt. Few had ever tasted whale meat. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's hunt climaxed months of training by the canoe's crew  
and tense confrontations with anti-whaling protesters. On Saturday, 
a small flotilla of protest boats disrupted a hunt, but 
demonstrators did not arrive on the scene Monday until about an 
hour after the whalers struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Paddling rapidly, the seven-man Makah crew stalked the whale  
under gray and misty skies about an eighth of a mile off shore, 
steering the canoe's long, narrow bow directly above the animal. 
</P>
<P>
	About an hour after dawn, blood stained the choppy waters of the  
Pacific as the hunters repeatedly harpooned the huge mammal. The 
whale, which appeared to be at least as long as the 32-foot canoe, 
thrashed once and dived, dragging the boat in a wide circle. 
</P>
<P>
	The whale resurfaced minutes later. Support crews in motorized  
boats moved in with rifles and shot the whale point-blank at least 
twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Whalers aboard the canoe and a support boat struck it twice more  
with harpoons, all within 10 minutes of the initial hit. 
</P>
<P>
	When pictures shot from TV news helicopters showed the hunting  
crew's success, Makahs gathered at the community center in the 
village of Neah Bay, eight miles north of the hunting grounds, to 
sing and celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no words that can express what's inside,'' Ms. Johnson  
said. ``Very full of pride, honor, respect of the whale for the 
warriors and the warriors' respect for the greatness of the 
whale.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
