<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
 *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
 *General Motors, down 2 3/4 at 80 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	A Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst downgraded his rating on  
automakers, citing an ``abnormally competitive'' environment. He 
said suppliers of auto parts will fare better than the major U.S. 
automakers for the next 12 to 18 months. 

</P>
<P>
 *Wyman Gordon, up 5 11/16 at 18 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The maker of forgings and castings for aerospace and energy  
manufacturers will be acquired by Precision Castparts Corp. for $20 
a share, or about $721 million. 

</P>
<P>
 *Gulfstream Aerospace, up 6 1/8 at 61 3/4  
</P>
<P>
 *General Dynamics, down 6 3/16 at 65 1/4 
</P>
<P>
	Defense giant General Dynamics will acquire Gulfstream, a  
business-jet manufacturer, for $5.3 billion. 

</P>
<P>
 *Harcourt General Inc., up 4 3/8 at 54    	
</P>
<P>
	Harcourt and Neiman Marcus Group Inc. plan to spin off Harcourt  
General's controlling interest in The Neiman Marcus Group to 
Harcourt General shareholders. The move is designed to separate 
Neiman's high-end retail identity from Harcourt General's 
educational publishing business. 

</P>
<P>
 *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Life USA, up 9 1/8 at 19 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The financial services holding company will be acquired by  
Allianz Life, a unit of Allianz AG, an international insurance 
group based in Munich, Germany. Allianz will pay $540 million, or 
$20.75 per share. 

</P>
<P>
 *Medical Manager, up 14 1/8 at 47 7/8  
</P>
<P>
 *Synetic, down 3 1/4 at 92 1/4 
</P>
<P>
	Synetic Inc. will acquire Medical Manager Corp., a provider of  
physician information systems, for $1.4 billion. Synetic, which has 
business in plastics and filtration technologies, as well as health 
care communications, will then change its name to Medical Manager 
Corp. 

</P>
<P>
 *Immune Response, down 4 1/4 at 7 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	An independent safety monitoring board recommended that Immune  
Response and its partner, Agouron Pharmaceuticals, conclude studies 
of their Remune drug. Remune, designed for use in HIV treatment, 
did not significantly change the condition of patients who took in 
Phase III trials. 



</P>
</TEXT>
