<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Hears Overturning NAFTA Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- The Clinton administration asked a  
federal judge Monday to throw out a union-backed lawsuit 
challenging the North American Free Trade Agreement as 
unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	A government lawyer said no court has ever required a president  
to withdraw from a pact like NAFTA, which critics blame for the 
loss of 400,000 American jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under international law we are not allowed to say, 'Sorry,  
Mexico. Sorry, Canada, we didn't do this right,'' Justice 
Department attorney Martha Rubio argued during a hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jeremiah Collins, representing the United Steelworkers of  
America, said the trade deal was approved by too small a majority 
in Congress five years ago and has since become a ``gigantic 
millstone'' for U.S. industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got thousands of people who are hurt by NAFTA,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Robert Propst issued no immediate decision  
on the lawsuit, filed in Birmingham because hundreds of Alabama 
steelworkers blame job losses on NAFTA. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers approved NAFTA at the urging of President Clinton in  
1993, reducing tariffs and lowering regulatory hurdles with the 
goal of increasing trade between the United States, Mexico and 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration contends the deal has been a success, citing  
increased U.S. exports and improved relations between the United 
States and Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents say NAFTA has drained jobs from the United States  
by encouraging companies to relocate to Mexico, hire low-paid 
workers and import goods back to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The crux of the lawsuit centers on whether NAFTA is a trade  
agreement -- as the administration contends -- or a treaty, as the 
United Steelworkers of America argues. 
</P>
<P>
	Both houses of Congress approved NAFTA on simple majority votes  
in 1993, indicating it was a trade agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lawsuit contends NAFTA is really a treaty and should  
have been subject to a two-thirds majority vote in the Senate, as 
required by the Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed last year by the Washington-based Made in the  
USA Foundation and Local 12 of the United Steelworkers of America 
in Gadsden, where some 1,300 members will be idled by the closing 
of a Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co. plant this year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
