</P>
<P>
	Fed Might Raise Interest Rates Soon  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (P) -- Americans, who have grown accustomed to nothing  
but good news on inflation, got a jolt last week when consumer 
prices jumped by the largest amount in nearly nine years, led by a 
sharp increase in gasoline prices. That development will be on the 
table when Federal Reserve policy-makers meet Tuesday, but private 
economists believe it will take more than one bad number to prompt 
the central bank to start raising interest rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard 2Q Profits Jump  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. beat Wall Street  
expectations with a 34 percent increase in second-quarter profits, 
fueled by sales of personal computers. The big maker of computers, 
printers and high-tech accessories said it earned $918 million, or 
88 cents a share, for the three months ended April 30. It earned 
$685 million, or 65 cents a share in the same period of last year. 
Revenue rose 3 percent to $12.4 billion from $12 billion. Analysts 
surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected the Palo Alto-based 
Hewlett-Packard to earn 80 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
	Spelling To Complete Sale To Viacom  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Viacom Inc. is paying $181 million in cash to  
buy the 20 percent of television producer Spelling Entertainment 
Group Inc. it doesn't already own. Viacom will pay $9.75 for each 
share of Spelling, giving it full control of the company that 
produces ``Melrose Place,'' ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Judge 
Judy.'' Viacom, which inherited its stake in Spelling from its 1994 
acquisition of the Blockbuster video chain, has been trying for 
some time to buy the rest of the company. Viacom also owns MTV, 
VH1, Nickelodeon, the Paramount movie studio, half of the UPN 
network and part of the Simon &AMP; Schuster publishing house. 

</P>
<P>
	Web Bookstores Discount Bestsellers  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com both plan to  
offer 50 percent discounts on books listed on the New York Times 
bestseller list. Both companies said the purpose is to increase 
sales and market share rather than immediate profits. ``This is not 
a sale, this is not a promotion -- this is everyday low pricing,'' 
said Jeff Bezos, founder and chief executive of Amazon.com. The 
move will have little impact on Barnesandnoble's bottom line, chief 
executive Jonathan Bulkeley said. Boyd said the Times bestseller 
list accounted for ``less than 3 percent of overall revenues'' at 
Barnesandnoble.com. 

</P>
<P>
	The Limited's Earnings, Sales Rise  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The Limited Inc. said its first-quarter  
earnings rose nearly 30 percent as results improved at several of 
its clothing store chains. The nation's largest specialty apparel 
retailer with 3,600 stores reported its net income, which excludes 
one-time items, was $33.5 million, or 14 cents per share, in the 
quarter ended May 1. One-time items included the divestiture of the 
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch chain last year. Sales rose 4.8 percent to $2.1 
billion from nearly $2.01 billion. The Limited was down 1 1/16 at 
46 5/6. 

</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us Reports Lower Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	PARAMUS, N.J. (AP) -- Toys R Us Inc.'s reported its first-quarter  
earnings fell 10.5 percent, but the retailer's executives said they 
expect demand for ``Star Wars'' merchandise to make 1999 a good 
year. Toys R Us earned $17 million. Per-share earnings were 
unchanged at 7 cents, and beat Wall Street expectations of 4 cents. 
Sales were $2.16 billion, up 5 percent. Toys R U was surpassed 
earlier this year as the nation's largest toy retailer by Wal-Mart. 
Toys R Us shares were down 1/4 at 22. 

</P>
<P>
	Workers Honor Ingalls Picket Line  
</P>
<P>
	PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) -- Hundreds of workers refused today to  
cross picket lines set up by a machinists union outside Ingalls 
Shipbuilding, Mississippi's largest private employer. The picket 
lines first went up outside the two main entrances to the shipyard 
yesterday after the union and the company could not resolve a 
dispute over the frequency of pay raises and bonuses. While only 
Machinists Local 1133 voted to strike, 11 of the 13 unions 
representing 8,000 Ingalls employees rejected the shipyard's latest 
contract proposal in weekend votes. 

</P>
<P>
	American Air, Attendants Reach Deal  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines and its flight attendants' union  
have reached a tentative agreement after nearly nine months of 
contract talks. AMR Corp., the airline's parent company, and the 
Association of Professional Flight Attendants, which represents 
20,000 members, did not disclose details of the plan. The pact does 
provide pay increases, improvements in retirement and increased 
scheduling flexibility, according to the APFA and AMR. The 
tentative agreement now will be subject to the APFA's ratification 
process. AMR stock was down 7/8 at 70 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones, Reuters Combine Archives  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones and Reuters announced a deal to  
combine their business news archives into a company that will 
provide financial information to paid subscribers over the 
Internet. The companies plan to introduce the new product, to be 
called Dow Jones Reuters Business Interactive, in about a year. 
Before that time, the two companies will share archived news for 
their database services. The deal does not include the consumer 
Internet services of either company, such as the successful online 
version of Dow Jones' flagship newspaper, Wall Street Journal 
Interactive. 

</P>
<P>
	RealNetworks, Snap.com Join Forces  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- RealNetworks Inc. and Snap.com today announced  
they are teaming up to help Internet users find music and video on 
the Web. RealNetworks said it will incorporate a search feature 
into its RealPlayer G2 software using Snap.com technology as the 
search engine. Snap.com, the Internet portal from NBC and CNET, 
will be featured on RealPlayer G2, which allowing users to search 
directly for streaming audio and video files on the Web. 

</P>
<P>
	General Dynamics Buys Jet Maker  
</P>
<P>
	SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) -- Defense giant General Dynamics will buy  
Gulfstream Aerospace Corp., a maker of business jets, for $5.3 
billion. The deal allows General Dynamics to expand beyond its core 
defense contracting business. The company was blocked last month in 
a bid to acquire Newport News Shipbuilding Inc. In its new deal, 
General Dynamics will pay $71.44 per share of Gulfstream, which 
controls about 60 percent of the world market for business jets. 
General Dynamics shares were down 6 3/16 this afternoon at 65 1/4, and 
Gulfstream was up 6 1/16 at 61 11/16. 

</P>
<P>
	U S West, Global Crossing To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Baby Bell phone company U S West Inc. plans to  
merge with growing telecommunications company Global Crossing Ltd. 
in a stock swap valued at $37 billion. The two companies will offer 
local, long-distance and wireless phone service, plus high-speed 
Internet access around the globe. The new company, which will keep 
the Global Crossing name, will have more than $15 billion in sales 
and a market value of about $65 billion. U S West stock was down 4 
at 58 1/4, and Global Crossing was down 1 1/8 at 60 1/4. 

</P>
