<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Tries for Education Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blocked last year by President Clinton,  
Republicans are trying again to give tax breaks to parents who send 
their children to private schools or teach at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton vetoed a similar bill in 1998 amid strong opposition by  
Democrat-aligned teacher unions. This year, Republicans added 
sweeteners such as tax incentives to finance school construction 
that appeal to Democrats and could help the GOP override a 
potential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance  
Committee, called the bill ``a first but important step'' in making 
education more affordable for all students and parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``This proposal is a down payment on education assistance for  
our nation's students and their families,'' Roth said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, scheduled for a vote Wednesday in the Finance  
Committee, would cost $7.6 billion over 10 years, according to a 
preliminary congressional analysis. It would be paid for by $7.9 
billion in new revenues, mainly from businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The centerpiece of the measure would raise the annual  
contribution limit on education IRAs, now used only for higher 
education, from $500 to $2,000. For the first time, the money could 
be withdrawn tax-free to pay expenses for kindergarten through 12th 
grade pupils who attend public, private or parochial schools or who 
are taught at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualified expenses would include tuition, fees, books, supplies,  
computer software and required uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Like under current law, the contribution limit would be phased  
out for individuals earning more than $95,000 in adjusted gross 
income and $150,000 for joint income tax filers. 
</P>
<P>
	When he vetoed a similar measure last year, Clinton said the  
money could be used better for public school construction and 
contended the GOP bill would primarily benefit the wealthy. The 
National Education Association, which led last year's opposition, 
said little has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's bad tax policy and it's bad education policy,'' said Mary  
Elizabeth Teasley, NEA legislative affairs director. ``It's a 
disguise for a private school voucher for the wealthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House had no comment on the bill Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are optimistic, however, that they can gain  
significant Democratic support. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., is 
the main co-sponsor of the education IRA bill, and several other 
items supported by Democrats were included. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them are public school construction components introduced  
by Democratic Sen. Bob Graham of Florida. The components would 
relax certain revenue bond rules and add schools to the list of 
projects that can be paid for with tax-exempt private activity 
bonds, which have an annual limit of $10 per resident or at least 
$5 million per state. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would allow tax-free distributions from state-sponsored  
and private prepaid college tuition plans, costing $925 million 
over 10 years. It would also extend the tax-free treatment of 
college-level educational assistance provided by an employer, a 
break now scheduled to expire in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
