<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Bookstores Discount Bestsellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Buying best sellers over the Internet just got a  
good deal cheaper. For some bookstores, the squeeze has tightened. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not immediately clear what the effect on the retail book  
business will be from a 50 percent discount offered by the nation's 
three leading online book sellers on books listed on The New York 
Times best seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the online sellers, it clearly was the start of a price  
war intended to lure more consumers in hopes of enticing them to 
buy other more lucrative products as they browse through the Web 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com of Seattle, the Internet book selling pioneer and  
largest Web-based book business, led the way and was quickly 
matched by No. 2 Barnesandnoble.com of New York and No. 3 
Borders.com of Ann Arbor, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	The discounts, previously as much as 40 percent, apply to  
paperback as well as hardcover books on the weekly list of at least 
68 titles. The deep discounts will mean the companies will make 
little or no profit on the books. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Ryan of Prudential Securities in New York said the bigger  
price cuts ``are clearly intended to drive traffic to their (Web) 
sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher E. Vroom, an electronic commerce analyst at Thomas  
Weisel Partners in San Francisco, agreed that the move seemed 
largely a marketing tactic. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they make any margin whatsoever, it's going to be a very  
tiny one,'' Vroom said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble vice president Ben Boyd said the Times best  
seller list accounted for ``less than 3 percent of 
(Barnesandnoble.com's) overall revenues.'' For Borders, the figure 
is about 5 percent, spokesman Rich Fahle said. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, chain bookstores in malls and general-purpose  
independent book retailers rely on best sellers for 30 percent to 
35 percent of their business, Vroom said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this will increase the pressure on smaller book  
sellers and result in further consolidation in the industry,'' 
Vroom said. ``Book sellers that have carved a particular niche in 
the marketplace will continue to prosper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan said the discounts would put further pressure on ``less  
efficient book sellers'' but added that it was too early to 
determine the impact on the retail book business overall. 
</P>
<P>
	The move will have little impact on Barnesandnoble's bottom  
line, chief executive Jonathan Bulkeley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``At our existing sales volume, the additional discount on best  
sellers will have a minor effect on our operating margin,'' 
Bulkeley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two large independents, Powell's Books in Portland, Ore., and  
Elliott Bay Book Co. in Seattle, said they expected little effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of Powell's extensive used, antique and rare book  
collections, ``we don't feel like we're competing directly with 
those (online) stores,'' said Dave Weich, who manages the store's 
Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``Online, we're not really a destination for somebody who wants  
to buy a big new best seller,'' Weich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't even have a New York Times best seller display in our  
store,'' Elliott Bay manager Tracy Taylor said. ``Our customers 
don't particularly come in looking for those titles ... it's just 
never been that kind of a store.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
