<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Rise / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures moved modestly higher  
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as wet weather continued to 
delay spring plantings. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants said wheat and corn in particular were  
poised to move sharply higher if wet weather persists in Midwest 
growing regions. Farmers typically have a limited window for 
planting those crops, and time is rapidly running out. Still, the 
government in its weekly updates has reported that dry periods 
between recent storms have given farmers ample time to continue 
planting. 
</P>
<P>
	After trading had ended, the National Weather Service also  
predicted normal to below-normal precipitation over the next 10 
days in major Midwestern growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans moved higher in step with corn, although some market  
participants worried that any planting delays for corn and wheat 
would lead to increased soybean acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.62 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn rose 2 cents to $2.23 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.22 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 1/2 cents to $4.70 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures fell sharply amid weak cash market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .25 cent to 62.15 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .25 cents to 73.92 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .90 cent to 57.97 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1.55 
cents to 54.65 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
