<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jefferson's Slave Kin Shunned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- The meeting marked the first time  
descendants of Thomas Jefferson's alleged mistress were invited to 
a Jefferson family reunion. And typical of a gathering that unites 
long-lost cousins, pent up emotions rose to the fore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every family has an in-group and an out-group, and a  
reconciliation that has to take place,'' said Mary Jefferson, a 
descendant of Sally Hemings, one of President Jefferson's slaves 
and his reputed lover. 
</P>
<P>
	The in-group at the weekend reunion were descendants of Thomas  
and Martha Jefferson, and they declined during a family business 
meeting Sunday to let relatives of Hemings officially join the 
family's 86-year-old Monticello Association. 
</P>
<P>
	They also blocked a vote to offer Hemings' descendants -- some  
three dozen of whom attended the event at Monticello, Jefferson's 
plantation home -- honorary membership while a paternity claim is 
researched. 
</P>
<P>
	The association, however, did appoint a committee to conduct  
more research into the paternity issue and allowed Hemings' 
descendants inside the hotel ballroom for the membership debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson, the nation's third president, was accused publicly  
while in office of being the father of several of Hemings' children 
after his wife died. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Hemings' family have passed down the paternity claim  
through the generations. In November, a DNA study concluded that 
Jefferson was likely the father of Eston Hemings, the slave's 
youngest son. 
</P>
<P>
	Descendants from both families said the reunion was mostly  
productive, although combative at times. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nation is looking to this family for leadership in healing  
some of the wounds of slavery and segregation, and I thought today 
we took a good first step toward doing that,'' said Monticello 
Association member Marla Randolph Stevens. 
</P>
<P>
	But before dessert was finished on Sunday, a Monticello  
Association member made a motion to ask the Hemings guests to leave 
the room during a discussion of ``family business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It got a little tense,'' Hemings descendant Bill Dalton of  
Chillicothe, Ohio, said afterward. The media was not allowed to 
attend any of the proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	Treena Woodson, a Hemings descendant from Philadelphia, said the  
acrimonious tone of the arguments hurt her feelings. ``It was kind 
of painful to hear that,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hemings descendant John Taylor King said ``there were little  
angry knots of people'' in the crowd. But he said the 30-23 vote to 
let the Hemings group stay restored his faith in the ``good 
intentions'' of the Jefferson descendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Dalton said the crowd of about 250 erupted into applause when  
the vote was announced. ``That's when I felt warm and welcomed,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucian Truscott of Los Angeles, the Jefferson descendant who  
first invited the Hemingses, told reporters after the meeting that 
there was ``an element of racism'' in the arguments to deny 
immediate membership. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jefferson descendant Theresa Shackelford of Nashville,  
Tenn., who wants the paternity claim to be researched further, 
disputed that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm for any lineal descendant to be able to be buried at  
Monticello, black, white or purple,'' Ms. Shackelford said. ``We're 
not racists. We're snobs.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
