<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MiningCo.com Grows to About.com </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Internet guide MiningCo.com Inc. plans to  
switch its name to About.com in an attempt to change its image from 
an entry point onto the Internet to a destination 
</P>
<P>
	About.com uses a staff of Internet searchers to compile guides  
on 650 topics. With the name change, the topics will be given names 
such as About Europe, About Dermatology, etc. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers use portals -- entry points for users to venture onto  
the Internet -- to help them to find a wealth of online services 
such as free e-mail, news, chat and personalized functions like 
stock quotes, local weather and sports. 
</P>
<P>
	However, About.com seeks to become a destination point for  
Internet users rather than just a portal, officials said. As such, 
the company has launched a membership program through which users 
can create their own ``AboutMe'' page that describes their 
interests and allows them to connect with others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel the About.com name is a simpler way to highlight to  
our expanding audience, the personal and relevant Internet 
experience our members have enjoyed so much,'' said Scott Kurnit, 
chairman and CEO. About. com will aid consumers who ``demand 
topic-specific destinations that combine search, community and 
original content,'' he added. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 15:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cannes Hosts Literary Adaptations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- Three of the movies vying for the Golden  
Palm award at this year's Cannes Film Festival are based on 
prize-winning books -- but only one seems to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian director Atom Egoyan's ``Felicia's Journey,'' a  
suspenseful, macabre tale of a lonely bachelor who befriends 
wayward girls, is based on William Trevor's 1988 Whitbread 
Prize-winning novel by the same name. 
</P>
<P>
	This fresh take on the traditional serial killer -- no blood, no  
detective tracking the criminal -- won enthusiastic praise at 
Monday's screening. 
</P>
<P>
	Egoyan said he took liberties with the original text,  
transforming the character of a socialite mother into a glamorous, 
celebrity TV chef who humiliates her fat son on camera, stuffing 
him with raw liver. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only violence in this film is emotional, and it begets a  
monster,'' Egoyan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``No One Writes to the Colonel,'' Mexican director Arturo  
Ripstein's adaptation of the novella by Gabriel Garcia Marquez, won 
praise from the Nobel Prize-winner but many viewers Monday found it 
slow-moving. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-hour film set in Mexico in the 1950s portrays an elderly  
retired colonel and his wife waiting, in vain, for the colonel's 
long-promised military pension to come in the mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Their only son has died in murky circumstances, and their only  
joy is a cockfighting bird they hope will save them from 
starvation. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia Marquez, who attended film school in Rome before becoming  
a novelist, praised Ripstein's effort, saying in a letter read to 
reporters: ``It's a great film ... and does justice to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripstein said he had wanted to adapt the novella since he was 21  
years old. ``Marquez said `I'll give it to you when you learn,' and 
I waited 33 years,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, veteran Chilean director Raoul Ruiz's adaptation of  
Marcel Proust's epic ``Le Temps Retrouve'' (Time Regained) had more 
than one critic napping -- despite an all-star cast featuring 
Catherine Deneuve, Emmanuelle Beart and John Malkovich. 
</P>
<P>
	Set around World War I and structured as a series of vaguely  
linked vignettes weaving past to present, it fails to capture the 
rich, analytic texture of Proust's descriptive prose. 
</P>
<P>
	``Proust is a director himself, with a vision of things that  
makes you want to adapt it to the screen,'' Ruiz told reporters. 
``The difficulties aren't insurmountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Proust has frustrated generations of filmmakers. Orson  
Welles, Luchino Visconti and Joseph Losey tried but gave up. Volker 
Schlondorff's ``Swann's Way'' was a critical flop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 15:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
