<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CVS Buys Online Pharmacy Soma.com </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Combining a virtual drug store with its  
real-world counterpart, pharmacy chain CVS Corp. announced Monday 
it is buying online drug retailer Soma.com for $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The move accelerates CVS' fledgling effort to sell drugs over  
the Internet, a concept that experts predict could take off the way 
Amazon.com has transformed the book selling business. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the relatively low selling price raised doubts about the  
long-term survival prospects of the handful of remaining online 
pharmacies. It also raised the specter of similar mergers, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soma.com gives CVS a major presence on the Internet, a warehouse  
distribution system, and the ability to sell drugs even in areas of 
the country where CVS has no stores. CVS has 4,122 stores, more 
than any other pharmacy chain. Most of its stores are east of the 
Mississippi River. 
</P>
<P>
	Woonsocket R.I.-based CVS provides Soma.com with instant name  
recognition and contracts to sell to members of many major health 
insurers. CVS officials say they have not decided whether to retain 
the Soma.com web site, its CVS.com or use another name. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-based Soma.com in January became the first Internet  
company to launch an online pharmacy. But analysts say the company 
was hampered by few health insurance contracts, which greatly 
limited the number of potential customers that could shop on its 
Web site. Additionally, because Soma.com could only fill orders for 
overnight delivery, it was of little use for patients who wanted 
their medications immediately after leaving the hospital or 
doctor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Pending federal antitrust approval, the deal should be completed  
in June, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``CVS plus Soma.com is a powerful combination,'' said Mark  
Husson, a Merrill Lynch analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the low price shows that online pharmacies have some  
inherent problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Either CVS negotiated the most amazing deal ... or stand alone  
on-line pharmacies don't have the value some first thought,'' 
Husson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The .coms were supposed to be a major threat to bricks and  
mortar pharmacies, but today we've seen one decide to sell itself 
for a surprisingly small amount of money,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soma.com has been competing with other privately-held online  
pharmacies Drugstore.com and PlanetRX Inc. and RX.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither CVS nor privately-held Soma.com would disclose how many  
customers Soma.com has. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, CVS announced plans to enhance its Internet site. The  
company quickly figured buying Soma.com would give it a head start 
over its traditional rivals, said Tom Ryan, CVS chairman and chief 
executive officer. Walgreen, the nation's largest pharmacy chain by 
revenue, and No. 3 Rite Aid are also improving their Internet 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	CVS has no plans to actively persuade its customers to buy drug  
online, but will make sure consumer are aware they have the option, 
Ryan said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, shares of CVS rose 62 1/2 cents to $46.12 1/2 on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 10:32:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Arrest Made in Picasso Slashing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch police questioned a mental  
patient today after he escaped from a psychiatric clinic, hopped a 
train to Amsterdam and severely slashed a famous Picasso painting 
in one of the capital's most prestigious art museums. 
</P>
<P>
	The virtual destruction of ``Woman Nude Before Garden,'' a 1956  
oil on canvas by the abstract master, stunned the art world and the 
Stedelijk Museum of Modern Art, where another mentally disturbed 
man slashed a work by American abstract impressionist Barnett 
Newman in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is very shocked. I find it horrible what happened,  
and I can't believe it has happened again,'' said Saskia Bruines, 
Amsterdam's city councilor for culture. ``We must step up security. 
We must ask ourselves what we could be doing that we haven't 
already done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Picasso, valued at between $5 million and $7.5 million, was  
slashed Sunday afternoon by a mental patient identified by Dutch 
police only as Paul G. The museum, which is insured for the damage, 
said restoration experts would try their best to repair the 
painting. 
</P>
<P>
	Amsterdam police spokesman Cees Rameau said the 41-year-old man  
had escaped earlier in the day from a psychiatric clinic in 
Utrecht, 45 miles southeast of Amsterdam. Officials said he was a 
top suspect in an incident at Amsterdam's Rijksmuseum 10 years ago, 
in which someone threw paint at another unidentified masterpiece. 
</P>
<P>
	The man has been under the supervision of the clinic since 1978,  
when he tried to hijack a KLM Royal Dutch Airlines jet from 
Amsterdam to Madrid using a toy gun. Passengers and crew members 
overpowered him and he was arrested and convicted on assault 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Rameau said the man headed straight for the Stedelijk Museum,  
which has a world-class collection of modern art including five 
other Picassos, bought a ticket, went to the Picasso and used a 
small razor knife to carve a large circle out of the middle of the 
canvas. 
</P>
<P>
	He then went to the headquarters of Dutch daily newspaper De  
Telegraaf, where he boasted of his crime to a reporter. The 
newspaper called police, and the man was arrested in the lobby, 
where he allegedly threatened to kill the journalist in question, 
De Telegraaf reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stedelijk Museum bought ``Woman Nude Before Garden'' in 1981  
for $950,000. The 51-inch by 64-inch painting, done in cool hues of 
blue and green, depicts a naked woman reclining in a chair in front 
of an open window with a lush garden in the background. 
</P>
<P>
	The model for the painting, which was done in Cannes, France,  
was Jacqueline Roque, Picasso's newlywed wife at the time. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 06:13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Counsel Change Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An alternative law must be crafted to replace  
the Independent Counsel Act, former Senate majority leaders Bob 
Dole and George Mitchell said in a New York Times opinion piece 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The underlying purpose of the law remains a vital one: to make  
sure allegations of criminal wrongdoing by high-ranking government 
officials are thoroughly investigated and prosecuted, Dole and 
Mitchell wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key is to find a system that accomplishes that aim while  
retaining both the independence and the accountability of 
investigators,'' they wrote in the article published on the Times' 
op-ed page. 
</P>
<P>
	The law expires next month, and Dole and Mitchell said it is  
obvious Congress will not renew it. The law has come under 
criticism because of special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's lengthy and 
divisive investigation into President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, a Republican who opposed the last reauthorization of the  
law, and Mitchell, a Democrat who supported it, said they convened 
a bipartisan group to study the act. 
</P>
<P>
	The group considered the 20 investigations since the law was  
created in 1978 after the Watergate scandal, and also looked at the 
way accusations of governmental wrongdoing were handled before the 
act. 
</P>
<P>
	Their four main recommendations, which are to be detailed in a  
report to be issued Tuesday, are: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Let the Justice Department do its job. The agency's regular  
offices could have handled some matters assigned to independent 
counsels, Dole and Mitchell wrote, without specifying which 
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Return the full authority to appoint special counsels to U.S.  
attorneys general. ``If an attorney general refuses to appoint a 
special counsel when the circumstances justify one, the ultimate 
remedy is the political process ...,'' the two wrote. ``There is no 
substitute for an informed public whose electoral judgment is the 
most effective check on the abuse of power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Make attorneys general establish rules for special counsels,  
guaranteeing their independence, making clear the scope of 
investigations and restricting the ability of attorneys general or 
presidents to remove them. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Make regulations that strike a balance between special  
prosecutors' independence from political pressures and their 
accountability. They suggested giving special prosecutors periodic 
deadlines -- perhaps after the first two years of a probe and then 
once a year after that -- when an attorney general will decide 
whether to continue an investigation or bring it to an end. Starr's 
inquiry has stretched over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the decision is to end an investigation, the reasons should  
be reported to Congress, so that the attorney general is publicly 
accountable for that critical decision,'' they wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 10:32:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Arrest Made in Picasso Slashing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch police questioned a mental  
patient today after he escaped from a psychiatric clinic, hopped a 
train to Amsterdam and severely slashed a famous Picasso painting 
in one of the capital's most prestigious art museums. 
</P>
<P>
