<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Strike at Navy Shipbuilder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) -- Hundreds of craftsmen refused Monday to  
cross machinists union pickets at Ingalls Shipbuilding in a dispute 
over the frequency of pay raises and bonuses at Mississippi's 
largest private employer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls had no immediate comment on the strike's impact on  
production. Company spokesman Den Knecht said, however, that the 
11,500-employee shipyard would continue to operate regular shifts. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Machinists at Ingalls set up  
pickets Sunday morning when a 39-month contract with the shipyard 
expired. The pickets were up when the first shift reported Monday 
morning and most workers turned their cars around at the gates and 
headed home. 
</P>
<P>
	All but two of the 13 unions representing 8,000 Ingalls  
employees rejected the shipyard's latest contract proposal over the 
weekend, but only Local 1133 of the Machinists union voted to 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metal Trades Council, which represents nine of the 11 unions  
that rejected the proposal, had offered to continue working on a 
day-to-day basis until a contract is worked out. But council 
leaders admitted that most workers were not expected to cross the 
picket lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls, a builder of Navy destroyers, is a division of Litton  
Industries, which controls a number of aerospace, defense and 
electronics businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Campbell, an analyst with Lehman Brothers in New York,  
said the strike was not likely to have a big impact on Litton 
earnings in the short-term ``just because you're talking about a 
part of a part of a company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``However, we would have to revisit this if the striking union  
stays out a long time and if large portions of the non-striking 
unions'' continue to honor picket lines, Campbell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Litton dropped 12 1/2 cents to $62.75 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Machinist Clyde Stevens, who picketed outside Ingalls until  
midnight Sunday, said, ``It's going pretty good. I haven't seen 
anybody in crafts cross the line yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Burnett, who also walked the picket line, said machinists  
union members were prepared to maintain their protest around the 
clock until the strike issues are resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the machinists local, also rejecting the proposal  
were Pascagoula Metal Trades Council AFL-CIO, which represents nine 
unions and about 6,500 workers, and International Brotherhood of 
Electrical Workers Local 733, representing 1,200 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	While those unions have agreed to continue working under the  
present contract on a day-by-day basis, union members were told to 
honor a sanctioned strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're so far behind in pay and cost of living,'' Stevens said,  
``we have to get the company's attention.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
