<DOCNO> APW19990517.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 14:01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aussie Accused of Selling Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former Australian intelligence official was  
paid $120,000 for nearly 1,000 secret U.S. defense documents by 
undercover FBI agents who posed as foreign spies, lured him to 
Virginia and arrested him, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean-Philippe Wispelaere, 28, was charged with attempted  
espionage and ordered held without bond during an initial 
appearance Monday before U.S. Magistrate Judge Theresa Buchanan in 
suburban Alexandria, Va. FBI agents arrested him last Saturday at 
Dulles International Airport outside Washington when he arrived 
from London for what he believed was another meeting with foreign 
spies. 
</P>
<P>
	An Australian citizen born in Montreal, Wispelaere worked for  
Australian intelligence from July 13, 1998, until his abrupt 
resignation Jan. 12, 1999, government court papers said. Australian 
Attorney General Daryl Williams confirmed this and announced an 
Australian inquiry into the case. 
</P>
<P>
	As an Australian intelligence officer, Wispelaere was cleared to  
work with U.S. top-secret and sensitive compartmented information, 
which has limited distribution, the government said. Such 
classified material was shared with Australia under U.S.-Australian 
defense treaties and could cause ``exceptionally grave damage'' to 
U.S. national security if disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The globe-girdling case began last January in Bangkok, Thailand.  
Since then, Wispelaere allegedly sold 713 classified U.S. defense 
documents to an undercover FBI man in Bangkok for $70,000 and 
mailed more than 200 others to a post office box the FBI set up in 
Virginia for an additional $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the documents involved a foreign country, the government  
said. Some of the documents were photographs, according to an FBI 
affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	Unmarried, Wispelaere got a master's degree in strategic defense  
studies in 1998 from the Australian National University. The FBI 
said he holds Australian, Canadian and French passports and 
complained to undercover agents of ``very dire, dire financial 
need'' for a knee operation and ``a (sigh) couple of other 
concerns, involving females, unfortunately, (laugh) as is always 
the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although his last known address was in Australia, he flew to the  
Bangkok meeting from Seoul, Korea. Wispelaere gave several aliases 
and one Canadian address that the FBI said were false. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, he also claimed to be working for the Canadian  
government in Seoul and receiving training in Cheltenham, England, 
the location of Britain's Government Communications Headquarters, a 
top-secret electronic intelligence-gathering agency similar to the 
U.S. National Security Agency. U.S. officials said he was lying 
about working for Canada and in Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 18, just six days after his unexpected resignation in  
Australia, Wispelaere walked into the embassy of a foreign country, 
which U.S. officials would not name, in Bangkok and offered to sell 
classified U.S. documents to that country for $500,000 in U.S. 
dollars, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	That country involved alerted U.S. officials to the offer and  
turned over a Nov. 24, 1998, secret U.S. document about a foreign 
country that Wispelaere provided as a sample of what he was 
offering, according to U.S. officials, who requested anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	In an affidavit, FBI agent John S. Adams laid out the following  
allegations against Wispelaere: 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI had an undercover counterintelligence agent pose as a  
spy for the foreign country and contact Wispelaere through an 
e-mail address at Hotmail.com that he had left with the embassy in 
Bangkok. 
</P>
<P>
	By e-mail, Wispelaere offered information like the sample and  
variations ``used only under specific environmental circumstances'' 
and requiring ``specialized technical training to be exploited.'' 
He also offered ``hard copy reports based on the other three 
types,'' which may have been photographs because he worried about 
carrying around photos stamped ``secret.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On April 3, while carrying a magazine as instructed, Wispelaere  
met the man he believed to be a spy in Bangkok's Le Meridien 
President Hotel. As FBI videocameras secretly recorded the scene 
over two days, Wispelaere turned over 713 classified U.S. documents 
in exchange for $70,000. The secret and top-secret U.S. defense 
documents were dated 1991 through 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 8, Wispelaere mailed to the undercover FBI agent at a  
post office box in Ashburn, Va., more than 200 secret and 
top-secret U.S. documents in exchange for $50,000 wired to a bank 
account in France. 
</P>
<P>
	In court, Wispelaere requested a lawyer be appointed to  
represent him at a detention hearing set for Thursday. He could 
face life in prison, or the death penalty if his case meets certain 
legal requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
