<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Infant Receives Cow Valve in Heart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The first person in the United States to  
have valve from a cow's neck transplanted into his heart is a 
13-month-old boy who was born with only one heart valve instead of 
two. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was our best shot and it's doing its job and it's doing  
it well right now,'' said Chris Doty, 31, father of little Ryan 
Doty. 
</P>
<P>
	While the transplant has not been approved in the United States,  
the Food and Drug Administration permitted it as a ``compassionate 
case'' due to the boy's deteriorating condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan was in fair condition Monday at Riley Hospital for  
Children, where cardiothorasic surgeon Dr. John Brown performed the 
surgery May 4. 
</P>
<P>
	With only one heart valve, Ryan's heart was unable to pump  
enough blood. He had received a heart-valve transplant at three 
months from an infant who had died, but that valve weakened and 
developed leaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was extremely ill and really wasn't expected to live. This  
was the only thing that could save his life,'' said Brown, director 
of heart transplantation surgery at the Indiana University Medical 
Center, which includes the children's hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said there is always an acute shortage of donor infant  
valves, which tend to fail in transplant procedures. And pig valves 
used for transplant in adult hearts are too large for infants, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brown said a valve from a cow's neck ``is perfect'' for  
transplanting into an infant's heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, who also suffers from hydrocephalus, or fluid on the  
brain, wasn't a candidate for a heart transplant because he had 
received so many blood transfusions during earlier surgeries and 
illnesses, said his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown has been working on bovine neck valves for years,  
transplanting them into dogs. His work led to the transplant being 
approved last year in Europe for use in infants. So far, 13 success 
transplants have been performed overseas, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has all the qualities and properties that heart surgeons  
have been looking for a long time,'' Brown said. ``It's strong, 
it's the right size, it has all the surrounding tissue you need to 
make the hookup to the heart, and it's less likely to have 
complications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The valve is treated with chemicals so that the human body won't  
reject it. Brown expects the FDA to approve the procedure in the 
United States by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan will outgrow the small valve. When they happens, he can  
undergo surgery again to receive a pig's valve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
