<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Globe Libel Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today left intact a  
million-dollar libel award against the tabloid newspaper Globe for 
repeating a book's claim that a California man, not Sirhan Sirhan, 
killed Robert F. Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling by  
California's highest court that the news media can be liable for 
repeating someone else's libelous statement about a private figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's action, while not a precedent-setting decision, is a  
$1.175 million victory for Khalid Khawar, a Bakersfield farmer. He 
was covering Kennedy's presidential campaign for a publication in 
his native Pakistan when the senator from New York was murdered in 
a Los Angeles hotel in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	Globe lawyers had argued that the state court's ruling  
``seriously threatens the right of the media to accurately report 
previously published allegations of public concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 1989 Globe article reported uncritically about a book in which  
conspiracy theorist Robert Morrow said Kennedy's murder had been 
plotted by the Iranian secret police and organized crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The book included a photo of Khawar with Kennedy at the hotel,  
and said the man pictured was Pakistani assassin Ali Ahmand. The 
tabloid article included the photo with a circle and arrow pointing 
out Khawar. 
</P>
<P>
	Khawar was not named in the article. But he said his photograph  
was recognized, and that he and his children later received death 
threats and that his house and son's car were vandalized. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury awarded Khawar $675,000 in compensatory damages for the  
tabloid's negligence and $500,000 in punitive damages for its 
``actual malice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the jury's verdict was reviewed by the state Supreme Court,  
a coalition of major news organizations including The Associated 
Press argued in support of the tabloid and contended that a 
``neutral reportage'' privilege is essential for coverage of public 
controversies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the state court ruled that Globe reporters and editors had  
``obvious reasons to doubt the accuracy'' of the book's claim. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were, to say the least, obvious reasons to doubt. ...  
The Morrow book was making the highly improbable claim that results 
of the official investigation, Sirhan's trial and this court's 
decision on Sirhan's appeal were all fundamentally mistaken,'' the 
state court said in upholding the jury verdict by a 7-0 vote last 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republication of accusations made against private figures are  
never protected by the neutral reportage privilege,'' the 
California court added. It stopped short of recognizing such a 
privilege when public officials and public figures are involved. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Globe lawyers said, ``When The  
Washington Post initially reported the Watergate allegations 
detailing the president's involvement with petty criminals, those 
allegations may have seemed `highly improbable' to many. Yet, those 
allegations were re-reported by virtually every news organization 
in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the California Supreme Court's rule, each of those news  
organizations would now face the risk of being found to have acted 
with `actual malice' for failing to investigate the ... allegations 
themselves before reporting on those allegations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Khawar's lawyer also urged the justices to take the case, to let  
courts nationwide know that the California court struck ``the 
proper balancing of First Amendment and personal reputational 
values.'' He said the court should do away with the ``neutral 
reportage theory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Globe International vs. Khawar, 98-1491.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 14:01:43 </DATE_TIME>
