<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard 2Q Profits Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. beat Wall Street  
expectations with a 34 percent increase in second-quarter profits, 
fueled by sales of personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The big maker of computers, printers and high-tech accessories  
said Monday it earned $918 million, or 88 cents a share, for the 
three months ended April 30. It earned $685 million, or 65 cents a 
share in the same period of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 3 percent to $12.4 billion from $12 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected the Palo  
Alto-based Hewlett-Packard to earn 80 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had solid net earnings in PCs, strong profit performance in  
printing and imaging, and significant profit improvement in our 
measurement business,'' said Hewlett-Packard chairman Lewis E. 
Platt. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Hewlett-Packard split into two separate ventures in an  
effort to revitalize some of its underperforming divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The split formed one company with the computer and imaging  
businesses, and second, much smaller company including testing and 
measuring, components, chemical analysis and medical components. 
</P>
<P>
	Platt said the results are especially notable because ``they  
show we can remain focused even as we make progress on our plan to 
divide HP into two companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the six months ended April 30, HP's net earnings increased  
16 percent to $1.9 billion, compared with $1.6 billion in the first 
half of fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Results were released after financial markets had closed. In  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares rose $3.81 1/4 to $88. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
