<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Honor Ingalls Picket Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) -- Hundreds of workers refused today to  
cross picket lines set up by a machinists union outside Ingalls 
Shipbuilding, Mississippi's largest private employer. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate word from Ingalls, a major shipbuilder  
for the Navy, on exactly how many of its 11,500 workers were 
honoring the pickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The picket lines first went up outside the two main entrances to  
the shipyard on Sunday morning after the union and the company 
could not resolve a dispute over the frequency of pay raises and 
bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Management employees were jeered by strikers as they entered the  
shipyard after 7 a.m. today, while workers who turned around in 
support of the union were cheered. 
</P>
<P>
	While only Machinists Local 1133 voted to strike, 11 of the 13  
unions representing 8,000 Ingalls employees rejected the shipyard's 
latest contract proposal in weekend votes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metal Trades Council, which represents nine of the 11 unions  
that rejected the contract, has offered to continue working on a 
day-to-day basis until a contract is worked out. But council 
leaders say they doubt their workers will cross the Machinists' 
picket lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was here last night until midnight and we didn't have any  
problems,'' striking machinist Clyde Stevens said today. ``It's 
going pretty good. I haven't seen anybody in crafts cross the line 
yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls management has asked workers to return to their jobs  
until federal mediators and national union leaders work out a 
better solution. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls is committed to achieving new labor agreements without a  
work disruption, said Den Knecht, vice president of public and 
industrial relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Kelly, Machinists business agent, said the workers want  
annual salary raises and more bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the last 12 years, the unions have gotten only seven raises  
and five bonuses,'' Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some union members contend Ingalls' proposed contract would have  
offset pay raises by hiking monthly insurance premiums, so they 
rejected it. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, picketing by the Machinists union shut down Ingalls for  
two days because other union members honored the lines. It was the 
first strike at the shipyards in 22 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
