<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hoechst, Rhone-Poulenc Set Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Germany's Hoechst AG and France's  
Rhone-Poulenc SA on Monday set November as a deadline for 
completing their merger into a new drugs and agricultural chemicals 
giant to be called Aventis. 
</P>
<P>
	The share-swap, to begin in October, will give Hoechst 53  
percent of the new company and Rhone-Poulenc the rest, the two 
companies said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The all-stock deal will result in one of the world's largest  
``life sciences'' companies, with annual sales of around $20 
billion. Based in Strassbourg, France, Aventis will be publicly 
traded in Paris, Frankfurt and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies expect the merger to be closed in November,  
provided the shareholders of the two groups approve it, the 
statement said. A 90 percent acceptance rate will be needed for the 
merger to succeed, the two companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before November, Hoechst plans to spin off its industrial  
chemical operations into Celanese AG by offering Hoechst 
shareholders one Celanese share for 10 Hoechst shares held. 
</P>
<P>
	The two groups said they plan to submit the merger plan to  
extraordinary shareholder meetings in mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoechst shareholders will meet again in October at an annual  
general meeting to vote on the payment of a special dividend, the 
companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoechst Chairman Juergen Dormann will head the new company,  
while Rhone-Poulenc Chairman Jean-Rene Fourtou will be his deputy. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger initially was planned to take several years, but it  
was accelerated at the urging of Kuwait Petroleum Corp., Hoechst's 
largest shareholder with a 24.5 percent stake. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
