<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 13:12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Grown With Less Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists are having success with new  
rice-planting methods, some based on ancient practices, that use 
much less fresh water -- a rapidly dwindling resource. 
</P>
<P>
	Desperately looking for ways to increase rice production to feed  
growing Third World populations, researchers say saving water will 
be a key challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Asia, 80 percent of fresh water goes to agriculture. With  
increasing urbanization, that just won't be available in the 
future,'' said Robert Cantrell of the International Rice Research 
Institute. Asia produces about 90 percent of the world's rice. 
</P>
<P>
	The new methods are being developed by farmers with the help of  
scientists from the United Nation's Consultative Group on 
International Agricultural Research, which has laboratories 
throughout the world. CGIAR will report on its new findings in 
Beijing next week during a meeting on pressing food security, 
poverty reduction and environmental protection challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	The methods include wet-seeding, intermittent irrigation, land  
leveling, improved weed management and techniques to cultivate 
cracked soils. 
</P>
<P>
	Cantrell, interviewed by telephone from his office in Makati  
City, Philippines, said water-saving techniques will not approach 
the impact of the ``rice revolution'' of the 1960s that in six 
years saw widespread adoption of new, strong varieties of 
high-yielding rice across Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	He said hybrid varieties, however, are still being developed and  
have allowed rice farmers to keep up with world demand. The 
water-saving methods pose new hope for feeding the world into the 
next century. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice production must increase 40 percent in the next three  
decades to meet the needs of Asia's poor, said Ismael Serageldin, 
CGIAR chairman and World Bank vice president for special programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the projected growth of Asian cities and industries and  
their increased need for fresh water, rice farming must become more 
water efficient,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Current methods that involve growing rice under water take twice  
as much water to produce rice than any other cereal crop, 
Serageldin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, rice plants are transplanted as seedlings into  
flooded fields. With wet-seeding, presoaked seeds are sown directly 
into muddied fields, using up to 25 percent less water. 
</P>
<P>
	Cantrell said the method now being tried out in Thailand,  
Vietnam and the Philippines was used by ancient tribes in the 
region, but nearly all rice farming now is done by flooding fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other new rice-growing methods being developed by farmers  
and scientists: 
</P>
<P>
	--In China, irrigation is being used to flood fields only after  
they have been allowed to nearly dry out, repeating the process 
through the growing period. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Cambodia, many rice paddies are in fields at different  
levels, with upper levels requiring more water. By leveling fields 
to one flat surface, less water is needed. Initials costs for this 
method, however, can be high. 
</P>
<P>
	--When fields are not flooded, weed management becomes a problem,  
and several methods are being developed to fight weeds, including 
weed-resistant rice strains, mechanical devices and chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	--Finally, methods are being developed to crumble soil that has  
developed cracks that suck up water without first letting it soak 
into the soil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
