<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carmakers Brace for Haulers Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Drivers who haul vehicles from auto assembly  
plants to dealers have taken a strike vote. 
</P>
<P>
	A walkout by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, which  
represents about 12,200 drivers and related workers, could quickly 
curtail U.S. new vehicle production and possibly dampen what 
promises to be a record sales year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone would have a problem,'' Ford Motor Co. president Jac  
Nasser said today. Nasser said his company was keeping in close 
contact with the Teamsters and the car haulers. 
</P>
<P>
	Votes on whether to authorize a strike were held last week and  
results were expected later today. The current contract with 
trucking companies that haul the vehicles expires May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The union wants enhanced job security, higher wages and better  
retirement benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	With 1999 car and truck sales already up 8.9 percent through  
April, and the traditionally strong summer selling season still 
ahead, a prolonged strike could be a devastating setback. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way we could get cars or trucks out of the  
plants,'' said Lou Stanford, owner of Varsity Ford in Ann Arbor and 
Varsity Lincoln Mercury in Novi. ``The last time it happened, we 
sat and sucked our thumbs until we could get cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., DaimlerChrysler AG and  
other automakers already are preparing alternative plans in case of 
a walkout by workers who deliver vehicles to showrooms and used-car 
auctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may ask our dealers to use their own trucks and drivers in  
case of a strike,'' DaimlerChrysler spokesman Dan Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations are the first big test at the bargaining table  
for new Teamsters chief James P. Hoffa, who assumed control of the 
union and its 1.4 million members last month. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, the union has struck just one car hauler.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the union waged a 32-day strike against Ryder System  
Inc.'s auto transport subsidiary, idling 500,000 cars and trucks at 
assembly plants, depots and ports. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied Holdings Inc. bought Ryder's car-hauling unit in 1997 and  
now controls about two-thirds of the U.S. market. It operates about 
5,200 car- and truck-hauling rigs from 120 terminals in the United 
States and Canada. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
