<HEADLINE> NBC Adds Five Dramas, Two Comedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Coming to NBC this fall, dramas about rescue  
workers, a White House with Martin Sheen as president and high 
school students circa 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	The network is bringing in a total of five new dramas and two  
new comedies, and will cancel ``Caroline in the City,'' ``Homicide: 
Life on the Street'' and ``NewsRadio.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All seven broadcast networks are presenting next September's  
schedules to advertisers this week. NBC, as the defending ratings 
champ, was up first. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC executives said they were making relatively few changes to  
minimize confusion for viewers. Some shows thought to be 
questionable for the fall schedule -- ``Jesse'' and ``Veronica's 
Closet'' -- were renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This may be the most stable schedule you'll see at a network  
in years,'' said Garth Ancier, new NBC entertainment president. 
</P>
<P>
	``ER'' creator John Wells, who failed last fall with his  
``Trinity'' drama, is getting two new chances in September. He's 
behind ``The West Wing,'' a political drama with Sheen and Rob Lowe 
as a White House staffer. Wells is co-executive producer with Aaron 
Sorkin, creator of ``Sports Night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells also created the new Sunday night drama, ``Third Watch,''  
which NBC West Coast President Scott Sassa called ``the best series 
we have.'' Reminiscent of ``ER'' and featuring some of the same 
actors, it's about rescue workers in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC is spinning off its popular ``Law &AMP; Order'' series with a  
Monday night drama focusing on particularly heinous crimes. ``Law &AMP; 
Order: Special Victims Unit'' will prominently use many of the 
actors from the original series. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC executives played hardball with its rivals at its Monday  
presentation, showing advertisers a filmed skit depicting the 
typical Fox viewer as a long-haired man who crushed beer cans on 
his head, and a CBS viewer as a clueless elderly lady. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are NBC's other new shows:  
</P>
<P>
	--''Cold Feet,'' a Friday night drama/comedy about three couples  
in various stages of relationships. NBC wanted to replace 
``Homicide'' with a show that would appeal more to women. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Freaks and Geeks,'' an hour-long show about two teen-aged  
siblings, set in a suburban high school. 
</P>
<P>
	--''The Mike O'Malley Show,'' a comedy starring the actor as a  
30-year-old bachelor who realizes that his partying days are about 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Stark Raving Mad,'' a comedy about a horror writer and his  
editor. It also won NBC's version of the lottery -- placement on its 
top-rated Thursday schedule between ``Frasier'' and ``ER.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
