<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Could Grow in Popularity / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HASTINGS, Neb. (AP) -- Nebraska is known as the Cornhusker State,  
but crop experts say wheat could grow in popularity among farmers 
as new, consumer-friendly varieties like white wheat are developed. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Agricultural  
Research Service announced the development of Nebraska's first hard 
white winter wheat, called Nuplains. 
</P>
<P>
	Six acres near Sidney are sown to Nuplains this year. The  
harvested seed wheat is to be available to certified seed growers 
this fall and to farmers by planting time in fall 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Graybosch, University of Nebraska-Lincoln Ag Research  
Service research geneticist, said the new winter wheat has 
potential for use in the growing market for tortillas, pita breads 
and Asian noodles. 
</P>
<P>
	``White wheats are being developed because customers want  
them,'' Graybosch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska produced 84.6 million bushels of wheat, half of which  
were exported, in 1998. Asia imports 400 million bushels of white 
wheat annually from Australia and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska wheat promoters hope to tap the growing Asian market.  
</P>
<P>
	Nuplains is a cross between Abilene, a hard red winter wheat and  
a Kansas experimental hard wheat. It allows Nebraska to join other 
states with white wheat programs, Graybosch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Few premiums exist now, but someday monetary incentives may be  
available for producers to grow nothing but white wheat, he said. 
Graybosch said yields are competitive, and white wheat is ``an 
option'' for Nebraska growers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Domestic millers will already take all they can get,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Millers like white-wheat flour because of the taste, Graybosch  
said. Red wheat contains tannins, which make it red and also give 
it a bitter flavor. 
</P>
<P>
	White wheat is sweeter, Graybosch said, meaning processors can  
mill closer to the hull and add less sugar. 
</P>
<P>
	While the difference between red and white wheat is in the  
genes, Graybosch stressed that white wheat is not a genetically 
modified grain. 
</P>
<P>
	``This white wheat occurs naturally,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Australia was first to develop white wheat varieties, and now  
enjoys strong trade with the Asian noodle market, Graybosch said. 
There are some disadvantages to growing white wheat, however, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	For one, white wheat is more susceptible than red wheat to  
pre-harvest sprouting in the heads. White wheat is geared toward 
relatively dry climates where the grain will be dry at harvest, 
Graybosch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daryl Strouts, executive director of the Kansas Crop Improvement  
Association in Manhattan, Kan., said Kansas universities have been 
working with white wheats since the mid-1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas released white wheat to seed growers for the first time  
in fall 1998. Kansas offers two varieties of certified white wheat. 
The varieties, Betty and Heyne, are named after their founders. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine producers have the seed growing on their farms. Most of the  
acreage is irrigated, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strouts said white varieties also will produce flour higher in  
protein because millers can mill closer to the bran, where the 
highest protein concentrations exist. 
</P>
<P>
	Millers also can extract 2 percent to 3 percent more flour from  
each white kernel than a red kernel, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
