<HEADLINE> NBC Adds Five Dramas, Two Comedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is adding five dramas to its prime-time  
schedule next fall, including a ``Law &AMP; Order'' spinoff, a look at 
the inner workings of the White House that stars Rob Lowe, and a 
show set in a suburban high school around 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	The network will also premiere two new comedies and cancel  
``Caroline in the City,'' ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' and 
``NewsRadio.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The seven broadcast networks all present next September's  
schedules to advertisers this week. NBC, the ratings champ for the 
last three years and locked in a battle for first place with CBS 
this year, is the first to pull the trigger. 
</P>
<P>
	A new comedy about a book editor, ``Stark Raving Mad,'' is given  
a coveted time slot on Thursday night, NBC's most popular night. It 
takes over for ``Veronica's Closet,'' which moves to Mondays. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's other new comedy, ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' is about a  
30-year-old man who realizes his partying days are over. 
</P>
<P>
	``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' will air on Monday nights.  
It's a police drama set in New York City and focusing on 
particularly heinous crimes. ``Law &AMP; Order'' remains on Wednesday 
nights. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wells, the creator of ``ER,'' is also behind two of the new  
dramas. ``West Wing'' is the White House drama, set for Wednesday 
nights, and he's also producing ``Third Watch,'' about paramedics, 
firefighters and police. 
</P>
<P>
	``Freaks and Geeks,'' about high school life circa 1980, is  
reminiscent of the teen-age dramas popular on the WB. That 
network's former entertainment chief, Garth Ancier, took over this 
month as NBC's entertainment president. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's fifth new drama, ``Cold Feet,'' is about three young  
couples in relationships with various levels of commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	One staple remains on NBC's schedule: hour-long installments of  
``Dateline NBC'' five nights a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
