<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Tries To Qualify for Indy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The luck of the draw, and maybe some  
favorable weather, might determine when and how well Tony Stewart 
qualifies for the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Indy Racing League champion already knows he won't  
have much time to practice, thanks to his Winston Cup commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest challenge will be the weather,'' said Stewart, who  
needs an early draw in the qualifying order on Saturday to have a 
chance for the pole position in the May 30 race. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing that's going to hurt us right now is a lack  
of track time, and if we wash out two or three days this week then 
that's what's going to hurt us the hardest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Practice was halted more than two hours early Monday because of  
rain. More rain was forecast for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who formed the Tri Star Motor Sports team to race at  
Indianapolis, already missed the opening day of practice on 
Saturday to compete in NASCAR's Pontiac Excitement 400 in Richmond, 
Va. He arrived in Indianapolis early Sunday, with little sleep, and 
took only a few shakedown laps in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite not driving an Indy car since October, Stewart quickly  
got up to speed, turning a lap of 222.091 mph, the seventh best in 
Sunday's practice. On Monday, he managed only six more laps, with a 
top speed of 219.700, before the rain hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray, who took Stewart's place with Team Menard, was the  
fastest for the third day in a row, turning a top lap of 224.843. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other fast drivers were rookie John Hollansworth Jr. at  
221.669, defending IRL champion Kenny Brack at 221.272 and two-time 
Indy winner Arie Luyendyk at 221.119. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Mike Borkowski and veterans Scott Harrington and Billy  
Boat hit walls in separate crashes, but none of them was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifications begin 11 a.m. Saturday. To race that night in The  
Winston at Concord, N.C., Stewart figures he needs to leave 
Indianapolis by 1:30 p.m., which means his position in the 
qualifying line is crucial. The order will be drawn Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't feel pressure,'' Stewart said of having  
possibly only one chance to get into the race. ``I think I'm going 
to have a good enough car underneath me that we're not going to 
have to worry about that. I think we can get in the show pretty 
solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The question, though, is which day.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have to be true to the Winston Cup guys,'' he said.  
``They've been good enough to give me this opportunity to come 
here, and the last thing I want to do is be late down there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That means if he doesn't qualify in the first 2 1/2 hours on  
Saturday, he will have to wait until Sunday, with no shot at the 
pole or any other spot high in the 33-car lineup. After the race, 
he will leave immediately again to drive in the Coca-Cola 600 at 
Concord that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, Stewart became the first driver to win U.S. Auto  
Club national championships in the sprint, midget and Silver Crown 
divisions in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, he made his debut in the Indianapolis 500,  
started from the pole after teammate Scott Brayton was killed in 
practice, led 44 laps and was rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, he started second, finished fifth and went on to  
capture the IRL series title. Last year, he started fourth at Indy 
but was first out after engine problems on the 23rd lap. 
</P>
<P>
	He left Team Menard at the end the season to drive full time for  
Joe Gibbs Racing, where he is the top rookie driver in NASCAR and 
seventh overall after finishing 15th Saturday at Richmond. But Indy 
has always been on his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being a young race car driver from Indiana, I'd be stupid if I  
said this wasn't the single most important race to me,'' said 
Stewart, who comes from nearby Columbus, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of races that are important to me that I still  
want to try to win, but if I could guarantee I was only going to 
win one of them, this would be the one I'd pick. It's the most 
important race of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After qualifications on Saturday and Sunday, the track will be  
closed until the final practice the following Thursday, known as 
Carburetion Day. After that, the next time the cars come on the 
track will be race day. 


</P>
</TEXT>
