<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spelling To Complete Sale To Viacom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Viacom Inc. is paying $181 million in cash to  
buy the 20 percent of television producer Spelling Entertainment 
Group Inc. it doesn't already own. 
</P>
<P>
	Viacom will pay $9.75 for each share of Spelling, giving it full  
control of the production company whose hits include ``Melrose 
Place,'' ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Judge Judy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Viacom, which inherited its stake in Spelling from its 1994  
acquisition of the Blockbuster video chain, has been trying for 
some time to buy the rest of the company. Viacom had offered to pay 
$9 per share for the rest of Spelling two months ago but had to 
sweeten the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors, concerned that the substantial cash payment could  
hurt Viacom, pushed the company's stock lower Monday. Viacom's 
shares fell $1.62 1/2 or 4 percent to $37.56 1/4 in afternoon trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Spelling's shares rose on news of the rich offer, gaining 75  
cents, or 8.5 percent, to $9.62 1/2. Both stocks trade on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Viacom also owns MTV, VH1, Nickelodeon, the Paramount movie  
studio, half of the UPN network and part of the Simon &AMP; Schuster 
publishing house. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
