<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Barak Unseats Netanyahu in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Ehud Barak, a peace process moderate, unseated  
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in elections today. Netanyahu 
conceded defeat in an emotional farewell after exit polls projected 
a sweeping victory for Barak. TV's Channel One had Barak ahead by 
58.5 percent to 41.5 percent for Netanyahu, while Channel Two gave 
the opposition chief a lead of 57 percent to 43 percent for 
Netanyahu. A Barak victory would likely jumpstart Israel's stalled 
negotiations with the Palestinians that were frozen during most of 
Netanyahu's three-year rule. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Urges Israeli Pullback  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Israelis elected Ehud Barak their new prime  
minister today, the Clinton administration renewed its call for an 
Israeli pullback on the West Bank and immediate and rapid talks 
with the Palestinians on Jerusalem and statehood. After a long and 
frustrating stalemate, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also 
set as a U.S. goal peace talks on ``an invigorated track'' between 
Israel and Syria and Lebanon. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Peace Efforts Increase  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Bad weather forced the cancellation  
of most NATO flights over Kosovo today as diplomatic efforts to 
solve the nearly 2-month-old conflict moved into higher gear. A 
U.N. delegation was in Belgrade today, preparing to make the first 
trip to Kosovo by international authorities since some 790,000 
ethnic Albanians were driven out of the southern Serb province 
beginning March 24, when NATO launched airstrikes against 
Yugoslavia. In what U.N. officials and NATO said was a worrying 
development, Serb forces today barred hundreds of ethnic Albanians 
who arrived at the Macedonian border from leaving Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Trie Tried on Obstruction Charge  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie, a longtime  
friend of President Clinton accused of funneling illegal 
contributions to Democrats, went on trial today on an obstruction 
charge. Trie is accused of obstructing justice by ordering an 
employee to destroy documents subpoenaed in 1997 by a federal grand 
jury and by a Senate committee. Trie could spend time in a federal 
prison if convicted and faces even stiffer penalties if convicted 
of charges in Washington that he made and arranged illegal 
contributions from foreigners to the Democratic National Committee. 

</P>
<P>
	Court To Decide on Auto Records Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a big-bucks battle over privacy, the  
Supreme Court agreed today to decide whether states can sell 
personal information from driver's license records such as people's 
addresses and Social Security numbers. The Clinton administration 
wants the justices to uphold a federal law that closes state motor 
vehicle records to the public. States have routinely sold such 
information to businesses, charities and political candidates, 
earning millions of dollars in revenue each year. When the law was 
enacted, 34 states made motor vehicle records public in some form. 

</P>
<P>
	Ruling Allows Cops To Seize Cars  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police do not need a warrant to seize  
someone's car from a public place under laws requiring forfeiture 
of property linked to crime, the Supreme Court said today. The 7-2 
ruling reinstated a Florida man's drug conviction based on the 
crack cocaine police found in his car after seizing it without a 
warrant. Police said the man's car was subject to forfeiture 
because it had been used to deliver drugs several months earlier. 
The case involves seizures made under a Florida law that allows 
forfeiture of property used in committing drug crimes. 

</P>
<P>
	US Increases Food Aid to N.Korea  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States announced today a  
400,000-ton food aid donation for North Korea as American 
inspectors flew there to determine whether the government is 
abiding by a promise not to develop nuclear weapons. Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright said the U.S. food commitment responded to 
an April appeal by the U.N. World Food Program. The pledge 
increased to 600,000 tons the U.S. food aid pledge to North Korea 
for the year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 59.28  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 59.28 at 10,854.04. NYSE decliners outnumbered 
advancers 2,034-1,008. The Nasdaq was up 17.58 at 2,545.44. 

</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island's Odom Enters NBA Draft  
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Rhode Island star forward Lamar  
Odom has entered the NBA draft after one collegiate season. The 
6-foot-10 Odom led Rhode Island in scoring (17.6) and rebounding 
(9.4) last season. Unless he hires an agent, Odom can pull out of 
the draft as late as June 23 and return to college. Last year, Odom 
declared for the draft, then pulled out after he was admitted to 
Rhode Island. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
