<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 18:21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roy Has Red Wings Against Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Their names are Arturs Irbe, Martin Brodeur,  
Patrick Roy and Nikolai Khabibulin. Over the past few years, they 
are the goaltenders who have tormented the Detroit Red Wings in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy, in particular, has become almost as familiar to Detroit  
fans as the octopus they like to toss at Joe Louis Arena. If he can 
win again Tuesday night in Game 6, the Colorado Avalanche will have 
eliminated the Red Wings -- dashing their quest for a third 
consecutive Stanley Cup championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy, extending his NHL playoff record for wins to 106, had 36  
saves as the Avalanche beat Detroit 3-0 in Game 5 on Sunday, the 
first time the home team has won in this series. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy has stopped 111 of the last 116 Detroit shots.  
</P>
<P>
	Roy's 12th career playoff shutout tied him with Terry Sawchuk  
for fourth place in NHL history. His last shutout in the postseason 
came in Game 5 against Detroit in the Western Conference finals in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the playoffs, there is adversity,'' Roy said. ``You have to  
find a way to go through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If there has been one thing that can give the Red Wings fits in  
the playoffs, it seems to be a goaltender who can all but stand on 
his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit has been fairly loaded with talent for several years  
now. But in 1994, Irbe was spectacular in goal and the San Jose 
Sharks booted the Red Wings in seven games -- in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Brodeur helped the New Jersey Devils sweep Detroit in the 1995  
finals, and Roy sent the Red Wings packing after six games in the 
1996 semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy and the Avs took the Red Wings to six games in 1997, before  
Detroit went on to sweep Philadelphia in the finals. Khabibulin and 
the Phoenix Coyotes made the Red Wings sweat out a six-game series 
last year, before they swept Washington for their second straight 
Cup title. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, here is Roy again.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's been outstanding,'' said Colorado forward Jeff Odgers,  
who scored his first goal of these playoffs Sunday. ``He's the kind 
of guy that when he makes up his mind that he's going to do 
something, he says, `Listen, boys, this is the way it's going to 
be.' 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing about Patty is he'll say it and he'll lead by  
example. If you don't go out there and give it your all, you're not 
only letting the team down, you're letting him down because he 
gives such a great effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``When your goaltender is playing as well as Patty is, it gives  
everyone else confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been three years since the Red Wings have been on the  
brink of elimination, dating to the 1996 Western Conference finals 
against Colorado. Down 3-1, the Red Wings rallied to win Game 5, 
but the Avs won Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit had advanced that year only because Steve Yzerman had  
managed to score in the second overtime in Game 7 of a second-round 
series against St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say we have been taken out of our game,'' Yzerman  
said. ``They are playing more disciplined than they did in the 
first two games in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roy has been solid in the net and they have gotten timely  
goals from all sorts of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings are attempting to become the first team to win  
three straight Cups since the New York Islanders won four straight 
between 1980-83. 
</P>
<P>
	If they should force a Game 7, it would be Thursday night in  
Colorado. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
