<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Computer Auction Site Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- CNET Inc., an online media company  
specializing in technology news and product information, launched 
an Internet auction service Monday where people can bid for used, 
refurbished and surplus computer products. 
</P>
<P>
	The company recently bought auction company AuctionGate  
Interactive of Irvine, Calif., to handle the bidding, which got a 
jump-start Monday with about 2,000 items offered for sale by 
computer resellers. 
</P>
<P>
	By combining the bidding venue with product information, news  
and reviews from CNET's related Web sites, the company hopes to 
become the preferred destination where technophiles can find 
products from ``the really useful to the completely geeky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CNET's auction venture will compete against eBay, which  
currently offers more than 72,000 items in its computers category, 
and Amazon.com, the online bookseller which also auctions 
technology products, among many other things. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin McKenzie, CNET's associate vice president for shopping  
services, said CNET hopes sellers and buyers will police themselves 
by rating each other on the site. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
