<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 17:51:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoltz Goes on DL With Sore Elbow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- John Smoltz, the best pitcher in Atlanta's  
struggling rotation, was placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday 
with an inflamed right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz (5-1) noticed the soreness during the Braves' 8-5 victory  
over the Chicago Cubs on Sunday. He allowed five runs in six 
innings, the most he has surrendered in 16 starts dating to last 
August, and his ERA climbed to 2.59 -- the first time it's been 
above 2.00 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're pitching good, you want to keep pitching,'' he  
said. ``But as frustrated as I am, I know I'll be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Team doctors drained fluid from Smoltz's elbow before Monday's  
game against the Pittsburgh Pirates. An MRI showed no serious 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	To take Smoltz's place on the roster, Atlanta activated relief  
pitcher Russ Springer. Smoltz's spot in the rotation will be taken 
by left-hander Bruce Chen, who is 3-2 with a 2.40 ERA in seven 
starts and 45 innings at Class Triple-A Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	``John's next start would be Sunday, so that's the only time  
we'd need Chen,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``(Smoltz) will 
miss two starts. In fact, he could make his next start, and if we 
were going down the stretch in September, he could start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz is still suffering the lingering effects of arthroscopic  
surgery in December 1997. He spent the first two weeks of last 
season on the disabled list and went back there for nearly a month 
after his elbow acted up again. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing new or worse in the X-rays and in the  
determining factors that they looked at today,'' Cox said. ``It all 
looks good. It looks the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Returning from his second stint on the DL June 20, he went 13-2  
with a 2.51 ERA in 18 starts. Overall, he led the majors in winning 
percentage with a 17-3 record (.850) to go along with a 2.90 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Smoltz was by far the most effective starter in  
Atlanta's heralded rotation, winning his first five starts and 
lasting no less than six innings in each of his eight starts. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander's injury comes with fellow Cy Young winners Tom  
Glavine (2-4, 4.53 ERA) and Greg Maddux (4-3, 4.83) struggling. 
Maddux has lost his last three starts and leads the NL in hits 
allowed with 79. The league is hitting .356 against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine lost his first four starts and then won three straight  
down before giving up five earned runs and seven his in a 9-0 loss 
at Chicago Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, despite his subpar outing Sunday, has allowed only 40  
hits in 55 2-3 innings, with 52 strikeouts. He seemed on track to 
challenge the best season of his career, a 24-8 performance in 1996 
that landed his lone Cy Young Award. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't really want to go on the disabled list at all,''  
Cox said. ``In fact, he tried to talk me into it this afternoon, 
the second time we talked. I just don't think it's the right thing 
to do. I think the right thing to do is to miss two starts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Chen is called up, the Braves either are likely to send  
rookie reliever Justin Speier to the minors or disable John Hudek, 
who has been ineffective since being acquired April 16 from 
Cincinnati in the Mark Wohlers trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Hudek has a blister on his right middle finger and is 0-1 with  
an 11.17 ERA in 9 2-3 innings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
