<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins Manager Has Back Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins manager John Boles will be away  
from the team 3-10 days after undergoing emergency back surgery 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors at Holy Cross Hospital in Fort Lauderdale worked two  
hours to remove a herniated disk in Boles' back. The 50-year-old 
manager is expected to be walking Tuesday and could be released as 
soon as Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a chance he could be back here managing Thursday,''  
general manager Dave Dombrowski said. ``We'll know more tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Third base coach Fredi Gonzalez was appointed interim manager  
before the Marlins began a seven-game homestand Monday night 
against the Chicago Cubs. The debut was unsuccessful, as Florida 
lost 8-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the way I wanted to manage my first major league  
game,'' said Gonzalez, who managed eight seasons in the Florida 
organization before joining Boles' staff this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bolesy was the guy that gave me my first opportunity,''  
Gonzalez said. ``I wish he was sitting here and saying, `I'll let 
you manage it,' instead of him going under the knife.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pitching coach Rich Dubee will handle the pitching changes  
during Boles' absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles had complained of back pain during Florida's  
just-completed nine-game road trip that ended Sunday in Milwaukee. 
He underwent magnetic resonance image testing Monday and was told 
surgery couldn't wait. 
</P>
<P>
	``John's a tough guy. He didn't say much about it,'' Dombrowski  
said. ``But he said that when he went out to the mound, there were 
a couple of times he didn't think he was going to make it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boles was being prepped for surgery as players gathered at Pro  
Player Stadium. Dombrowski and Gonzalez addressed the team before 
batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them don't change a thing. Score 20,'' Gonzalez said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins (11-27) went 5-4 on the road trip, winning series in  
Los Angeles and Milwaukee. That moved them out of last place in the 
NL East, one game ahead of Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to change anything. The guys know what they  
need to do,'' said pitcher Alex Fernandez, scheduled to come off 
the disabled list himself on Tuesday after missing two weeks with a 
groin injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, 35, had managed the independent Miami Miracle for 1 1/2  
seasons before the Marlins made him their first minor league 
manager in 1992. He took Erie to a second-place finish in the New 
York-Penn League that year. 
</P>
<P>
	He has earned manager of the year honors in the California,  
Florida State and Eastern leagues and guided Sun Cities to the 
Arizona Fall League title this past offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like he's been managing a long time,'' Dombrowski  
said. ``It's a short-term thing, just until Bolesy gets back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
