<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Failed Japan Bank Exec Found Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- An executive of a failed Japanese bank was found  
hanged Monday in his company dormitory room, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent suicide was the second in the last two weeks by  
officials from the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., who 
reportedly faced questioning about an alleged cover-up of bad 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The death follows a series of suicides over the past two years  
by top corporate and government officials linked to scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazunori Fukuda, 51, was found dead in his room by a manager of  
the dormitory in the city of Nishinomiya, a police official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-Term Credit Bank, once one of Japan's top banks, was  
nationalized last year after regulators said it would never be able 
to dig its way out from under a mountain of bad loans. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time the government had taken over a bank since  
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the bad debt was the result of aggressive lending to  
real estate developers before property prices collapsed in the 
early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank executives denied that LTCB was insolvent as the government  
moved to take it over in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Fukuda, most recently the manager of the bank's Osaka branch,  
served until last summer as managing director of the bank's 
real-estate loan division, media reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive faced questioning by prosecutors over the alleged  
falsification of financial records to hide the extent of the bank's 
bad-loan problems, national broadcaster NHK reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A former LTCB vice president, Takashi Uehara, 59, was found  
hanged earlier this month in a Tokyo hotel room. Prosecutors had 
been questioning Uehara about the alleged cover-up, media reports 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, suicide is often seen as a respectable way to avoid  
the disgrace of scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
