<DOCNO> APW19990517.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-17 06:17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Embassy in Beijing Cleans Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- U.S. Marines and Chinese workers shoveled debris  
and scrubbed the U.S. Embassy in Beijing today after protests last 
week left the compound a rock-scarred, paint-spattered picture of 
unleashed rage. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine days after demonstrations erupted over NATO's bombing of  
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, bulletproof glass on the U.S. 
Embassy's main door stood pockmarked and cracked. An air 
conditioning unit, charred and twisted, was dumped by the front 
gate. Rock-shattered windows remained boarded up. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests are over, but China's anger persists. The Communist  
Party's flagship newspaper, the People's Daily, today called NATO's 
war against Yugoslavia and the May 7 bombing of the Chinese Embassy 
``a great step in the United States' strategy to dominate the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Propping up the government's view that the embassy bombing was a  
deliberate test of China's will, the newspaper said the United 
States is determined to ``not allow the emergence of any nation or 
group of nations that can challenge its leading position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since government-sanctioned protests ended  
Wednesday, U.S. diplomats took reporters into the embassy compound 
to inspect the damage and the clean-up. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew-cut marines in civvies hosed down the embassy's  
paint-spattered front entrance, sending inky rivulets into the 
fenced-off forecourt that U.S. officials feared was about to be 
stormed May 9 when protests were at their height. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from lumps of rock, brick and concrete, Molotov cocktails,  
paint bombs and at least one stink bomb, protesters also hurled 
bottles filled with urine and feces, said a U.S. diplomat who was 
trapped inside the embassy during the siege. Protesters used 
slingshots to fire ball-bearings and marbles. 
</P>
<P>
	The government-sanctioned protests brought tens of thousands of  
people to Beijing's normally quiet embassy district in days of wild 
rage seldom seen in tightly controlled China. Numbers dwindled last 
Monday and Tuesday after police controlled access to the area. 
Small groups of protesters returned to hurl rocks at the embassy on 
Wednesday, the diplomat said. 
</P>
<P>
	American students trapped on Chinese campuses by angry  
protesters also phoned the embassy ``pleading for help,'' said the 
diplomat, who spoke on condition that he not be named. ``Campuses 
were getting out of control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Embassy staff went to work Monday, but visa offices were closed  
indefinitely, said embassy spokesman Bill Palmer. His office, in 
another U.S. Embassy building three blocks away from the main 
compound, also was stoned, littering it with broken glass and lumps 
of concrete. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters last week also beset U.S. consulates in four cities,  
setting fire to the consul's residence in Chengdu. The consulates 
in Chengdu and Shenyang set to cleaning up the remains of mob 
violence Monday, while those in Shanghai and Guangzhou resumed most 
operations. None issued student, business or tourist visas. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the embassy's visa section, where windows remained  
broken and the forecourt strewn with debris, hopeful applicants and 
people waiting to collect documents anxiously stood behind a police 
cordon. None said the bombing made them hate Americans or dampened 
their desire to visit the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``These matters don't have anything to do with the people of our  
two countries. The trouble is past, what we need now are more 
channels, more exchanges,'' said a retiree from the northern port 
city of Qingdao who gave his surname, Zhu. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the crowd had traveled to Beijing from surrounding  
provinces to get visas. While some cast doubt on the Chinese 
government's charge that the embassy attack was deliberate, they 
also refrained from condemning the damage wreaked by protesters. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were blowing off steam. How would you have felt if it had  
been your embassy that was bombed?'' asked a Beijing woman surnamed 
Han. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990517.0262 </DOCNO>
